// GAMSAT Section 1 (Reasoning in Humanities and Social Sciences) question bank + taxonomy.
// Tagged on two axes: genre (the four GAMSAT S1 stimulus types) and skill (the reasoning tested).
// All stimuli and questions are original, written to mirror the style/difficulty of real S1; none are copied.
// Question object shape:
//   id            "gs1-prose-0001"
//   genre         prose | poetry | social_behavioural | graphic | testing | calibration | dialectic
//   skill         main_idea | inference | tone | characterisation | figurative_language | vocab_in_context | argument
//   stimulusId    groups questions under one shared stimulus
//   stimulus      { kind:"text"|"image", content, attribution }
//   stem          question text
//   format        single_best
//   options       array of option strings
//   answer        option index
//   explanation   human-authored, shown after answering
//   difficulty    easy | medium | hard
//   source        always "original"

const GAMSAT_S1_GENRES = {
  prose: "Prose fiction",
  poetry: "Poetry",
  social_behavioural: "Social & behavioural",
  graphic: "Graphic & illustration",
  testing: "Testing",
  calibration: "Calibration",
  dialectic: "Dialectic"
};

const GAMSAT_S1_SKILLS = {
  main_idea: "Main idea",
  inference: "Inference",
  tone: "Tone & attitude",
  characterisation: "Characterisation",
  figurative_language: "Figurative language",
  vocab_in_context: "Vocabulary in context",
  argument: "Argument & evidence"
};

const GAMSAT_S1_TAXONOMY = { genres: GAMSAT_S1_GENRES, skills: GAMSAT_S1_SKILLS };

const GAMSAT_S1_DIFFICULTIES = ["easy", "medium", "hard", "very_hard"];

const GAMSAT_S1_QUESTIONS = [
  { id: "gs1-poetry-001", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each dusk he climbs to trim the wick no ship requires,\nthe harbour silted now, the sea-lanes drawn elsewhere;\nand still the great lens turns its patient figures\nacross a bay that keeps no count of who is there.\n\nAsk him, and he says the light is for the lost,\nthough none are lost here now, and none arrive;\nhe brings the brass to a particular gloss\nas if the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive.\n\nWhen he is gone the board will let the tower cool.\nHe knows this. Climbing, he is neither glad nor grieved.\nThe light is, by every ledger, surplus to need,\nand burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central preoccupation is", format: "single_best", options: ["the quiet dignity of a faithful labour done for its own sake, asking no reward","the indifference of the natural world to human persistence","whether keeping a light no one needs is a noble fidelity or a futile self-deception","whether a devotion that serves no purpose is thereby ennobled or merely emptied"], answer: 3, explanation: "D names the question the poem keeps open: whether a devotion that serves no purpose is ennobled or merely emptied. C is the near-twin, also an open question but with the wrong horns (fidelity versus self-deception), where the poem weighs dignity against hollowness, not whether he is fooling himself. A settles for the warm reading the poem refuses; B takes the uncounting bay, a secondary note, for the theme.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-002", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each dusk he climbs to trim the wick no ship requires,\nthe harbour silted now, the sea-lanes drawn elsewhere;\nand still the great lens turns its patient figures\nacross a bay that keeps no count of who is there.\n\nAsk him, and he says the light is for the lost,\nthough none are lost here now, and none arrive;\nhe brings the brass to a particular gloss\nas if the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive.\n\nWhen he is gone the board will let the tower cool.\nHe knows this. Climbing, he is neither glad nor grieved.\nThe light is, by every ledger, surplus to need,\nand burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The final line, 'burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves', is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["a line poised between celebrating gratuitous excess and exposing futility","an ironic exposure of the keeper's belief that his work matters","an affirmation that selfless acts shine most when they expect no return","a lament that his effort has been spent on an empty bay"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'neither glad nor grieved' holds both at once, and A names that balance, the line poised between celebrating gratuitous excess and exposing futility. B collapses it to irony, C to an affirmation of selflessness, and D to a lament, each taking only one horn.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-003", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each dusk he climbs to trim the wick no ship requires,\nthe harbour silted now, the sea-lanes drawn elsewhere;\nand still the great lens turns its patient figures\nacross a bay that keeps no count of who is there.\n\nAsk him, and he says the light is for the lost,\nthough none are lost here now, and none arrive;\nhe brings the brass to a particular gloss\nas if the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive.\n\nWhen he is gone the board will let the tower cool.\nHe knows this. Climbing, he is neither glad nor grieved.\nThe light is, by every ledger, surplus to need,\nand burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In context, the keeper's being 'neither glad nor grieved' is best captured by the single word", format: "single_best", options: ["phlegmatic","anhedonic","stoic","impassive"], answer: 3, explanation: "Impassive names a feeling that simply does not register, matching 'the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive'. Anhedonic is only the absence of pleasure, too narrow for a man who feels no grief either; stoic implies feeling endured or suppressed, though nothing here is being borne; phlegmatic names a calm temperament, a disposition rather than this emptiness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-004", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each dusk he climbs to trim the wick no ship requires,\nthe harbour silted now, the sea-lanes drawn elsewhere;\nand still the great lens turns its patient figures\nacross a bay that keeps no count of who is there.\n\nAsk him, and he says the light is for the lost,\nthough none are lost here now, and none arrive;\nhe brings the brass to a particular gloss\nas if the keeping, not the kept, were the thing alive.\n\nWhen he is gone the board will let the tower cool.\nHe knows this. Climbing, he is neither glad nor grieved.\nThe light is, by every ledger, surplus to need,\nand burns the brighter for the nothing it relieves.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In context, that the light is 'surplus to need' casts the keeper's labour as", format: "single_best", options: ["quixotic","otiose","supererogatory","sisyphean"], answer: 2, explanation: "All four are advanced and plausible. Supererogatory (beyond what need or duty requires) matches 'surplus to need' without prejudging value; otiose (pointless), quixotic (deludedly idealistic) and sisyphean (futile, endless) each import a verdict the poem declines.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-005", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He copied what he could not read for forty years,\neach character a shape to him, and not a sound;\nthe meaning travelled through him to the page\nthe way a wire conducts a charge it never owns.\n\nHe never asked what passed beneath his hand.\nSome called him faithful; others, merely blank.\nThe errors that he did not make were not\nforbearance, but the absence of a stake.\n\nAnd yet the text survives because of him,\nuncomprehended, perfect, handed on:\nthe one unbroken link in its long chain\nwas made of a man who did not understand.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly concerned with", format: "single_best", options: ["the way mechanical labour deadens the soul of the labourer","the idea that the most reliable transmission may be the one least touched by a mind of its own","whether the copyist's faithfulness is a virtue or merely the absence of any temptation to err","the claim that genuine fidelity to a text requires fully understanding it"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: his very non-comprehension is why the chain held, so the most reliable transmission may be the one least touched by a mind of its own. D is the trap, the opposite claim that fidelity requires understanding; C is the near-twin, a real tension but a different one (virtue versus mere absence of temptation), not the transmission point the close presses; A moralises about the labourer beyond the text.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-006", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He copied what he could not read for forty years,\neach character a shape to him, and not a sound;\nthe meaning travelled through him to the page\nthe way a wire conducts a charge it never owns.\n\nHe never asked what passed beneath his hand.\nSome called him faithful; others, merely blank.\nThe errors that he did not make were not\nforbearance, but the absence of a stake.\n\nAnd yet the text survives because of him,\nuncomprehended, perfect, handed on:\nthe one unbroken link in its long chain\nwas made of a man who did not understand.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The simile 'the way a wire conducts a charge it never owns' implies that the copyist", format: "single_best", options: ["carried a meaning through himself without its ever becoming his","was indifferent to the harm his errors might cause","took an active, shaping hand in the meaning he transmitted, leaving on it the impress of his own understanding","resented being used merely as an instrument"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: a wire conducts a charge it never owns, so the copyist carried the meaning through himself without its becoming his. C is the elaborate trap, reversing the simile into active shaping; B and D attribute attitudes (indifference, resentment) a wire cannot hold.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-007", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He copied what he could not read for forty years,\neach character a shape to him, and not a sound;\nthe meaning travelled through him to the page\nthe way a wire conducts a charge it never owns.\n\nHe never asked what passed beneath his hand.\nSome called him faithful; others, merely blank.\nThe errors that he did not make were not\nforbearance, but the absence of a stake.\n\nAnd yet the text survives because of him,\nuncomprehended, perfect, handed on:\nthe one unbroken link in its long chain\nwas made of a man who did not understand.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "Calling his accuracy 'not forbearance, but the absence of a stake' draws the line between", format: "single_best", options: ["caring about accuracy and being careless of it","altering the text on purpose and altering it by mistake","fully understanding the text and, in other places, wholly failing to grasp a word of it","resisting a temptation to alter the text and never feeling that temptation at all"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: forbearance would mean holding back a real urge, whereas 'the absence of a stake' means there was no urge to hold back, exactly the line D draws. C is the elaborate near-miss (understanding versus failing to understand), a different contrast; A and B substitute contrasts the line never makes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-008", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He copied what he could not read for forty years,\neach character a shape to him, and not a sound;\nthe meaning travelled through him to the page\nthe way a wire conducts a charge it never owns.\n\nHe never asked what passed beneath his hand.\nSome called him faithful; others, merely blank.\nThe errors that he did not make were not\nforbearance, but the absence of a stake.\n\nAnd yet the text survives because of him,\nuncomprehended, perfect, handed on:\nthe one unbroken link in its long chain\nwas made of a man who did not understand.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The closing stanza, that the chain's one link 'was made of a man who did not understand', is best read as", format: "single_best", options: ["celebrating his humility as the highest form of service","lamenting that a whole life was poured out, uncomprehending, upon work the man himself could neither understand nor ever bring himself to value","holding his non-understanding as both the guarantee of the text's survival and the emptying of his own part in it","crediting the institution, not the man, with the survival of the text"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the close balances two readings at once, his non-understanding as both the guarantee of the text's survival and the emptying of his own part in it. B is the elaborate trap, taking only the bleak horn (a wasted, uncomprehending life); A takes only the warm horn (humility as service); D contradicts 'because of him' by crediting the institution.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-009", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She keeps the house the way he left it: every chair\nat the angle of his leaving, the clock he wound\nstill wound, though now by her, to the same hour;\nthe dust permitted only where he let it lie.\n\nVisitors call it love, and she does not correct them.\nShe has not moved the coat that waits behind the door\nfor a return the calendar has ruled against.\nTo alter anything would be to admit a date.\n\nSo the rooms hold their breath. And whether this is faith,\nor a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace,\nshe could not say, and does not ask; she only\nwinds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central tension lies in", format: "single_best", options: ["whether her refusal to change the house is fidelity or a self-made prison","whether her grief is sincere or merely a performance for her visitors","the comfort of familiar objects after a bereavement","the quiet way the dead go on governing the living through the habits they leave"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the poem's explicit either/or is 'whether this is faith, or a cell', fidelity or a self-made prison. B is the near-twin, an open question with the wrong horns (sincere versus performed), where the poem never doubts her grief is real. D states only the one reading (the dead govern the living) as if settled; C reduces it to comfort.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-010", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She keeps the house the way he left it: every chair\nat the angle of his leaving, the clock he wound\nstill wound, though now by her, to the same hour;\nthe dust permitted only where he let it lie.\n\nVisitors call it love, and she does not correct them.\nShe has not moved the coat that waits behind the door\nfor a return the calendar has ruled against.\nTo alter anything would be to admit a date.\n\nSo the rooms hold their breath. And whether this is faith,\nor a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace,\nshe could not say, and does not ask; she only\nwinds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In 'To alter anything would be to admit a date', the word 'admit' most nearly means", format: "single_best", options: ["concede","broach","ratify","usher in"], answer: 0, explanation: "To admit a date here is to concede the fact of his death and its finality. Broach (to raise as a topic) is the near-miss; ratify (to approve formally) and usher in (to let enter, the literal sense of admit) both miss the act of acknowledgement.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-011", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She keeps the house the way he left it: every chair\nat the angle of his leaving, the clock he wound\nstill wound, though now by her, to the same hour;\nthe dust permitted only where he let it lie.\n\nVisitors call it love, and she does not correct them.\nShe has not moved the coat that waits behind the door\nfor a return the calendar has ruled against.\nTo alter anything would be to admit a date.\n\nSo the rooms hold their breath. And whether this is faith,\nor a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace,\nshe could not say, and does not ask; she only\nwinds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The image that 'the rooms hold their breath' chiefly conveys", format: "single_best", options: ["the suspense of a household awaiting news","the tension between her and her visitors","the heavy staleness of air that gathers in a house long shut up and left unaired","a stillness that is also a refusal to let time resume"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'the rooms hold their breath' fuses stillness with a willed arrest of time, which D names. C is the elaborate trap, literalising it into the staleness of shut-up air; A invents a household awaiting news; B imports interpersonal tension with the visitors.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-012", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She keeps the house the way he left it: every chair\nat the angle of his leaving, the clock he wound\nstill wound, though now by her, to the same hour;\nthe dust permitted only where he let it lie.\n\nVisitors call it love, and she does not correct them.\nShe has not moved the coat that waits behind the door\nfor a return the calendar has ruled against.\nTo alter anything would be to admit a date.\n\nSo the rooms hold their breath. And whether this is faith,\nor a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace,\nshe could not say, and does not ask; she only\nwinds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "At the close, 'she only winds the clock, and lets the coat go on waiting', the woman is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["dutiful but awakening","faithful and at peace","devoted but unfree","loving and consoled"], answer: 2, explanation: "Devoted but unfree holds both halves the poem leaves standing: the care is real, yet the house is 'a cell whose bars are objects she will not displace'. The second word of each other pair fails, since 'she could not say, and does not ask' rules out peace, awakening and consolation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-013", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He maps a coast that will not keep its shape:\nthe tide redraws by night what he sets down,\nand every chart he finishes is wrong\nbefore the ink is dry enough to fold.\n\nHe knows this. Still he measures, line by line,\nthe bays that will be elsewhere by the spring,\nas if the use of maps were not to last\nbut to have looked, exactly, once, and said so.\n\nCall it folly; call it the only honesty\na shifting world allows: to fix a moment\nnot because it stays, but because it was,\nand would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central claim is", format: "single_best", options: ["that careful, exact observation is simply wasted labour in a world that will not hold still","that the worth of mapping lies in faithful witness to a passing moment, not in permanence","whether the cartographer maps from stubbornness or from a clear-eyed reason of his own","that all human knowledge is provisional and soon overturned"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the constructive turn is 'to fix a moment because it was', so mapping's worth lies in faithful witness, not permanence. A takes the 'folly' horn the poem answers; C frames an open question the poem in fact settles, calling the labour 'the only honesty a shifting world allows', not mere stubbornness; D generalises to all knowledge.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-014", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He maps a coast that will not keep its shape:\nthe tide redraws by night what he sets down,\nand every chart he finishes is wrong\nbefore the ink is dry enough to fold.\n\nHe knows this. Still he measures, line by line,\nthe bays that will be elsewhere by the spring,\nas if the use of maps were not to last\nbut to have looked, exactly, once, and said so.\n\nCall it folly; call it the only honesty\na shifting world allows: to fix a moment\nnot because it stays, but because it was,\nand would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The detail that each chart is wrong 'before the ink is dry enough to fold' chiefly emphasises", format: "single_best", options: ["the cartographer's own haste and carelessness in finishing before he had checked","his refusal to wait for conditions to settle","the poor quality of his instruments","the speed with which his finished work is already falsified by the tide"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the chart is wrong before the ink dries, stressing the speed with which the tide falsifies his finished work. A blames his haste and carelessness, though he is meticulous; B implies a deliberate refusal to wait, but the point is the world's speed; C blames poor instruments.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-015", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He maps a coast that will not keep its shape:\nthe tide redraws by night what he sets down,\nand every chart he finishes is wrong\nbefore the ink is dry enough to fold.\n\nHe knows this. Still he measures, line by line,\nthe bays that will be elsewhere by the spring,\nas if the use of maps were not to last\nbut to have looked, exactly, once, and said so.\n\nCall it folly; call it the only honesty\na shifting world allows: to fix a moment\nnot because it stays, but because it was,\nand would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "Which person's work would the poem most regard as sharing the cartographer's purpose?", format: "single_best", options: ["an archivist who preserves old maps so that later scholars may draw on their accumulated use","a forecaster who predicts how the coast will look next year","a builder who raises a monument meant to outlast the centuries","a diarist who records one day exactly, knowing the entry will change nothing"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the cartographer's worth is exact witness to a passing moment, not permanence or use, so the diarist matches. A is the trap, the archivist's cumulative use, which the poem sets aside; C seeks endurance; B seeks prediction.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-016", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He maps a coast that will not keep its shape:\nthe tide redraws by night what he sets down,\nand every chart he finishes is wrong\nbefore the ink is dry enough to fold.\n\nHe knows this. Still he measures, line by line,\nthe bays that will be elsewhere by the spring,\nas if the use of maps were not to last\nbut to have looked, exactly, once, and said so.\n\nCall it folly; call it the only honesty\na shifting world allows: to fix a moment\nnot because it stays, but because it was,\nand would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The closing words, that the moment 'would, unmarked, have gone unwitnessed by', imply that without his record it would have", format: "single_best", options: ["been remembered, but inaccurately, by others who had glimpsed it without ever setting it down","recurred unchanged in a later season","passed with no one having marked that it was so","shown that the coast was never stable"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: without his record the moment would have passed with no one marking that it was so. A is the elaborate trap, supplying inaccurate others who half-remember it; B has it recurring unchanged in a later season; D merely restates the coast's instability rather than the point about witness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-017", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each year she lifts a little of the grime,\nand with it, here and there, a fleck of him,\nthe painter, whose last touches were the first\nto thin and lift beneath the cleaning cloth.\n\nThe face emerges brighter, and less his.\nWhere she repairs, she guesses; where she guesses,\nthe hand that fills the loss is hers, not his,\nso that the saved and the destroyed are one.\n\nAt what point is it kept, and at what point made?\nShe works to the edge of that unanswered line,\nand signs no name, and lets the label stand\nthat calls the brightened canvas all his own.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem turns chiefly on", format: "single_best", options: ["the formidable technical difficulty of cleaning an old painting without inflicting fresh damage","the dishonesty of letting a restored work bear only the artist's name","whether the restorer's work honours the painter or quietly betrays him","whether restoration preserves a work or gradually replaces it with the restorer's own"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the poem's 'kept, or made?' line asks whether restoration preserves the work or gradually replaces it with the restorer's own. C is the near-twin, an open question with moralised horns (honour versus betrayal), where the poem's question is preservation versus replacement; A reduces it to technical difficulty; B takes the label, only a consequence, for the centre.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-018", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each year she lifts a little of the grime,\nand with it, here and there, a fleck of him,\nthe painter, whose last touches were the first\nto thin and lift beneath the cleaning cloth.\n\nThe face emerges brighter, and less his.\nWhere she repairs, she guesses; where she guesses,\nthe hand that fills the loss is hers, not his,\nso that the saved and the destroyed are one.\n\nAt what point is it kept, and at what point made?\nShe works to the edge of that unanswered line,\nand signs no name, and lets the label stand\nthat calls the brightened canvas all his own.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "On the line 'so that the saved and the destroyed are one', rescue and effacement in her work are", format: "single_best", options: ["one and the same act, each achieved only in the doing of the other","two distinct stages following in sequence, the rescue accomplished first and the loss coming only afterward","opposite results, only one of which finally happens","alike to the eye but opposite in their effect"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the paradox is identity, to save is, in the same stroke, to efface, each achieved only in the doing of the other. B is the elaborate trap, making them sequential (rescue then loss); C makes them alternatives; D makes them merely similar in appearance.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-019", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each year she lifts a little of the grime,\nand with it, here and there, a fleck of him,\nthe painter, whose last touches were the first\nto thin and lift beneath the cleaning cloth.\n\nThe face emerges brighter, and less his.\nWhere she repairs, she guesses; where she guesses,\nthe hand that fills the loss is hers, not his,\nso that the saved and the destroyed are one.\n\nAt what point is it kept, and at what point made?\nShe works to the edge of that unanswered line,\nand signs no name, and lets the label stand\nthat calls the brightened canvas all his own.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "That she 'signs no name, and lets the label stand' is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["an evasion that leaves unresolved how much of the work is now hers","modest deference to the original artist's authorship","a fear that claiming credit would damage her reputation","a legal requirement governing the attribution of restored works"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: signing no name and letting the label stand is an evasion that leaves unresolved how much of the work is now hers, matching the 'unanswered line'. B reads it as settled humility the poem withholds; D invents a legal rule; C invents a fear for her reputation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-020", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Each year she lifts a little of the grime,\nand with it, here and there, a fleck of him,\nthe painter, whose last touches were the first\nto thin and lift beneath the cleaning cloth.\n\nThe face emerges brighter, and less his.\nWhere she repairs, she guesses; where she guesses,\nthe hand that fills the loss is hers, not his,\nso that the saved and the destroyed are one.\n\nAt what point is it kept, and at what point made?\nShe works to the edge of that unanswered line,\nand signs no name, and lets the label stand\nthat calls the brightened canvas all his own.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's attitude toward her work is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["admiring of her skill and restraint","quietly accusatory of a kind of forgery","troubled, and deliberately without verdict","indifferent to the philosophical puzzle it raises"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the poem works to the edge of an 'unanswered line' and signs no verdict, so its attitude is troubled and deliberately without one. A resolves it into admiration; B resolves it into the accusation of forgery; D mistakes the poem's evident absorption for indifference.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-021", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The photograph has outlived what it shows:\nher face, in time, gave way to its one pose,\nuntil the moment we recall as her\nis this, the angle that the shutter chose.\n\nWe say we keep her. What we keep is light\narrested on an afternoon gone white\nwith distance; and the living, shifting face\nis gone the more securely for the sight.\n\nHand me no album as a stay of loss.\nThe likeness, loyal, smiling, will not move,\nand what it saves it quietly supplants,\nthe keepsake closing over what we love.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem chiefly maintains", format: "single_best", options: ["that photographs subtly distort the very appearance of those they depict", "that a fixed image can come to replace, rather than preserve, the living memory", "that memory is inherently unreliable without physical aids", "that grief is eased by keeping mementos of the dead"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the keepsake 'quietly supplants' the living memory, so a fixed image can replace rather than preserve it. A reduces the claim to distorted looks; D is the consoling view the poem refuses ('hand me no album'); C reverses the poem, which says the aid harms memory rather than propping up a weak one.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-022", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The photograph has outlived what it shows:\nher face, in time, gave way to its one pose,\nuntil the moment we recall as her\nis this, the angle that the shutter chose.\n\nWe say we keep her. What we keep is light\narrested on an afternoon gone white\nwith distance; and the living, shifting face\nis gone the more securely for the sight.\n\nHand me no album as a stay of loss.\nThe likeness, loyal, smiling, will not move,\nand what it saves it quietly supplants,\nthe keepsake closing over what we love.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In 'an afternoon gone white with distance', 'gone white' is best replaced by", format: "single_best", options: ["effaced","hoary","pallid","candid"], answer: 0, explanation: "The remembered afternoon has been blanked out by time, so effaced (rubbed away) fits. Hoary (white with age) and candid (from the Latin for white) play on the colour but miss the erasure; pallid (pale) is only a partial loss, not a blanking.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-023", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The photograph has outlived what it shows:\nher face, in time, gave way to its one pose,\nuntil the moment we recall as her\nis this, the angle that the shutter chose.\n\nWe say we keep her. What we keep is light\narrested on an afternoon gone white\nwith distance; and the living, shifting face\nis gone the more securely for the sight.\n\nHand me no album as a stay of loss.\nThe likeness, loyal, smiling, will not move,\nand what it saves it quietly supplants,\nthe keepsake closing over what we love.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "That the living face is 'gone the more securely for the sight' is best understood to mean that", format: "single_best", options: ["that seeing the photograph makes the fact of the loss feel sharper each time one looks","that repeated viewing gradually wears out the photograph","that the more one looks, the more one notices the photograph's flaws","that the photograph, by fixing one look, makes the living face harder to recover"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the fixed image displaces recall, so the photograph, by fixing one look, makes the living face harder to recover. A is the emotional gloss (the loss feels more final) rather than the point about memory; B and C literalise 'sight' as looking that damages the print.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-024", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The photograph has outlived what it shows:\nher face, in time, gave way to its one pose,\nuntil the moment we recall as her\nis this, the angle that the shutter chose.\n\nWe say we keep her. What we keep is light\narrested on an afternoon gone white\nwith distance; and the living, shifting face\nis gone the more securely for the sight.\n\nHand me no album as a stay of loss.\nThe likeness, loyal, smiling, will not move,\nand what it saves it quietly supplants,\nthe keepsake closing over what we love.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's attitude toward the album is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["sentimentally grateful for the comfort it brings","bitterly contemptuous of the sentimental people who keep photographs and mistake them for the dead","wary, treating the consolation it offers as a quiet betrayal","detached and merely analytical about memory"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'what it saves it quietly supplants' makes the poem wary, treating the album's consolation as a quiet betrayal. B is the elaborate trap, overstating into contempt for the people who keep photographs; A is the surface gratitude the poem refuses; D understates the felt loss into mere analysis.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-025", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He cuts the rose back hard, to a few bare canes,\npast where a kinder hand would think to stop;\nthe bush that flowered last year he leaves a stump,\nand calls the wreckage prudence, calls it love.\n\nCome spring it answers him in heavier bloom.\nThe wound was where the strength went; what he took\nwas last year's triumph, holding back the next.\nHe has learned to doubt the mercy that would spare.\n\nAnd still, each cut, he is a man with shears\nabove a living thing, deciding what it loses;\nthe garden thrives by his hard charity,\nand never has a say in what it pays.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem is chiefly about", format: "single_best", options: ["the disagreement between gentle and severe approaches to gardening", "the way an apparent harm can be the very condition of a later flourishing", "the casual cruelty that the gardener's warm talk of prudence and love quietly conceals", "whether the gardener's hard pruning is wisdom or a cruelty he will not admit to himself"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the poem joins flourishing-through-harm (hard pruning brings heavier bloom) with the disquiet of holding such power. C reads 'calls it love' as mere euphemism for cruelty, one horn only; D is the near-twin, an open question framed as wisdom versus self-deceived cruelty, where the poem grants the pruning works and dwells on the unease of power; A frames a settled debate between gentle and severe gardening.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-026", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He cuts the rose back hard, to a few bare canes,\npast where a kinder hand would think to stop;\nthe bush that flowered last year he leaves a stump,\nand calls the wreckage prudence, calls it love.\n\nCome spring it answers him in heavier bloom.\nThe wound was where the strength went; what he took\nwas last year's triumph, holding back the next.\nHe has learned to doubt the mercy that would spare.\n\nAnd still, each cut, he is a man with shears\nabove a living thing, deciding what it loses;\nthe garden thrives by his hard charity,\nand never has a say in what it pays.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The line 'The wound was where the strength went' most nearly means that", format: "single_best", options: ["the plant's energy had been concentrated in the part he removed","that cutting the plant back so hard weakened it, draining away the strength it had stored over the year","the gardener regretted the damage he had done","the plant was diseased at the point where he cut"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: last year's growth held the strength, so removing it frees the next, the paradox of 'the wound was where the strength went'. B is the elaborate trap, literalising 'wound' as weakening, the opposite; C imports regret; D invents disease.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-027", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He cuts the rose back hard, to a few bare canes,\npast where a kinder hand would think to stop;\nthe bush that flowered last year he leaves a stump,\nand calls the wreckage prudence, calls it love.\n\nCome spring it answers him in heavier bloom.\nThe wound was where the strength went; what he took\nwas last year's triumph, holding back the next.\nHe has learned to doubt the mercy that would spare.\n\nAnd still, each cut, he is a man with shears\nabove a living thing, deciding what it loses;\nthe garden thrives by his hard charity,\nand never has a say in what it pays.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "On the gardener's view, to spare the plant would be", format: "single_best", options: ["merciful in seeming, harmful in effect", "cruel in seeming but kind in effect", "both merciful and beneficial", "neither merciful nor harmful"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: to spare the plant looks merciful yet stunts it, so sparing is merciful in seeming but harmful in effect. B is the inverted trap, describing the cutting (cruel-seeming, kind in effect) rather than the sparing; C denies the harm; D empties the line by making sparing neither.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-028", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He cuts the rose back hard, to a few bare canes,\npast where a kinder hand would think to stop;\nthe bush that flowered last year he leaves a stump,\nand calls the wreckage prudence, calls it love.\n\nCome spring it answers him in heavier bloom.\nThe wound was where the strength went; what he took\nwas last year's triumph, holding back the next.\nHe has learned to doubt the mercy that would spare.\n\nAnd still, each cut, he is a man with shears\nabove a living thing, deciding what it loses;\nthe garden thrives by his hard charity,\nand never has a say in what it pays.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The final line, that the garden 'never has a say in what it pays', chiefly", format: "single_best", options: ["observes, reasonably enough, that plants lack minds and so are owed no real moral consideration at all","condemns the gardener as a tyrant over his plants","introduces a note of disquiet about power exercised over what cannot consent","celebrates the gardener's complete mastery of his craft"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the closing line introduces a note of disquiet about power exercised over what cannot consent ('never has a say in what it pays'). A is the elaborate trap, the dismissive view that mindless plants are owed nothing; B overstates into condemning the gardener as a tyrant; D celebrates his mastery and misses the unease.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-029", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The snow does not discriminate. It lays\nthe same white sentence over wall and weed,\nthe rubbish heap, the rose, the broken chair,\nand grants them, for a night, a single grace.\n\nCall it a lie: it hides what it should show,\nthe ruined yard made lovely by a coat\nthat owes the truth of things below it nothing,\nand melts by noon to give the mess its name.\n\nOr call it mercy: that the world should have\none hour exempt from what it is, one hour\nwhen even the discarded and the failed\nlie even with the cherished, under white.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's central tension is", format: "single_best", options: ["the transience of natural beauty","the serene indifference of nature, laying its white over the cherished and the discarded alike","whether the snow's concealment is a falsehood or a mercy","the way appearances deceive us about reality"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the poem's explicit 'Call it a lie... Or call it mercy' sets concealment as falsehood against concealment as mercy. B seizes on 'does not discriminate', but the question is evaluative, not about indifference; A is the secondary note of transience ('melts by noon'); D takes only the 'lie' horn.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-030", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The snow does not discriminate. It lays\nthe same white sentence over wall and weed,\nthe rubbish heap, the rose, the broken chair,\nand grants them, for a night, a single grace.\n\nCall it a lie: it hides what it should show,\nthe ruined yard made lovely by a coat\nthat owes the truth of things below it nothing,\nand melts by noon to give the mess its name.\n\nOr call it mercy: that the world should have\none hour exempt from what it is, one hour\nwhen even the discarded and the failed\nlie even with the cherished, under white.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "In 'the same white sentence', the word 'sentence' most nearly means", format: "single_best", options: ["an edict","a locution","an adjudication","a periphrasis"], answer: 0, explanation: "The snow is laid alike over everything, so 'sentence' is an edict, a decree imposed uniformly. A locution (a turn of phrase) plays on the grammatical sense; an adjudication (a verdict on worth) is denied by the grace granted regardless; a periphrasis (a roundabout phrasing) is unrelated.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-031", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The snow does not discriminate. It lays\nthe same white sentence over wall and weed,\nthe rubbish heap, the rose, the broken chair,\nand grants them, for a night, a single grace.\n\nCall it a lie: it hides what it should show,\nthe ruined yard made lovely by a coat\nthat owes the truth of things below it nothing,\nand melts by noon to give the mess its name.\n\nOr call it mercy: that the world should have\none hour exempt from what it is, one hour\nwhen even the discarded and the failed\nlie even with the cherished, under white.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "That the snow's coat 'owes the truth of things below it nothing' means that", format: "single_best", options: ["the snow is indifferent to the value of what it covers","the beauty of snow is independent of what it falls on","the snow will inevitably melt and reveal the truth","the snow conceals the real condition of what lies beneath it"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'owes the truth of things below it nothing' means the snow conceals the real condition of what lies beneath. A shifts to indifference about value; B to the autonomy of snow's beauty; C is the next line's idea (that it will melt and reveal), not this one.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-032", genre: "poetry", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The snow does not discriminate. It lays\nthe same white sentence over wall and weed,\nthe rubbish heap, the rose, the broken chair,\nand grants them, for a night, a single grace.\n\nCall it a lie: it hides what it should show,\nthe ruined yard made lovely by a coat\nthat owes the truth of things below it nothing,\nand melts by noon to give the mess its name.\n\nOr call it mercy: that the world should have\none hour exempt from what it is, one hour\nwhen even the discarded and the failed\nlie even with the cherished, under white.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The final stanza, beginning 'Or call it mercy', functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["resolve the poem firmly and finally in favour of the consoling reading, settling the question the earlier stanza had left open","ironically undercut the idea that snow could be merciful","offer the merciful reading as a genuine alternative without discrediting the first","lament that the mercy is only temporary"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'Or call it mercy' offers the merciful reading as a genuine alternative without discrediting the 'lie' reading, keeping both standing. A is the elaborate trap, having the stanza resolve the balance the poem keeps open; B ironically discredits the mercy; D shifts to the mercy being merely temporary.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-033", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The late work is all gaps. The finish goes,\nthe early polish that the critics praised;\nthe line now breaks, recovers, breaks again,\nand what was mastery is something else.\n\nHis students call it falling off, and grieve\nthe sure hand that the years have taken from him.\nHe does not seem to mourn it. Where he once\nwould close a phrase, he leaves it standing open.\n\nIs it the failing of a craft outlived,\nor craft itself outgrown, the rule let go\nby one who knows it now too well to need it?\nThe hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem turns on the question of", format: "single_best", options: ["the ingratitude of students toward an ageing master","whether an artist's late roughness is a failing decline or a deeper freedom","the inevitable physical decline that overtakes and ends every artist's working life","whether the late roughness is the master's own choice or the work of failing eyes and hands"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the poem's either/or is whether the late roughness is 'the failing of a craft outlived, or craft itself outgrown', decline or a deeper freedom. C states only the decline horn as settled fact; D is the near-twin, an open question recast as deliberate choice versus failing body, where the poem's axis is decline versus a freedom that is itself a kind of mastery; A misreads the grieving students as ungrateful.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-034", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The late work is all gaps. The finish goes,\nthe early polish that the critics praised;\nthe line now breaks, recovers, breaks again,\nand what was mastery is something else.\n\nHis students call it falling off, and grieve\nthe sure hand that the years have taken from him.\nHe does not seem to mourn it. Where he once\nwould close a phrase, he leaves it standing open.\n\nIs it the failing of a craft outlived,\nor craft itself outgrown, the rule let go\nby one who knows it now too well to need it?\nThe hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The last line, that 'the hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike', is best read as", format: "single_best", options: ["the master is physically frailer than he admits","onlookers cannot be trusted to judge an artist fairly","freedom and decline are, in the end, one and the same condition, indistinguishable in themselves","the same outward sign is compatible with opposite inner truths, so it cannot settle the question"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'the hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike' means one outward sign fits opposite inner truths, so it cannot settle the question. C overstates that the two conditions are identical, when only the sign is; A literalises it into physical frailty; B shifts to the untrustworthiness of onlookers.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-035", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The late work is all gaps. The finish goes,\nthe early polish that the critics praised;\nthe line now breaks, recovers, breaks again,\nand what was mastery is something else.\n\nHis students call it falling off, and grieve\nthe sure hand that the years have taken from him.\nHe does not seem to mourn it. Where he once\nwould close a phrase, he leaves it standing open.\n\nIs it the failing of a craft outlived,\nor craft itself outgrown, the rule let go\nby one who knows it now too well to need it?\nThe hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "About the master's leaving phrases 'standing open', the poem leaves which possibilities open? I. that it is the decline of failing skill. II. that it is the freedom of mastered skill. III. that it is mere carelessness.", format: "single_best", options: ["I only","I, II and III","II and III only","I and II only"], answer: 3, explanation: "The poem hovers between decline (I) and freedom (II) and refuses to choose, but it never offers carelessness (III): the openness is pointed, not slack. So I and II only.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-036", genre: "poetry", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The late work is all gaps. The finish goes,\nthe early polish that the critics praised;\nthe line now breaks, recovers, breaks again,\nand what was mastery is something else.\n\nHis students call it falling off, and grieve\nthe sure hand that the years have taken from him.\nHe does not seem to mourn it. Where he once\nwould close a phrase, he leaves it standing open.\n\nIs it the failing of a craft outlived,\nor craft itself outgrown, the rule let go\nby one who knows it now too well to need it?\nThe hand that shakes and the hand that is freed shake alike.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The phrase 'the rule let go by one who knows it now too well to need it' casts the master as having", format: "single_best", options: ["forgotten the rules he once knew","rejected the rules as worthless","so wholly internalised the rules that he no longer needs to apply them consciously","lost, with age, the very capacity to follow the rules he had once commanded so surely"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'knows it too well to need it' casts the master as having so wholly internalised the rules that he no longer applies them consciously. D is the elaborate trap, taking the decline horn (lost the capacity); A (forgotten) is the same decline reading; B overstates into rejecting the rules as worthless.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-poetry-037", genre: "poetry", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She forgave him everything, and let him know it,\nand in the letting-know the gift turned strange:\nfor to forgive aloud is to assume\nthe bench, the robe, the right to have condemned.\n\nHe had not asked. The pardon, like a hand\nlaid on a head that did not bow, conferred\na height she had not had till she forgave,\nand could not give the wrong back what it was.\n\nPerhaps she meant it kindly. Even so,\nthe kindest pardon keeps a little court,\nand seats the one forgiven, and stays standing;\nmercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The poem's controlling claim is", format: "single_best", options: ["that forgiveness is, at bottom, always a disguised form of revenge","that to forgive openly is to claim a superiority over the forgiven, even when kindly meant","that one ought to forgive privately rather than aloud","whether her pardon was a genuine kindness or a veiled assertion of power over him"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: 'mercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word' makes open forgiveness a claim of superiority over the forgiven, even when kindly meant. D is the near-twin, leaving as an open question what the poem in fact commits to ('Even so...'), that even sincere pardon asserts rank; A overstates it into disguised revenge; C turns an implication into a prescription to forgive privately.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-038", genre: "poetry", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She forgave him everything, and let him know it,\nand in the letting-know the gift turned strange:\nfor to forgive aloud is to assume\nthe bench, the robe, the right to have condemned.\n\nHe had not asked. The pardon, like a hand\nlaid on a head that did not bow, conferred\na height she had not had till she forgave,\nand could not give the wrong back what it was.\n\nPerhaps she meant it kindly. Even so,\nthe kindest pardon keeps a little court,\nand seats the one forgiven, and stays standing;\nmercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The images of 'the bench, the robe, the right to have condemned' present forgiveness as", format: "single_best", options: ["placing the forgiver in the position of a judge","evidence that the woman had a legal grievance against the man","proof that the man had committed a crime","something that should be a formal, deliberate act"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'the bench, the robe, the right to have condemned' place the forgiver in a judge's position. B and C literalise the courtroom image into an actual grievance and an actual crime; D turns the image into a recommendation that forgiveness be formal.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-039", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She forgave him everything, and let him know it,\nand in the letting-know the gift turned strange:\nfor to forgive aloud is to assume\nthe bench, the robe, the right to have condemned.\n\nHe had not asked. The pardon, like a hand\nlaid on a head that did not bow, conferred\na height she had not had till she forgave,\nand could not give the wrong back what it was.\n\nPerhaps she meant it kindly. Even so,\nthe kindest pardon keeps a little court,\nand seats the one forgiven, and stays standing;\nmercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The image of 'a hand laid on a head that did not bow' most precisely conveys that the forgiveness", format: "single_best", options: ["was refused outright by the man","elevated her over a man who had neither sought nor submitted to it","met with a pride that prevented any gratitude","was extended against the man's clearly and explicitly stated wishes, over his open objection"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: 'a hand laid on a head that did not bow' shows forgiveness conferring a height over a man who had neither sought nor submitted to it. D claims an explicit wish against it the poem does not state; A overstates into an outright refusal; C judges the man's pride rather than the asymmetry.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-poetry-040", genre: "poetry", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-poetry-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "She forgave him everything, and let him know it,\nand in the letting-know the gift turned strange:\nfor to forgive aloud is to assume\nthe bench, the robe, the right to have condemned.\n\nHe had not asked. The pardon, like a hand\nlaid on a head that did not bow, conferred\na height she had not had till she forgave,\nand could not give the wrong back what it was.\n\nPerhaps she meant it kindly. Even so,\nthe kindest pardon keeps a little court,\nand seats the one forgiven, and stays standing;\nmercy, once spoken, is not quite the equal's word.", attribution: "Original poem" }, stem: "The concession 'Perhaps she meant it kindly. Even so' chiefly functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["withdraw the poem's criticism of her","shift the blame from her to the man","reveal that her show of kindness was entirely feigned, a performance to conceal a colder motive","grant her sincerity while insisting the act of forgiving still asserts rank"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'Perhaps she meant it kindly. Even so' grants her sincerity while insisting the act of forgiving still asserts rank. C contradicts 'meant it kindly' by calling the kindness feigned; A would withdraw the criticism the 'Even so' preserves; B redirects the blame to the man, which the poem does not.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-001", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best understood as a portrait of", format: "single_best", options: ["a generous friend whose overbearing but well-meant counsel is, year by year, taken for granted by the man it saved","a friendship worn thin by the resentment that unequal success breeds","a candid man whose tactlessness, not his motives, is what has slowly cost him friends","a man who mistakes for his chief virtue a habit of steering others toward ends of his own"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the cost to 'our Sundays', slipped in 'in passing', exposes self-interest dressed as candour, so the portrait is of a man who takes for a virtue his habit of steering others his own way. C is the near-twin, pinning the trouble on tactlessness, but what the buried detail reveals is motive, not manner. A adopts his flattering self-image as the wronged loyal friend; B takes his own alibi, that success breeds ingratitude.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-002", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That he 'mentioned only in passing' the post's taking Daniel abroad most likely indicates that", format: "single_best", options: ["the loss of their Sundays, which he calls incidental, was in fact his real motive, lightly disguised","he sincerely judged the distance a small thing beside the merits of the case he laid out","he wished to spare Daniel the awkwardness of the leaving","he was too modest to dwell on his own sacrifice"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: losing 'our Sundays' is the one reason that actually moved him, mentioned 'in passing' to keep it from view. B is the near-twin, taking the offhandness as honest proportion, but he concedes he raised it 'only because honesty must be complete', so he knew its weight. C recasts the concealment as kindness; D accepts his modesty at face value.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-003", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's closing talk of 'the slow ingratitude that success breeds'", format: "single_best", options: ["is the hard-won, slightly weary wisdom of a man who has watched success spoil people","correctly identifies Daniel's growing arrogance as the cause of the distance","is a self-serving gloss on a coolness his own managing conduct better explains","shows the narrator has, at last, begun to suspect his own part in the estrangement"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the thinning thanks more likely track Daniel's dawning sense of having been managed, so 'ingratitude' is a gloss that protects the narrator. B is the near-twin, accepting his diagnosis as accurate. A flatters the remark as earned wisdom; D credits him with a self-suspicion the passage gives no sign of, since he still lays the coolness at Daniel's door.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-004", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The attitude the passage takes toward the narrator is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["sympathetic to a misunderstood and loyal man","openly hostile, denouncing him as a villain","quietly ironic, letting his own words convict him","neutral, merely transcribing his account"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage never editorialises; the damning detail ('beyond the reach of our Sundays') is his own. A adopts his view; B overstates the temperature; D ignores how the details are arranged to undercut him.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-005", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "I have never been able to watch a friend make a mistake and say nothing; it is, I think, my chief virtue, though it has cost me friends. When Daniel meant to take the northern post I drove four hours to talk him out of it, and sat in his kitchen until two in the morning laying out, point by point, what he could not see for himself. That the post would have taken him abroad, beyond the reach of our Sundays, I mentioned only in passing, and only because honesty between friends must be complete. He stayed. He thanks me still, a little less warmly each year, which I attribute to the slow ingratitude that success breeds in a man who has forgotten he was ever advised.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "His insistence that 'honesty between friends must be complete' shows him to be", format: "single_best", options: ["candid and selfless", "principled but self-serving", "honest though tactless", "scrupulous and consistent"], answer: 1, explanation: "He invokes a fine principle, but only to license the remark that served him, so high-principled but self-serving holds both halves. Each other pair fails on its second word: he is not selfless, tactlessness is not the point, and he is not consistent, since the principle never runs against his own interest.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-006", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Miss Pratt is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["someone whose genuine care is interwoven with loneliness and a hope not wholly disinterested","a kind neighbour whose goodness the street rightly admired","a calculating woman who, beneath a convincing show of devotion, befriended the dying man only for the possessions she meant to inherit","a lonely woman indifferent to what others thought of her"], answer: 0, explanation: "A braids her real care, her own cold house, and the managed grief over the jug, so genuine care is interwoven with loneliness and an interested hope. C is the elaborate trap, hardening her into a pure schemer; B takes the street's admiring verdict; D denies her evident attention to appearances.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-007", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The remark that 'a charity which warms the giver is charity still'", format: "single_best", options: ["endorses her visits as wholly selfless","grants the self-interest yet refuses, pointedly, to call it hypocrisy","lays down a general law that all charity is, at bottom, self-serving","gently mocks the street for excusing what it ought to condemn"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the remark grants that her charity 'warms the giver' yet, 'without unkindness', declines to call it hypocrisy. C is the twin trap, inflating a remark about her into a law about all charity. A ignores 'warms the giver'; D turns the street's tolerant verdict into mockery the line does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-008", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Her being 'careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant'", format: "single_best", options: ["shows the grief was, after all, a performance got up for the watching street", "shows she had come to value the blue jug above the man himself", "reveals a mixed self-consciousness that complicates her grief without cancelling it", "marks a rare moment of honesty about her own mixed motives"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the managed display betrays a watchfulness about how she appears, complicating her grief without proving it hollow. A is the twin trap, pressing 'careful to seem' all the way to a got-up performance, further than the detail bears; B over-reads it into valuing the jug above the man; D reverses it, since she is managing appearances, not confessing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-009", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's stance toward Miss Pratt and the street is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["sharply satirical, exposing the whole street's complacent approval as the foolishness of people who cannot see what is in front of them","wry but humane, noting the self-interest without withdrawing sympathy","tender and wholly uncritical toward everyone involved","coldly clinical about provincial hypocrisy"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the narrator notes the self-interest yet judges 'without unkindness', a wry but humane middle. A is the elaborate trap, overstating into sharp satire of a foolish street; C ignores the noted self-interest; D overstates the edge into cold clinical contempt.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-010", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Miss Pratt visited the old man every afternoon that last winter, and the street, which missed nothing, approved. She read to him, and turned his cushions, and was seen leaving at dusk with the particular tiredness of the good. That she had no family of her own, and few callers, and that the house she returned to was colder than his, were facts the street also knew, and folded, without unkindness, into its approval, as though to say that a charity which warms the giver is charity still. When he left her, in the end, the small blue jug she had admired, she was careful to seem surprised, and more careful still to seem to grieve a little longer than the jug alone would warrant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, 'the particular tiredness of the good' presents her weariness as essentially", format: "single_best", options: ["performative","lugubrious","fatuous","perfunctory"], answer: 0, explanation: "Performative catches a tiredness worn for the watching street, a badge of virtue put on for an audience. Lugubrious (mournful) misreads display as gloom; fatuous (silly) and perfunctory (cursory) miss that the weariness is shown, not slight.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-011", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly turns on", format: "single_best", options: ["the gap between the candidate's confident reading of the room and what it actually conveyed","the way interviews reward surface confidence over the substance a candidate has prepared","the quiet cruelty of a panel that lets an earnest applicant deceive himself","the value of thorough preparation in winning a post"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the passage turns on the distance between how the candidate reads the scene and what it really conveys. B is the twin trap, hardening that single case into a thesis about interviews rewarding confidence, a moral the passage does not draw. C overstates the kindly panel into cruelty; D takes the surface lesson about preparation.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-012", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "'Thorough', said the second time more slowly, is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["blunt and critical", "warm and sincere", "courteous but cool", "casual and offhand"], answer: 2, explanation: "The slowed repetition keeps the courtesy of praise while draining its warmth, so polite but discouraging. Warm-and-sincere takes it at face value; blunt-and-critical overstates an open verdict the panel never gives; casual-and-offhand misses its loaded deliberateness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-013", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'look he took for admiration' is presented in a way that", format: "single_best", options: ["confirms that the panel did admire his plan","lets the reader feel the candidate may be misreading the look, without saying so outright","tips the reader off that the panel had already turned against him","leaves the look genuinely ambiguous, as opaque to the reader as to the candidate"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: 'a look he took for admiration' plants a doubt in the reader without asserting the reverse. D is the near-twin, but it overstates the opacity: the phrasing tilts the reader to suspect a misreading rather than leaving it evenly poised. C claims a settled verdict against him the text does not give; A takes his reading as confirmed.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-014", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The final sentence works chiefly to", format: "single_best", options: ["condemn the panel for deciding before the candidate had even left the building","hint that the decision the panel reached was an unjust one","leave open the chance that his letter of acceptance will yet succeed","let the reader, not the candidate, learn the outcome, and so spring the irony"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the closing line hands the outcome to the reader while the candidate walks off composing his acceptance, which is where the irony lands. A is the trap, reading a rebuke of the panel's haste into a neutral detail; B editorialises that the decision was unjust; C contradicts the implied result.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-015", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He left the interview certain it had gone well. They had smiled when he entered, and the senior man had said, twice, how very thorough his preparation was; and when he set out his plan for the department they had exchanged a look he took for admiration. He did not weigh the brevity of the questions that followed, nor the way the senior man had glanced at the clock and then, more kindly, at the door; nor that 'thorough' had been said the second time more slowly. He walked to the station composing the letter he would write to accept. Behind him, in the room, they were already speaking of the next candidate.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's attitude toward the candidate is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["mocking of his vanity","indifferent to his fate","quietly admiring of the unshaken confidence with which he reads the room and composes his letter of acceptance","pitying but not unkind, watching him misread a settled outcome"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the narrator watches the candidate misread a settled outcome with pity but not unkindness. C is the elaborate trap, taking his confidence admiringly and missing the irony; A overstates into mockery of his vanity; B mistakes the sympathetic irony for indifference.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-016", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The scene chiefly conveys", format: "single_best", options: ["the practical awkwardness of selling a long-lived-in house","a woman's grief and buried guilt rising up through an ordinary sale","the casual insensitivity of buyers chattering of boilers while she parts with her past","her quiet relief at being free at last of a house full of hard memories"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: under the boiler-and-curtains talk runs a freighted history (the brother, the telephone), so grief and buried guilt surface through a flat sale. D is the near-miss, reading 'leaving everything' as release, but the weight of the remembered silence pulls toward grief, not relief. C blames the ordinary buyers for insensitivity; A takes the surface difficulty of selling.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-017", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Her not having spoken is, for her, chiefly a source of", format: "single_best", options: ["bereavement","compunction","resentment","vindication"], answer: 1, explanation: "Compunction, a prick of conscience over what one did or failed to do, names her guilt at the fatal silence. Bereavement is only the loss, not the self-blame; resentment and vindication point the feeling outward, away from her own omission.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-018", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The drawer that 'had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided... to behave'", format: "single_best", options: ["externalises her sense that the house is quietly releasing her","shows the buyers are skilled with old fittings","indicates she had exaggerated the house's faults","suggests that the house, with new owners and fresh attention, has genuinely become an easier and more tractable place to manage"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the drawer behaving 'as though the house had decided to behave' externalises her sense that the house is quietly releasing her. D is the elaborate trap, literalising it into the house being genuinely easier now; C literalises it into her having exaggerated the faults; B credits the buyers' skill.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-019", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing line, 'She was leaving everything', carries beneath its literal sense", format: "single_best", options: ["her surrender of a whole freighted past, not the furnishings alone","a weary readiness to be done with the house and all it holds","nothing beyond the literal fact of a fully furnished sale","a flash of bitterness toward the buyers who take even the curtains"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'everything' gathers the curtains and the freighted past alike, the loss of a whole history. B is the twin, hearing in it a relieved readiness to be done, where the remembered silence makes it surrender rather than release. C stops at the literal furnished sale; D imports a bitterness toward the buyers the scene does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-020", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The buyers wanted to know about the boiler. She told them what she could, and watched the woman open and close the kitchen drawer that had always stuck, and not stick, as though the house had decided, today of all days, to behave. In the hall the man was saying the light was good. It was good. She had read forty years of letters by it, and once, on the stairs, had not said a thing that might have kept her brother in the country, and had heard, from this hall, the telephone that told her why the silence afterward would be permanent. The light was very good, she agreed. They would take the curtains if she was leaving them. She was leaving everything.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's manner is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["sentimental and openly mournful","coolly detached and, beneath the surface, genuinely unfeeling toward the woman and her loss alike","restrained, the feeling carried by understatement and juxtaposition","ironic at the woman's expense"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the grief is carried by what is placed beside the sale, understatement and juxtaposition rather than statement. B is the elaborate trap, mistaking the restraint for a genuine absence of feeling; A overstates into open mournfulness; D mistakes the target, since the irony is not at the woman's expense.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-021", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is chiefly about", format: "single_best", options: ["a son's lasting resentment of a father he still thinks was mean","a father's quiet failure to make his love legible to the boy until far too late","the belated recognition of a love the boy had long misread as meanness","the way teenagers everywhere misjudge their undemonstrative parents"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage enacts the son's late recognition of a love he had taken for meanness. B is the twin, shifting the weight onto the father's failure to express himself, but the change the passage records is in the son's reading, not the father's conduct ('the books were chosen'). A keeps the early resentment the ending overturns; D dissolves the particular into a law about all teenagers.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-022", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'the books were chosen, not the notes' means", format: "single_best", options: ["that the father, harried, had in truth put little real thought into the gift","the father weighed the book's worth above the cash he tucked inside it","the father could never quite settle on which book to give","the real gift was the book, picked with care; the money was only its wrapping"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'chosen, not the notes' means the book, found with care, was the true gift and the money its wrapping. B is the twin, taking 'chosen' as a weighing of monetary worth, where it marks care, not price. A inverts it into little thought spent; C invents an indecision the passage does not show.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-023", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The money described as 'the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper' figures it as", format: "single_best", options: ["proof, taken quite literally, that the father had been too poor even to afford a sheet of decent wrapping paper for the gift","the son's wish that the gift had been better presented","the father's resentment at having to give money at all","a stand-in for a tenderness he lacked the means to express more handsomely"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the money as 'wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper' figures it as a stand-in for a tenderness he lacked the means to express more handsomely. A is the elaborate trap, literalising it into actual wrapping paper; B shifts to the son's wish for better presentation; C imports a resentment the passage denies ('he did not defend himself').", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-024", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The contrast in the last lines, that he has the books still but cannot recall what he spent the notes on, chiefly", format: "single_best", options: ["shows the narrator was always careless with money","sharpens the reversal: what he scorned has lasted, what he prized is gone","marks his regret at the forgettable things he wasted the notes on","implies the chosen books proved of little real use to him"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: keeping the books yet forgetting the spent notes sharpens the reversal, the scorned gift endured and the prized cash vanished. C is the twin, hearing regret over particular purchases, but the point is the contrast itself, not remorse for what he bought. A makes him merely careless; D contradicts 'I have the books still'.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-025", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "My father gave me, each birthday, a single banknote folded into a book, and I thought him mean, and said so once, to his face, at fifteen, in the language of that age. He did not defend himself. It was years before I understood that the books were chosen, not the notes; that he had spent his evenings finding the one volume I did not know I wanted; and that the money, which I had counted and found wanting, was only the wrapping he could not afford to make from better paper. I have the books still. I spent the notes that night, and cannot, for my life, recall on what.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The older narrator's attitude toward his fifteen-year-old self is", format: "single_best", options: ["a son's lasting resentment of a frugal father","the belated recognition of a love the child had misread as meanness","the universal tendency of adolescents everywhere to misjudge the quiet parents who love them most","a father's failure to express his affection clearly"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the passage enacts a belated recognition of a love the boy had misread as meanness. C is the elaborate trap, generalising the specific case into a law about all teenagers; A takes the early resentment as the lasting note; D blames the father, whereas the fault lies in the son's earlier reading.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-026", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The sketch is chiefly concerned with", format: "single_best", options: ["the warmth of an exceptional host whose every attention is tirelessly bent on his guests' pleasure", "a domineering man who manoeuvres his guests into doing what he wants behind a show of looking after them", "how an overwhelming hospitality becomes a form of mastery, the guest made the occasion of the host's display", "the impossibility of ever feeling at ease as the guest of so forceful a personality"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the details build to 'whose harbour it was' and being 'the occasion of someone else's enjoyment', hospitality staged as a display of mastery. B also reads power in but mislocates it: Carver is not scheming to get his own way so much as staging his own pre-eminence (the tide lifts every boat). A takes the warmth at face value, the reputation the final clause qualifies; D shrinks it to a guest's social discomfort.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-027", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing tide image, that his generosity 'lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was'", format: "single_best", options: ["praises Carver for benefiting everyone around him","accuses Carver of actively harming his guests","suggests that it was Carver's evident wealth, more than any warmth of character, that drew people to his table and secured their admiration","concedes his generosity is real while exposing its function as a display of ownership"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'whose harbour it was' is the sting, so the image concedes his generosity is real while exposing its function as a display of ownership. C is the elaborate trap, fastening on 'harbour' as mere wealth; A takes 'lifts every boat' as pure praise; B overstates to active harm.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-028", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'Objection was provided for' tells us Carver had, in effect, every objection", format: "single_best", options: ["countenanced","brooked","forestalled","entertained"], answer: 2, explanation: "He anticipated and absorbed each preference so none could be raised: the objections were forestalled, headed off in advance. Brooked (tolerated), countenanced (permitted) and entertained (considered) all imply he let objections arise, the opposite of his method.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-029", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Being sent home as 'the occasion of someone else's enjoyment' implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the visit served Carver's own pleasure more than the guest's","the guests had, despite themselves, enjoyed the weekend more than they admitted","Carver took deep and genuine delight in his guests' company","the guests came away faintly guilty at their own ingratitude"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: to be sent home 'the occasion of someone else's enjoyment' makes the guest the instrument of Carver's pleasure, not its sharer. C is the near-twin, true that Carver enjoyed himself, but the phrase casts the guest as the occasion of that enjoyment rather than a companion in it. B reverses it into the guests' secret enjoyment; D invents guilt in them.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-030", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To be Carver's guest was to be conquered by kindness. He met you at the door with both hands, took your coat before you had decided to remove it, and had your weekend planned before you had unpacked. Objection was provided for: any preference you named, he had, with a delighted cry, anticipated and improved. By Sunday you had eaten what he chose, walked where he led, and admired what he valued, and were sent home laden with the sense, not quite of having enjoyed yourself, but of having been the occasion of someone else's enjoyment. He was reputed the most generous of men, and the reputation was just, provided one understood that his generosity, like a tide, lifted every boat in the harbour the better to show whose harbour it was.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's tone toward Carver is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["amused but exacting","indignant and heated","fond but exasperated","detached and impartial"], answer: 0, explanation: "Amused but exacting fits the wry precision of 'conquered by kindness', light in manner yet sharp in its dissection. The other pairs each carry a false half: the tone is not heated, not fond, and not detached.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-031", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The man is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["a deeply and genuinely compassionate man whose fine feeling for others is simply too rare and too delicate for the coarse world around him to appreciate","an artist too sensitive for the coarseness of ordinary life","a hypocrite who in truth feels nothing whatever","a man whose cultivated sensibility is a form of detachment from, not engagement with, others' feeling"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: his cultivated sensibility is a form of detachment from others' feeling, not engagement with it, a feeling kept 'decanted' and performed for art. A is the elaborate trap, adopting his flattering self-image as the unappreciated compassionate man; B repeats that self-image as the too-sensitive artist; C overstates into feeling nothing at all, though he does feel, coldly.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-032", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "His emotions 'kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display' are presented as", format: "single_best", options: ["pure and entirely sincere","suppressed and never felt at all","refined into a presentable display, drained of anything genuinely disturbing","unusually clear, transparent and easy for others to read, since he hides nothing of what he feels"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: decanted and de-sedimented, his emotions are refined into a presentable display, drained of anything genuinely disturbing. D is the elaborate trap, literalising 'clarified' into transparent and easy to read; A takes 'clarified' as sincerity; B overstates into emotions never felt at all.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-033", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That a comforted friend 'went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble' implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the friends came away genuinely comforted and grateful for so fine a sympathy", "the friends were ashamed of their own emotional weakness", "he would openly rebuke those who burdened him with real trouble", "his exquisite sympathy made real suffering feel a coarse intrusion on his refinement"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the shame springs from his manner, which makes real trouble seem coarse, so his sympathy makes suffering feel an intrusion on his refinement. A takes 'comforted' straight as gratitude; B relocates the cause to the friends' own weakness; C overstates into open rebuke.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-034", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In context, that he found 'the dying instructive' means he", format: "single_best", options: ["treated others' dying chiefly as material for his own edification","learned, from sitting with the dying, a great many practical facts about illness and the manner of its ending","comforted the dying by instructing them","found visiting the dying tedious"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: finding 'the dying instructive' treats their dying chiefly as material for his own edification. B is the elaborate trap, literalising 'instructive' into learning practical facts about illness; C reverses the direction into his instructing them; D contradicts his appetite for such scenes.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-035", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "He was a connoisseur of feeling in others, as some men are of wine, and could detect the first false note in a grief or a joy at fifty paces. His own emotions he kept decanted, clarified of any sediment that might cloud the display; and if he wept, which he did, beautifully, at the right passages, it was with the air of a man performing a duty owed to art rather than discharging any pressure of his own. The poor he found picturesque, the dying instructive, and a friend's catastrophe an occasion for the exercise of a sympathy so exquisitely calibrated that the friend, comforted, went away faintly ashamed of having brought so coarse a thing as real trouble into so fine a presence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's tone toward him is", format: "single_best", options: ["admiring of his refined sensibility","quietly mournful at the essential loneliness of so refined and feeling a man, misunderstood by a coarser world","neutral and merely descriptive","coolly satirical, dismantling his refinement as self-regard"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the precise mockery of 'so fine a presence' is coolly satirical, dismantling his refinement as self-regard. B is the elaborate trap, sentimentalising him into a lonely, misunderstood soul; A accepts the refined surface admiringly; C mistakes the sharp edge for neutral description.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-036", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is best read as", format: "single_best", options: ["a victim of unlucky timing in a competitive workplace","a man genuinely wronged by a friend who had burdened an ordinary professional courtesy with quite unreasonable expectations of loyalty","a man constructing, in real time, the excuses by which a betrayal is made to seem an accident","a scrupulous friend who agonised over a real dilemma"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the whole passage is the building of a defence, excuses constructed in real time to make a betrayal seem an accident. B is the elaborate trap, adopting his framing that the friend's expectations were unreasonable; A adopts another part of his framing (unlucky timing); D credits an agonising the breezy reasoning belies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-037", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Opening with 'betrayal is a strong word' is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["a concession","a euphemism","a refutation","a recantation"], answer: 1, explanation: "He reaches for a milder term to soften the deed before naming it, the move of a euphemism. A concession would grant a point against himself; a refutation would argue the charge false; a recantation would withdraw a view he once held, none of which he does.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-038", genre: "prose", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that 'confidences, surely, are not contracts' is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["a fair distinction that frees him of any real obligation to Marcus", "proof that Marcus had no business expecting his discretion", "a sign he had honestly misread the terms on which the secret was shared", "a self-serving equivocation that shrinks a moral duty into a merely legal one"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'confidences are not contracts' swaps the moral force of a confidence for the narrower notion of a legal contract, a self-serving equivocation. C is the near-twin, recasting the slide as an innocent misunderstanding; A and B accept the equivocation, as a fair distinction or as cancelling Marcus's claim to discretion.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-039", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "By 'accidents of timing' he recasts choices he made as mere", format: "single_best", options: ["volition","negligence","misfortune","happenstance"], answer: 3, explanation: "He dresses deliberate acts as chance, so happenstance. Negligence would still be a fault of his; misfortune makes it bad luck befalling him; volition (the will) is the very thing he is hiding, the opposite of accident.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-040", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It would be wrong to call what I did a betrayal; betrayal is a strong word, and the situation was more delicate than such words allow. Marcus had told me of the offer in confidence, yes, but confidences, surely, are not contracts; and when the same post was mentioned to me, was I to pretend ignorance, to perform a loyalty that would have helped no one and cost me everything? I said only what was true, and what they would have learned in any case. That I said it first, and that Marcus heard of my appointment before I had found the moment to tell him myself, are accidents of timing for which I can hardly be held to account.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's stance toward the narrator is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["warmly sympathetic to the genuine predicament of a man caught between loyalty and his own legitimate ambition","furiously condemnatory of his conduct","letting his own smooth reasoning expose the self-deception","genuinely undecided about his guilt"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage lets his own smooth reasoning expose the self-deception, the irony convicting him by his fluency. A is the elaborate trap, taking his predicament sympathetically at face value; B overstates into furious condemnation; D mistakes the irony for genuine indecision about his guilt.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-prose-041", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is chiefly concerned with", format: "single_best", options: ["how an elaborate courtesy can be the very medium of an unspoken rivalry","the buried grief that quietly draws two siblings together over a shared loss","a model of how an inheritance ought fairly to be shared","a quarrel over the monetary worth of a family estate"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the courtesy is the vehicle of the contest, civility as the medium of an unspoken rivalry. B is the twin, hearing shared grief where the scene runs on wariness ('watched the other like a cat'); the grief surfaces only as another front of the contest. C takes 'fairness' at face value; D contradicts 'of no value'.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-042", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'each of them watched the other like a cat' conveys", format: "single_best", options: ["the two were grieving too deeply to trust the lawyer", "under the show of fairness ran a wary competitiveness", "the siblings were already in open hostility", "each feared the other would cheat over money"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the simile sets watchfulness beneath the courtesy. C is the twin, hardening that quiet vigilance into open hostility, which the smiling surface belies. A and D misplace the wariness onto grief or the lawyer.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-043", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Robert's declining first choice 'so that the generosity might be his'", format: "single_best", options: ["shows Robert's genuine selflessness","indicates that Robert, out of simple courtesy and respect for his sister, was content to let Helen choose before him","proves Robert wanted nothing from the house","reveals that even the concessions were moves in a contest for the higher ground"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: declining first choice 'so that the generosity might be his' shows even the concessions were moves in a contest for the higher ground. B is the elaborate trap, taking the deference as simple courtesy; A takes the gesture as genuine selflessness; C overstates his disinterest into wanting nothing.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-044", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the division would seem to 'an observer... loving and a lawyer, prudent' implies", format: "single_best", options: ["that the division was at once perfectly sound in law and genuinely warm in feeling, a model of affectionate fairness between kin","that lawyers are more honest than ordinary observers","the same conduct could be read as love or as calculation, and the passage leans to calculation","the siblings needed legal advice to divide the house"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the doubled description, loving to an observer and prudent to a lawyer, shows the same conduct readable as love or calculation, and the passage leans to calculation. A is the elaborate trap, taking both labels straight as warm and lawful; B and D literalise 'lawyer' into honesty or a real need for legal advice.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-045", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Of the clock, 'Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it' indicates that", format: "single_best", options: ["both, with selfless tenderness, truly wished the other to keep the keepsake","neither sibling cared about the plain old clock at all","the courteous offer hid that each wanted the clock and would not say so","the clock was too valuable for either to give up"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'each said the other should have it; neither meant it' is courtesy masking that each wanted it but would not say so. A takes the offer as selfless; B contradicts that the clock 'carried her'; D contradicts 'of no value'.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-046", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The division was conducted with great fairness, which is to say that each of them watched the other like a cat. Helen offered Robert first choice, and Robert, who understood the offer, declined it, so that the generosity might be his; and they proceeded thus, conceding and re-conceding, each gift a small manoeuvre, until the modest house had been parcelled out in a spirit that an observer would have called loving and a lawyer, prudent. Only over the clock did the surface break: a plain thing, of no value, that their mother had wound on Sundays. Each said the other should have it. Neither meant it. And in the long, smiling deadlock over the one object that carried her, the whole of what they would not say to each other stood, at last, in the room.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing image, that 'the whole of what they would not say... stood, at last, in the room', chiefly", format: "single_best", options: ["renders their buried rivalry and grief wordlessly present without being spoken","shows the two siblings at last openly voicing the long-held grievances they had circled all evening","marks their reconciliation over a shared loss","introduces an outsider who breaks the deadlock"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the closing image renders their buried rivalry and grief wordlessly present, fully there yet still unspoken. B is the elaborate trap, having them finally voice their grievances, which 'would not say' denies; C sentimentalises into reconciliation; D invents an outsider who breaks the deadlock.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-001", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is primarily concerned to argue", format: "single_best", options: ["the worth of free speech lies in preserving the difference between genuine assent and mere compliance, not in the discovery of truth","the orthodox defence of free speech confuses the value of truth with the value of liberty","no right to speak can be founded on the speaker's being right without thereby ceasing to be a right","tolerating dissent is justified less by any good it produces than by what suppressing it would reveal about the one who suppresses"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the closing 'what we protect is the difference between agreement and submission' is the constructive thesis. D is the near-twin trap, a close paraphrase that shifts the emphasis onto the censor's self-exposure rather than 'what we protect'. B and C are critical steps toward the thesis mistaken for it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-002", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's charge against the truth-based defence is that it", format: "single_best", options: ["protects only the opinions that turn out true, and so secures nothing that needed protecting","ties the legitimacy of speech to a verdict on its content that cannot be returned until the speech has already been heard","treats the eventual triumph of truth in open contest as the normal outcome, when history shows it the rare exception","grants the censor the very authority it set out to deny, by allowing that proven error might rightly be silenced"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the objection is the timing-and-grounding circularity, legitimacy held hostage to a verdict that cannot be returned until after the speech. C is the elaborate trap (empirical scepticism about truth prevailing); A (redundancy) and D (reflexive self-undermining) are clever objections one could raise but not his.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-003", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's preferred ground for protecting speech?", format: "single_best", options: ["Many who are never silenced still submit to opinions they have not examined, so freedom alone secures no real assent.","One who is silenced may later, in freedom, arrive sincerely at the same view, so suppression need not foreclose genuine assent.","The censor often suppresses precisely the opinion he fears would persuade him.","Even under full freedom, the parties themselves can rarely tell being persuaded from being outmanoeuvred."], answer: 1, explanation: "B: if one who is silenced can later, in freedom, sincerely reach the same view, then suppression need not foreclose genuine assent, which undercuts 'the censor forfeits the only proof'. A attacks a stronger claim than the author makes (he never says freedom guarantees assent); C supports him, since a censor suppressing what he fears would persuade confirms the point; D challenges only whether the distinction can be known, not its value.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-004", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "'The difference between agreement and submission' is the distinction between", format: "single_best", options: ["assent freely given and compliance produced by force","private conviction and public conformity","being persuaded and being defeated in argument","believing a claim and merely obeying a command"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: agreement is assent freely given, submission is compliance produced by force, exactly the line the passage draws. C is the cruellest near-miss, since being 'defeated in argument' is still inside the rational contest, whereas submission is yielding to power; B (private vs public) and D (believing vs obeying) shift the contrast off the free-versus-forced axis.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-005", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In calling such a freedom 'not a freedom but a wager', the author is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["restating the view in plainer terms","conceding a key point to that view","offering a vivid analogy designed to lend further support to the very view he is in fact opposing","drawing out an unacceptable consequence of the view he opposes"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: calling the freedom 'a wager' draws out an unacceptable consequence of the truth-defence and rejects it, a reductio. C is the elaborate trap (a supporting analogy); A mistakes it for a plain restatement; B for a concession.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-006", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against censorship is usually made in the name of truth: suppress an opinion and you may suppress the correct one; permit all, and truth will win the open contest. But this defence concedes too much, for it rests the right to speak on the chance that the speaker is right, and would evaporate the moment we were certain he was wrong. A freedom that survives only while its outcome is in doubt is not a freedom but a wager. The sounder ground is that no one, having silenced another, can afterwards claim to have been persuaded by him: the censor forfeits not the truth, which may be on his side, but the only proof that his conviction was ever more than power. What we protect is not the speaker, nor even the truth, but the difference between agreement and submission.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best exemplifies what the author says we protect?", format: "single_best", options: ["a public debate, conducted in good faith, in which the prize goes to whichever argument turns out the most truthful","a censor who blocks a claim he privately fears is true","a state that permits a protest it is confident is mistaken, since silencing it would prove nothing","a voter who changes his mind after a persuasive speech"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: permitting a protest one is confident is mistaken preserves the agreement/submission distinction, exactly what the author says we protect. A is the trap, the rejected truth-defence (the prize to the truest argument); B is the censor he criticises; D is persuasion working, not the protection principle.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-007", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In allowing that, once the causes are laid bare, 'no room is left for blame', the author's move is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["a refutation","a concession","an extrapolation","a recantation"], answer: 1, explanation: "He grants the opponent's pull before resisting it, a concession. 'Recantation' (withdrawing a belief once held) is the obscure trap; he never held the view. 'Extrapolation' tempts but he is granting, not extending.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-008", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's view of the relation between the causal explanation of an act and the responsibility for it is that", format: "single_best", options: ["the explanation leaves responsibility open, and responsibility leaves the explanation open","the explanation settles responsibility, but responsibility leaves the explanation open","the explanation leaves responsibility open, but responsibility settles the explanation","the explanation settles responsibility, and responsibility settles the explanation"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'leaves wholly open the further question' means the explanation does not settle responsibility, and nothing lets responsibility settle the explanation, so the two are independent both ways. B and C each let one direction settle the other; D makes each settle the other, which the passage denies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-009", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one would the author most likely regard as committing the error he describes?", format: "single_best", options: ["a judge who, told of an offender's brutal childhood, records the conviction but shortens the sentence","a man who forgives a betrayal without asking why it happened","a scientist who refuses to study cruelty's origins for fear of seeming to excuse it","a historian who, having traced every cause of a massacre, concludes that none of those involved can be blamed"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the historian treats a full causal account as dissolving blame, exactly the error the passage names. A does the right thing (explains yet still convicts); B is forgiveness without any explanation, off the axis; C is the opposite error, refusing to explain for fear of excusing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-010", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of understanding as 'a solvent in which responsibility dissolves' casts explanation as something that threatens to ___ responsibility.", format: "single_best", options: ["exculpate","adumbrate","vitiate","reify"], answer: 2, explanation: "'Vitiate' (impair, nullify) fits 'dissolves'. 'Adumbrate' (foreshadow) is the obscure trap; 'exculpate' is the seductive near-miss, but one exculpates a person, not 'responsibility'; 'reify' is wrong.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-011", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The engineer who 'skimped on the steel' is introduced in order to", format: "single_best", options: ["concede that certain failures, being wholly the product of impersonal forces, cannot be judged in moral terms at all","contrast physical accidents with moral wrongs","qualify the claim that explanation never excuses","show that a full causal account can sit alongside undiminished responsibility"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: we know exactly why the bridge fell and still blame the engineer, so a complete causal account can coexist with full responsibility. A is the trap, conceding some failures escape moral judgement; B reverses the example's force (it draws a parallel, not a contrast); C misreads a supporting case as a qualification.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-012", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To explain an action is one thing; to excuse it is another, and the confusion of the two has muddled our moral talk more than any open defence of wickedness could. Learning why a man betrayed his friend, the debts, the fear, the slow corrosion of resentment, we are tempted to feel that, the causes once laid bare, no room is left for blame, as though understanding were a solvent in which responsibility dissolves. Yet we do not absolve the engineer who skimped on the steel merely because we can say, to the last bolt, why the bridge came down. The fullest account of how a thing came to pass leaves wholly open the further question whether the one who did it ought to have done otherwise; to treat the first question as having silently answered the second is not compassion but a failure of attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Calling the confusion 'not compassion but a failure of attention' implies that those who make it", format: "single_best", options: ["have not looked closely enough to see that two distinct questions are in play","are, at some level, being deliberately dishonest about their real motives for letting the wrongdoer off","are too kind for their own good","lack the knowledge needed to judge such cases"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'a failure of attention' locates the fault in not seeing that two distinct questions are in play. B is the trap, imputing deliberate dishonesty; C takes 'compassion' at face value as excess kindness; D blames missing knowledge rather than inattention.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-013", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The distinction between false and genuine humility turns ultimately on", format: "single_best", options: ["the sincerity of his self-deprecation","the degree of his self-deprecation","the words he chooses to describe himself","where the speaker's attention is directed"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the stated criterion is self-attention, genuine humility 'is not thinking about its own height'. C is ruled out by 'words may be identical'; B (degree) and A (sincerity) are the tempting near-misses, but the passage's line is attention, not how much one deprecates or how sincerely.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-014", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The argument depends on assuming that", format: "single_best", options: ["pride is always a vice and humility always a virtue","humble people are usually praised in the end","the same words can express opposite inner states","most displays of modesty are insincere"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the argument needs that identical words can express opposite inner states, since only then must inner orientation do the distinguishing. A (pride always a vice), B (the humble are praised) and D (most modesty is insincere) are never required by the argument.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-015", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage commits the author to which? I. False modesty seeks the praise it pretends to refuse. II. One cannot know whether one's own humility is genuine. III. Outward behaviour is an unreliable guide to humility.", format: "single_best", options: ["I only","I and III only","II and III only","I, II and III"], answer: 1, explanation: "I and III follow (the hook awaiting contradiction; behaviour 'may be identical', so it underdetermines). II is the overreach trap: the passage distinguishes the states, implying they are tellable apart.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-016", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The self-deprecation described is best characterised as", format: "single_best", options: ["captatory","obsequious","sycophantic","ingratiating"], answer: 0, explanation: "All four mean roughly favour-seeking. The act angles to elicit a specific compliment, which is captatory (rare: seeking to capture favour). 'Ingratiating' is the near-miss; obsequious and sycophantic point at flattering a superior, which he is not.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-017", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say genuine humility 'has left the room before the compliment arrives' means that it", format: "single_best", options: ["is too shy to remain present for praise","departs as soon as others begin to flatter it","deliberately and carefully avoids any situation in which it might be noticed and praised, keeping itself out of the light","is not present to itself as an object of regard, and so is not waiting for praise at all"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'left the room before the compliment arrives' figures self-forgetfulness, the humble mind not present to itself as an object of regard. C is the elaborate trap, making it deliberate avoidance, which is still self-aware; A and B make it social shyness or literal departure.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-018", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a modesty that is the subtlest form of pride. The man who insists, at every turn, on his own smallness has found a way to keep himself perpetually in view; his self-deprecation is a hook on which he hangs, waiting to be contradicted. We are meant to protest, and in protesting to supply the praise he was too delicate to claim. Genuine humility does not advertise its dimensions at all; it is not thinking about its own height. The difference is not in the words said, which may be identical, but in whether the speaker has left the room, so to speak, before the compliment arrives.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's attitude toward the falsely modest man is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["indignant and morally severe","gently sympathetic toward what is, after all, a fairly harmless and very human little vanity","wry and dryly perceptive, exposing a contradiction","detached and merely classificatory"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'the subtlest form of pride' is wry and dryly perceptive, exposing the contradiction in false modesty. B is the elaborate trap, excusing it as harmless vanity; A overstates the heat into indignation; D mistakes the pointed exposure for neutral classification.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-019", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main contention is", format: "single_best", options: ["whatever is natural is generally good and whatever is unnatural suspect","whether something is natural does not settle whether it is good, though a narrower caution can be salvaged","human beings ought, as a rule, not to interfere with natural systems they did not design and cannot fully understand","nature is, on the whole, crueller than human contrivance"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the passage both refutes the natural-good inference and salvages a narrower caution. C is the trap, the reverence the passage separates from caution; A is the view refuted; D overreads the examples into a verdict on nature.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-020", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The pairs 'disease... the vaccine' and 'cruelty between animals... the hospital' are offered to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["each pair sets a natural harm against an unnatural good, so naturalness cannot certify value","nature is, on the whole, a cruel system","medicine is in every respect superior to nature","human beings should never interfere with the natural processes that arose without their design"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: each pair sets a natural harm (disease, animal cruelty) against an unnatural good (vaccine, hospital), so naturalness cannot certify value. D is the trap, drawing the opposite practical moral (never interfere); B fastens on the cruelty half; C inflates it into medicine being superior in every respect.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-021", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The remark that 'caution is not reverence' draws a line between", format: "single_best", options: ["cowardice and genuine respect", "people who are careful and people who are careless", "prudent humility about what we do not understand and that nature holds moral authority", "the sceptical scientific mind and the reverent, tradition-honouring religious one"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: caution rests on our ignorance of complex systems, reverence on nature's supposed moral authority. D is the trap, broadening it into science versus religion; A misreads caution as mere cowardice; B reduces it to careful versus careless people.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-022", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the salvaged claim 'warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound' shows that the author's humility", format: "single_best", options: ["can be used to justify any conclusion at all","ultimately refutes itself on inspection","ultimately supports a quiet reverence for the natural order after all, once its caution is properly understood","tells against complacent traditionalism as much as against reckless innovation"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: a humility grounded in limited understanding distrusts complacent custom as much as reckless innovation, so it 'warns equally'. C is the trap, making it support reverence, which 'caution is not reverence' denies; A overstates into justifying any conclusion; B claims it refutes itself.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-023", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The sentence beginning 'What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower' chiefly functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["abandon the author's own position","trade the refuted inference for a weaker claim the author will defend","restate the opening claim in stronger terms","concede, in the end, that the appeal to nature had been substantially right all along, needing only minor qualification"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the sentence trades the refuted natural-good inference for a weaker caution the author endorses. D is the trap, reading the narrowing as conceding the appeal was right; A misreads it as abandoning his position; C inverts the move, since the replacement claim is weaker.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-024", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "That a thing is natural is constantly offered as a reason to prefer it, and that a thing is unnatural as a reason to distrust it; yet the inference, stated plainly, does not survive a moment's pressure. Disease is natural, and the vaccine that defeats it is not; cruelty between animals is natural, and the hospital is a human contrivance. If natural tracked good, we should have to praise the one and suspect the other, which no one proposes. What can be rescued from the appeal is narrower and worth keeping: not that the natural is good, but that systems we did not design and do not fully understand may fail in ways we cannot foresee, so that caution before altering them is prudent. But caution is not reverence; the same humility that warns against remaking an ecosystem warns equally against assuming that whatever is customary is therefore sound.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say the inference 'does not survive a moment's pressure' means that it", format: "single_best", options: ["collapses as soon as it is examined with any care","is offered far too quickly and glibly for the one making it to be entirely sincere about it","is rarely made by serious thinkers","depends on physical force to be accepted"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'does not survive a moment's pressure' reads 'pressure' as scrutiny, so the inference collapses on examination. B is the elaborate trap, making it about the speaker's insincere haste; C is about frequency; D literalises pressure as force.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-025", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central contention is", format: "single_best", options: ["consistency is only the agreement of beliefs with one another, no guarantee of truth, and can entrench error","consistency, the steady agreement of one's beliefs over time, is the single most important intellectual virtue and the surest mark of an honest mind","one should change one's views as often as possible","open-minded people are usually mistaken"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: consistency is mere internal agreement, no guarantee of truth, and can keep error in place. B is the trap, the view attacked (consistency the supreme virtue); D misreads the praise of open-mindedness; C mistakes answerability for restless changing of views.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-026", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The miser and the fanatic are cited to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["such people are unusually logical","inconsistency is always preferable to consistency","one can be perfectly consistent and yet wholly wrong, so consistency alone is no merit","a rigid insistence on consistency tends, over time, to harden ordinary conviction into outright fanaticism"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the miser and fanatic show flawless internal agreement with no contact with truth, so consistency alone is no merit. D is the trap, asserting an unclaimed causal link (consistency causes fanaticism); A flatters them as logical; B overstates the other way.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-027", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'something harder' the author would honour in place of consistency is", format: "single_best", options: ["the refusal ever to contradict oneself","holding one's beliefs answerable to the facts, and revising them when truth requires","defending a system that no fact can disturb","a ready willingness to change one's mind whenever challenged, so as never to be caught defending a losing position"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the 'something harder' is holding beliefs answerable to the facts and revising them when truth requires. D is the trap, mere instability dressed as open-mindedness; A and C are the rigidity the passage criticises.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-028", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs' means that genuine inquiry", format: "single_best", options: ["treats consistency as something worth sacrificing when the facts demand a change","values steady consistency above every other consideration, prizing it as the very foundation of a trustworthy mind","abandons consistency altogether as worthless","regards correction as too expensive to undertake"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'to pay, in the coin of consistency' makes consistency the price worth paying to get a correction right. B is the elaborate trap, inverting the priority; C overstates into abandoning consistency as worthless; D reverses the willingness to pay.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-029", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The argument assumes that", format: "single_best", options: ["consistency and truth never coincide","most people are inconsistent most of the time","fanatics, whatever they profess, are never really sincere in the rigid convictions they so loudly defend","beliefs can be evaluated against the world, not merely against one another"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the argument assumes beliefs can be checked against the world, which lets 'agreement with the world' outrank internal agreement. C is the trap (fanatics insincere), never needed; A overstates into consistency and truth never coinciding; B is not needed.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-030", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We prize consistency as if it were a kind of honesty, and call a man who changes his mind unreliable; but consistency is only the agreement of one's beliefs with one another, and has nothing necessarily to do with their agreement with the world. The miser is perfectly consistent, and so is the fanatic; each holds a tight, self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb. To prize consistency above all is therefore to make a virtue of the very rigidity that keeps error in place, for the mind that will not tolerate a contradiction is also the mind that will not admit a correction. What deserves the honour we give consistency is something harder: the readiness to hold one's beliefs answerable to what is the case, and to pay, in the coin of consistency, whatever a true correction costs.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "A 'self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb' is one that is", format: "single_best", options: ["admirably rigorous and well-defended","too complex for ordinary people to follow","internally coherent but sealed against correction","supported, in its defenders' eyes, by such overwhelming evidence that no objection could possibly shake it"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: a 'self-supporting system that no fact is allowed to disturb' is internally coherent but sealed against correction. D is the elaborate trap, reversing it into being evidence-backed; A takes it as a virtue (rigorous); B shifts to complexity.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-031", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main contention is that", format: "single_best", options: ["to tolerate a practice is really a disguised, softened way of endorsing it, a quiet blessing dressed up as mere permission","a society should forbid only those practices the majority dislikes","toleration presupposes disapproval, so it is the opposite of endorsement, though it can decay into indifference","indifference toward a disliked practice is preferable to forbidding it"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage holds both that toleration presupposes disapproval (so it is the opposite of endorsement) and that it can decay into indifference. A is the trap, the error it corrects (toleration as disguised endorsement); B is a policy rule never offered; D inverts the warning.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-032", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "'There is nothing to tolerate in what one approves' supports the idea that", format: "single_best", options: ["toleration is meaningful only when its object is something one objects to","approval and toleration are simply two names for one attitude","a genuinely tolerant person must remain studiously neutral, neither approving nor disapproving of whatever they allow","people seldom in fact approve of what they permit"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: if there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves, toleration is meaningful only when aimed at what one objects to. C is the trap, the neutrality the passage rejects; B collapses approval and toleration into one attitude; D is an empirical aside.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-033", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Toleration 'decays into mere indifference' when", format: "single_best", options: ["a society comes to approve the practice it once merely permitted","the state at last forbids the practice it had allowed","people grow steadily louder and more organised in their open condemnation of the very practice they continue to permit","the disapproval that toleration restrained gradually fades, leaving only the habit of permitting"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the restraint acts on nothing once the disapproval thins, leaving only the habit of permitting. C is the trap, since louder condemnation strengthens the disapproval, the opposite; A is a different end-state (approval); B is the opposite drift (prohibition).", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-034", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the passage's view, toleration is marked by which combination?", format: "single_best", options: ["approval present, objection absent","approval absent, objection absent","approval absent, objection present but restrained","approval present, objection present"], answer: 2, explanation: "Toleration = disapproval (objection) held in check, with no approval. A is endorsement-like; B is indifference; D is incoherent for this account.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-035", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which best illustrates the decay the author warns of?", format: "single_best", options: ["a town that bans a club it once allowed","a town that keeps allowing a practice but no longer remembers that anyone objected to it","a town that debates a practice heatedly each year","a town that, over the years, comes warmly to celebrate and take pride in the very practice it had once only grudgingly permitted"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: permission emptied of its lost disapproval is the decay the author warns of. D is the trap, the slide into approval, a different case; A is prohibition; C keeps the objection alive.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-036", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "To tolerate a practice is not to approve it; there is nothing to tolerate in what one approves. Toleration is disapproval held deliberately in check, and so it is the opposite of endorsement, not a disguised form of it. The confusion matters, because a society that forgets the difference will read every permission as a blessing, and then, offended, will move to forbid what it had merely allowed. Worse is the slow drift the other way: toleration can decay, by degrees, into mere indifference, the disapproval it once restrained thinning until nothing is left but the habit of permitting, and a people no longer recalls that it ever minded at all.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Describing toleration as disapproval 'held deliberately in check' implies the tolerant person", format: "single_best", options: ["continues to disapprove but restrains acting on it","has, through long familiarity, gradually ceased to disapprove of the practice at all","is genuinely indifferent to the practice","secretly approves of the practice"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: disapproval 'held deliberately in check' means the tolerant person keeps disapproving but restrains acting on it. B is the elaborate trap (no disapproval left, which is indifference); C also describes indifference; D describes secret endorsement.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-037", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's main point is that", format: "single_best", options: ["sharp criticism is, after all, a markedly more effective teaching tool than praise, since performance reliably improves after a scolding","the swings after praise and criticism are mostly regression to the cadet's average, not evidence about feedback","luck plays no real part in a cadet's performance","flight instructors should give cadets less feedback"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the swings are regression toward the cadet's average, a statistical artefact, not evidence about feedback. A is the trap, the instructor's mistaken conclusion (criticism works, praise spoils); C denies the luck the argument relies on; D adds advice the passage never gives.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-038", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The pattern would appear 'even if his words made no difference' because", format: "single_best", options: ["extreme landings are partly luck and tend to be followed by more average ones whatever the instructor says","praise and criticism happen to cancel out","the cadets pay no attention to whatever the instructor says","the instructor records the cadets' landings too inaccurately for any real effect of his feedback to show up"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: regression to the mean, extreme performances are partly luck and tend to be followed by more average ones. D is the trap, blaming measurement, but the effect is in real, fluctuating performance; C posits inattention; B misdescribes the mechanism.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-039", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The instructor's central error is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["praising cadets too rarely","mistaking a natural return toward average for the power of his own words","failing to keep the kind of proper, systematic records that would have revealed the true pattern","being harsher than he ought to be"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: he reads a natural return toward average as the power of his words, a regression effect taken as causal. C is the trap (poor records); A and D concern frequency or manner, not the inference.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-040", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most undermine the passage's explanation?", format: "single_best", options: ["over many later flights, the praised cadets improved far more than the scolded ones","cadets vary in natural talent","good and bad landings occur in roughly equal numbers","luck affects the outcome of a landing very much more powerfully than the instructor has ever been willing to believe"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: a controlled comparison showing praised cadets improve more is a real feedback effect the regression story denies. D is the trap, but more luck only strengthens the regression account; B and C are compatible with it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-041", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which everyday case shares the instructor's error?", format: "single_best", options: ["a gardener who waters plants and finds they grow","a coach who rests injured players and sees them heal","a student who deliberately studies a great deal more before an examination and goes on to score considerably higher","a patient who credits a remedy taken at his sickest for the recovery that followed"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the sickest moment is an extreme, so recovery (regression) tends to follow regardless of the remedy, the same artefact. C is the trap, but more study is a plausible genuine cause, not regression; A and B likewise involve real causes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-042", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "An instructor noticed that when he praised a cadet for an excellent landing, the next was usually worse, and when he scolded one for a poor landing, the next was usually better; from which he concluded that criticism works and praise spoils. But the pattern would appear even if his words made no difference at all. An unusually good landing is partly luck, and luck does not persist; the next attempt tends to fall back toward the cadet's ordinary level, praise or no praise. The same return, upward, follows a dismal landing. The instructor had mistaken a statistical tide for the effect of his own voice.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The metaphor 'a statistical tide' names", format: "single_best", options: ["the influence of the instructor's tone on morale","the gradual and genuine improvement of the cadets' skill over the full length of the training course as they learn","the natural ebb and flow of performance around an average, independent of his intervention","the random errors made in recording scores"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the 'statistical tide' is the natural ebb and flow of performance around an average, independent of his intervention. B is the elaborate trap, reading it as real learning over the course; A credits his tone; D reduces it to recording errors.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-043", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central point is that", format: "single_best", options: ["the charity is, in all likelihood, quietly exaggerating or selectively reporting its results", "without a comparison group the ninety per cent figure cannot show the charity caused the recovery", "ninety per cent is too low a rate to be impressive", "charities should not report statistics to donors"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: with no baseline, the figure cannot be credited to the charity. A is the trap, alleging exaggeration the passage avoids; C misjudges the issue; D is a broader rule than the argument supports.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-044", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that 'a number is not an argument' chiefly means that a statistic", format: "single_best", options: ["is, more often than not, quietly fabricated or massaged precisely in order to persuade the unwary","is less convincing than a vivid example","establishes nothing until it is set against the right comparison","should never be trusted on its own"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'a number is not an argument' means a statistic establishes nothing until set against the right comparison. A is the trap, imputing fabrication; B changes the subject to vivid examples; D overstates into blanket distrust.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-045", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The figure is 'a figure in search of a meaning' because", format: "single_best", options: ["the charity has probably inflated or selectively reported it","without the recovery rate of comparable families left unaided, it cannot be credited to the charity","ninety per cent sounds impressive but is too vague a figure to act on","a bare statistical percentage can never really capture the human reality behind each of the cases it counts"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: without the recovery rate of comparable families left unaided, the figure cannot be credited to the charity. D is the trap, a general complaint that percentages miss human reality, not this specific omission; A imputes dishonesty; C mistakes vagueness for the gap.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-046", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most undermine the charity's implied claim of success?", format: "single_best", options: ["most families said they were grateful for the help","the charity helped more families this year than last","a certain number of the families helped slipped back into the very same crisis again within two or three years","families in the same crisis who received no help recovered within a year at about the same rate"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: a matched no-help group recovering at about the same rate supplies the missing baseline and erases the charity's apparent effect. C is the trap, but later relapse does not bear on whether the help caused the initial recovery; A and B likewise do not.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-047", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which argument commits the same omission the passage identifies?", format: "single_best", options: ["a shop that claims its prices are the very lowest in town and prints a long list of them in proof","a tutor who boasts that most of his students pass, without saying how many would have passed anyway","a doctor who reports the exact dose she prescribed","a school that publishes the names of its prize-winners"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the tutor claims success while omitting how many would have passed anyway, exactly the missing no-treatment comparison. A is the trap, a checkable claim with no causal-success boast a baseline would test; C and D make no causal success claim at all.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-048", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "A charity reports that ninety per cent of the families it helps are out of crisis within a year, and invites us to admire the result. But a number is not an argument. We are told nothing of how many families in the same straits, given no help at all, would also have recovered within a year, as many do, by the ordinary action of time and circumstance. Without that comparison the ninety per cent floats free: it may record a triumph, or merely the rate at which such crises pass on their own. It is a figure in search of a meaning, and the meaning lies precisely in the comparison the report omits.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say the ninety per cent 'floats free' is to say it", format: "single_best", options: ["lacks the anchor of comparison that would give it significance","is suspiciously round and smooth, the kind of figure that is far more often invented than carefully measured","changes from year to year","is too high to be believable"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'floats free' means the figure is unmoored from the comparison that would give it significance. B is the elaborate trap, reading it as a round, invented number; C reads it as year-to-year variation; D as too high to believe.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-049", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The thrust of the passage is that", format: "single_best", options: ["the successful do not really deserve their success","people should not argue about what others deserve","the dispute persists because the two parties use 'deserve' in different senses, each true on its own terms","worldly success is, when one looks closely, mostly a matter of luck and circumstance rather than of genuine effort or merit"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the quarrel persists because the parties use 'deserve' in two different senses, each true on its own terms, an equivocation. D is the trap, taking a side (success is mostly luck); A takes the other side; B draws an unstated recommendation.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-050", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The two senses of 'deserve' the passage distinguishes are", format: "single_best", options: ["one expressed sincerely and one expressed with cynicism","one concerned with wealth and one with social standing","one credited to the effort a person made, and one questioning whether the conditions for that effort were themselves earned","one grounded in the formal entitlements recognised by law, the other in the deeper and less codified demands of morality"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the two senses are desert credited to the effort a person made, and desert that questions whether the conditions for that effort were themselves earned. D is the trap, a legal-versus-moral distinction the passage never makes; A treats the sides as sincere versus cynical, though both are 'right'; B narrows the rewards to wealth versus status.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-051", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Describing the quarrel as 'not a disagreement so much as a collision' implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the parties are not contradicting each other but using one word for two things, so they talk past one another","the dispute has grown unusually bitter and personal, the two no longer able to discuss the matter calmly or in good faith","one of the two sides must be lying","the question of desert has no possible answer"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: a 'collision' marks claims that never meet, the parties using one word for two things. B is the trap, reading it as mere heat; C ignores that both are right; D overstates into unanswerability.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-052", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the passage's view, the quarrel would end if", format: "single_best", options: ["one of the two sides, after long argument, finally broke down and admitted that it had been wrong all along","the parties distinguished the two senses and saw that both claims can hold at once","they agreed that success is undeserved","they agreed that success is fully deserved"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: distinguishing the two senses dissolves the collision, since both claims can then hold at once. A is the trap, presuming one side is simply wrong; C and D each pick a side the passage shows is only half-right.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-053", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which exchange shares the structure the passage describes?", format: "single_best", options: ["two people who dispute whether a coin has been secretly weighted, and settle the matter by carefully testing it many times","two people who argue over the result of a coin toss they both saw","two people who agree a coin toss is fair and move on","two people who argue whether a coin toss is 'random', one meaning unpredictable to us, the other meaning uncaused"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'random' is split into two senses (unpredictable to us versus uncaused), the same equivocation. A is the trap, a factual dispute settled by testing, not an equivocation; B and C are likewise factual.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-054", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two people quarrel over whether the successful deserve their success, and never touch, because each means a different thing by the word. One asks whether they worked, chose well, and bore the risk, and answers, rightly, that many did. The other asks whether they earned the advantages that made the working possible, the health, the schooling, the steady home, and answers, also rightly, that no one earns the conditions of his own effort. It is not a disagreement so much as a collision: two true things said past each other. The word deserve has quietly split in two, and the dispute will last exactly as long as no one notices.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the word 'has quietly split in two' means that it", format: "single_best", options: ["has fallen out of common use","has become a term of abuse","now carries two distinct meanings the disputants have not separated","no longer carries any single definite meaning at all, having dissolved into vagueness through long overuse"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'split in two' means the word now carries two distinct meanings the disputants have not separated. D is the elaborate trap, overstating into the word meaning nothing definite, when each sense is definite; A reads it as falling out of use; B as a term of abuse.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-sb-055", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim is that", format: "single_best", options: ["official accident reports are, more often than people suppose, simply inaccurate or incomplete about what actually happened","naming one necessary condition 'the cause' reflects our interests and where blame should fall, not a bare fact about the event","fires have too many causes to be explained at all","the frayed wire, not the oxygen, is the true cause of the fire"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: selecting one necessary condition as 'the cause' reflects our interests and where blame should fall, not a bare fact. A is the trap, but the report is selective, not inaccurate; C treats selection as impossibility; D asserts the very privileging the passage calls a choice.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-056", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Treating the oxygen as a 'mere condition' is used to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["oxygen matters less to a fire than the wire does","fires are physically too complex to understand","oxygen and wire are equally necessary, so calling one 'the cause' is a line we draw, not a fact","official accident reports deliberately omit the important contributing facts that would otherwise spread the blame more widely"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: oxygen and wire are equally necessary, so calling one the cause is a line we draw, not a fact. D is the trap, alleging deliberate omission the passage does not claim; A accepts the ranking; B overstates into fires being unintelligible.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-057", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the owner and the electricians each find their cause 'with perfect sincerity' most strongly implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["one of them must be lying about the fire","their disagreement concerns nothing real","the perfect sincerity of each party is itself a guarantee that the causal judgement he has reached must be correct","people can honestly select different causes because each fixes on the condition that suits a prior interest"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: equal sincerity with opposite conclusions shows the selection is shaped by prior interest. C is the trap, confusing sincerity with accuracy; A contradicts 'perfect sincerity'; B denies the disagreement is about anything real.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-058", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing claim that the search for causes is 'a search for the responsible' means that", format: "single_best", options: ["blame and moral judgement have no legitimate place at all in an honest, properly objective report of what caused an event","we tend to designate as the cause the condition someone could and should have changed","looking for causes is a waste of effort","the responsible party is always, in fact, the true cause"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: 'a search for the responsible' means we pick as the cause the condition someone could and should have changed. A is the trap, overstating into blame having no place in honest reports; C does not follow; D collapses the selection/fact distinction.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-059", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which best illustrates the passage's point?", format: "single_best", options: ["after a crash, investigators carefully measure the skid marks and road conditions and record every physical detail with precision","after a crash, two witnesses give identical accounts of what happened","after a crash, the driver blames the road and the council blames the driver, each citing a genuine factor","after a crash, the cause is found to be a sudden tyre failure"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: driver and council each blame the factor that points away from themselves, interested selection among real conditions. A is the trap, mere measurement; B is agreement among witnesses; D simply names a cause without the selection problem.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-sb-060", genre: "social_behavioural", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-sb-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ask why the warehouse burned and you will be told: a frayed wire. But the fire needed the wire, the oxygen, the stacked paper, the absent sprinkler, and a hundred conditions besides, each as necessary as the next. To call one of them the cause and the rest mere conditions is not to report a fact about the fire but to make a choice, and the choice is governed by where we think the remedy, and the blame, should fall. The owner names the wiring; the electricians name the storage; each, with perfect sincerity, finds the cause that points away from himself. The search for causes is already, half secretly, a search for the responsible.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say the search is 'half secretly' a search for the responsible means the link to blame is", format: "single_best", options: ["present and operative, though not consciously acknowledged","openly admitted by everyone involved","deliberately and knowingly concealed by those involved in order to deceive the people who read the report","imaginary and without real effect"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'half secretly' means the link to blame is present and operative though not consciously acknowledged. C is the elaborate trap, imputing deliberate concealment to deceive; B makes it openly admitted; D denies it has any real effect.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-001", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group: 18-29 reads 12, 30-44 reads 9, 45-59 reads 11, 60+ reads 15.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "Which comparison between the groups is best supported by the chart?", format: "single_best", options: ["reading declines steadily as age rises across the four groups", "the oldest group reads roughly double what the youngest group reads", "the youngest group reads more than any of the other three groups", "the youngest and oldest groups each read more than either middle group"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the end bars (12 and 15) both stand above the middle two (9 and 11). A imposes a steady decline, but the values dip then rise; B over-reads 15 against 12 as roughly double; C is false, since the 60+ mean of 15 tops the youngest group's 12.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-002", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group: 18-29 reads 12, 30-44 reads 9, 45-59 reads 11, 60+ reads 15.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "Across the four groups, the pattern of reading is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["a steady, continuous decline in reading as the age of the group increases","lowest in the middle groups and higher at both ends","a steady rise as age increases","a single dip at 30-44, with the other three groups about equal"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the values run 12, 9, 11, 15, dipping at 30-44 then climbing, so both ends sit above the middle. D is the near-miss, but the other three are not about equal (the 60+ mean of 15 clearly tops 12 and 11); A imposes a steady decline and C a steady rise, neither matching the dip-then-rise.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-003", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group: 18-29 reads 12, 30-44 reads 9, 45-59 reads 11, 60+ reads 15.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "The chart gives each group's mean but not the spread within it, so the chart cannot tell us", format: "single_best", options: ["which single one of the four age groups recorded the very highest mean number of books read in the year","whether some people in the youngest group read more than some in the oldest","the rank order of the four age groups from most to least","how far the 60+ mean exceeds the 30-44 mean in books"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: a mean hides the spread within each group, so whether some 18-29 readers out-read some 60+ readers cannot be told. A is the elaborate trap, the highest mean, which can be read straight off; C (rank order) and D (the gap) can likewise be read off the bars.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-004", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group, a single snapshot in time.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "Which conclusion does the chart, on its own, actually support?", format: "single_best", options: ["people come to read more as they grow older","reading keeps older people mentally active","the 30-44 group has the least free time for reading","in this sample, the 60+ group reported the highest mean"], answer: 3, explanation: "D is all a single snapshot licenses: in this sample the 60+ bar is highest. A reads a longitudinal trend into cross-sectional data (different cohorts, not the same people ageing); B and C import causes (mental activity, free time) the chart never measures.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-005", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "svg", content: "<svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 230\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" role=\"img\"><text x=\"200\" y=\"16\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">Mean books read per year, by age group</text><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"50\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><line x1=\"50\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"370\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#0a1628\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/><text x=\"44\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">16</text><text x=\"44\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"end\" fill=\"#33415c\">0</text><rect x=\"70\" y=\"70\" width=\"55\" height=\"120\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"97\" y=\"64\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">12</text><text x=\"97\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">18-29</text><rect x=\"150\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"90\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"177\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">9</text><text x=\"177\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">30-44</text><rect x=\"230\" y=\"80\" width=\"55\" height=\"110\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"257\" y=\"74\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">11</text><text x=\"257\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">45-59</text><rect x=\"310\" y=\"40\" width=\"55\" height=\"150\" fill=\"#0ea5e9\"/><text x=\"337\" y=\"34\" font-size=\"11\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#0a1628\">15</text><text x=\"337\" y=\"204\" font-size=\"10\" text-anchor=\"middle\" fill=\"#33415c\">60+</text></svg>", alt: "Bar chart of mean books read per year by age group, measured once.", attribution: "Original data figure" }, stem: "To decide whether people come to read more as they age, one would most need", format: "single_best", options: ["a much larger number of people sampled in each age group","the same people followed and measured repeatedly as they grow older","the median rather than the mean, calculated within each age group","data on which genres each group prefers"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: only following the same people over time can show change with age. C is the near-miss, swapping median for mean within the same one-off snapshot, which still cannot show change; A merely enlarges the sample; D adds genre data, neither addressing the cohort problem.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-006", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Table: 420 surveyed at the north end (beside the on-ramp) gave 62% support; 1180 at the south end gave 41% support.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "Taking both samples together, those who support the bridge are", format: "single_best", options: ["exactly half of those surveyed","a clear majority of the total surveyed","a minority of the total surveyed","impossible to estimate from the table"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: about 260 of 420 in the north and 484 of 1180 in the south support it, roughly 744 of 1600, just under half, so supporters are a minority overall. A misreads it as an even split; B as a majority; D denies an estimate the two rows in fact allow.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-007", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Table showing northern respondents were surveyed beside the proposed on-ramp.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "That the northern respondents were surveyed 'beside the proposed on-ramp' most undermines confidence in", format: "single_best", options: ["the southern figure of 41% support","the northern figure of 62% support","the total number of respondents across the two sites","the impartiality of those who commissioned the survey"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: surveying beside the on-ramp gathers the very people who would gain from the bridge, so the northern 62% is inflated and least trustworthy. A is untouched, since the southern site has no tie to the ramp; C is a plain count bias cannot distort; D is the tempting over-reading, treating a sampling flaw as a question of the surveyors' honesty, which the table does not raise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-008", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Bridge survey table, north 62% support, south 41% support.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "A headline reading 'Most locals back the bridge' would be misleading chiefly because", format: "single_best", options: ["once the two sites are weighted by their size, a majority of locals in fact oppose the bridge","the 62% figure comes from the site whose residents would most directly benefit from it","it applies 'most' to one site's result rather than to the surveyed population as a whole","it lets those polled beside the ramp stand in for residents the survey never reached"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: weight the 62% of 420 against the 41% of 1180 and the combined result is majority opposition, so 'most back it' states the reverse of the truth, the chief fault. C is the near-miss, the scoping error that produces the mistake, but the headline misleads because the corrected total flips, not merely because 'most' was loosely applied. B names a reason the 62% is unreliable rather than why the total inverts; D raises a coverage gap the table does not quantify.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-009", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Bridge survey table by location.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "Which statement is best supported by the table?", format: "single_best", options: ["the survey was deliberately rigged","the bridge would do real harm to the south","that residents living in the north are, on the whole, considerably better informed about the bridge proposal than those in the south","opposition to the bridge is greater among those surveyed away from the on-ramp"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the southern site, away from the ramp, opposes at 59% against the north's 38%, so opposition is higher away from the on-ramp. C is the elaborate trap, inventing a difference in how well-informed each group is; A leaps to deliberate rigging; B infers real harm the figures do not establish.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-010", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>Support for a proposed bridge, by where respondents were surveyed.</p><table><caption>Bridge survey results</caption><thead><tr><th>Survey site</th><th>Respondents</th><th>Support</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>North end (beside the proposed on-ramp)</td><td>420</td><td>62%</td></tr><tr><td>South end</td><td>1180</td><td>41%</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Bridge survey table by location.", attribution: "Original data table" }, stem: "To gauge genuine local opinion, the most important change would be to", format: "single_best", options: ["discard the larger southern sample altogether, on the ground that its sheer size unfairly swamps the northern voice","poll a larger number of people at the on-ramp site itself","sample both areas at sites unconnected to the bridge, in proportion to population","restrict the survey to those who say they intend to use the bridge"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: representativeness needs neutral locations and weighting by population. A is the elaborate trap, throwing away the larger, more representative sample; B intensifies the on-ramp bias; D narrows to an interested group.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-graphic-011", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Table: a clan-A man marries a clan-B woman and their children are clan C; B marries A, children D; C marries D, children A; D marries C, children B.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "Which one of the following must be true in the Garu system?", format: "single_best", options: ["a woman belongs to the same clan as her own children","a woman belongs to a different clan from her own children","a brother and a sister belong to different clans","a husband and a wife belong to the same clan"], answer: 1, explanation: "A child's clan is set by the father, and a mother's clan never matches it: a clan-B woman's children are C, a clan-A woman's are D, and so on. Siblings share their father's clan, and spouses are always of different clans, so the other three are false.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-012", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Garu clan marriage and descent table.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "A man's grandson (his son's son) belongs to the same clan as", format: "single_best", options: ["the man himself","the man's son","the man's wife","no one else in the family"], answer: 0, explanation: "A man of A has a son of C, whose son (a clan-C man's child) is clan A again, the grandfather's clan. The son is C, the wife B, so neither matches.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-013", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Garu clan marriage and descent table.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "Which one of the following is NOT possible in the Garu system?", format: "single_best", options: ["a grandfather and his grandson belonging to the same clan","two siblings belonging to the same clan","a husband and a wife belonging to different clans","a father and his son belonging to the same clan"], answer: 3, explanation: "No clan's children are its own (A gives C, C gives A, B gives D, D gives B), so a father and son can never share a clan. A grandfather and grandson do share one (A to C to A); spouses always differ; siblings always match.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-014", genre: "graphic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Garu clan marriage and descent table.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "In this system, marriage and descent are such that", format: "single_best", options: ["a man shares a clan with his own children, but he and his son's children belong to two quite different clans","a man, his children and his grandchildren all share one clan","a man and his children belong to different clans, but he and his son's children share a clan","all four clans may intermarry without restriction"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: a man of A has children of C (different) but son's-children of A (same). A is the elaborate trap, reversing the pattern, since it is the children, not the grandchildren, who differ; B erases the generational shift; D denies the fixed marriage rule.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-graphic-015", genre: "graphic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-graphic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "html", content: "<p>In the Garu kinship system there are four clans (A, B, C, D). A man of a given clan must marry a woman of a fixed clan, and their children belong to a third clan, as the table shows.</p><table><caption>Garu marriage and descent</caption><thead><tr><th>Man's clan</th><th>Marries a woman of clan</th><th>Children belong to clan</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A</td><td>B</td><td>C</td></tr><tr><td>B</td><td>A</td><td>D</td></tr><tr><td>C</td><td>D</td><td>A</td></tr><tr><td>D</td><td>C</td><td>B</td></tr></tbody></table>", alt: "Garu clan marriage and descent table.", attribution: "Original diagram" }, stem: "A child of clan A whose father is of clan C has a mother of clan", format: "single_best", options: ["C","D","A","B"], answer: 1, explanation: "A clan-C man marries a clan-D woman (row C), and their children are clan A, so the mother is clan D.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-testing-001", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Centrally, the passage claims that", format: "single_best", options: ["the marks by which we recognise competence can be counterfeited, so expert authority can never rationally be trusted","in a world too large to know firsthand, adopting the view experts agree on is the layman's only responsible course","since identifying a trustworthy expert itself takes expertise, deference simply collapses into the independent judgement it was meant to replace","choosing whom to defer to, far from sparing us judgement, calls on the very competence it appears to let us do without"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the close calls deference 'one of judgement's hardest exercises', a demanding use of judgement, not a holiday from it. C is the near-twin trap, saying deference collapses into judgement (one thing), where the passage keeps it a hard species of judgement, still distinct from judging firsthand. B is the 'chorus of agreement' the passage warns a charlatan can join, dressed up as prudence. A freezes the middle step (signs can be faked) into a blanket scepticism the passage never reaches.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-002", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'difficulty it cannot itself resolve' is that", format: "single_best", options: ["to pick trustworthy experts the layman would need the very competence whose absence is what sent him to experts in the first place","the outward marks of authority, manner, credential, consensus, are precisely the marks an impostor can counterfeit","experts within one field routinely contradict each other, leaving the layman no settled view to adopt","the advice to defer is sound in a world too large to know firsthand, yet it comes with no guarantee attached"], answer: 0, explanation: "A names the self-undermining loop: selecting good experts needs the competence the layman is defined as lacking. B is true and lifted straight from the passage, but it is the symptom (why the signs fail), not the structural difficulty. C is a real but different hazard (experts disagreeing) the passage never raises. D recasts the opening concession that the advice is 'sound' as if it were the problem.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-003", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The point of listing 'the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement' is that these signs", format: "single_best", options: ["are the outward marks the layman is thrown back on once direct assessment of competence is beyond him", "can be worn by the impostor as convincingly as by the master, so they cannot sort one from the other", "explain why incompetent authorities so regularly win the public's confidence", "ought to be discounted by the layman in favour of some surer sign of real competence"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the passage's point is that the charlatan can 'wear' the very signs the master earns, so the marks fail to separate them. A is true (he is indeed thrown back on these signs) but states their role rather than the point being pressed about them, that they do not discriminate. C asserts a consequence (why frauds prosper) the passage does not claim; D invents a surer route it never offers.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-004", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In calling deference 'one of [judgement's] hardest exercises', the author means that", format: "single_best", options: ["deference and independent judgement, once the difficulty is faced, prove to be the same activity under two names","choosing an authority well draws on more independent judgement, not less, and never its surrender","because judging experts is so hard, the layman does best to judge less and lean on the consensus more","the work of judgement is finished the moment a genuine expert has been correctly identified"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: a 'hardest exercise' of judgement is still an exercise of it, more judgement, not its handover. A is the near-twin trap, collapsing deference and judgement into one thing, where the passage keeps deference a hard species of judgement. C inverts the moral into leaning on the 'chorus' a charlatan can join; D makes judgement redundant once an expert is found, the opposite of the claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-005", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's worry?", format: "single_best", options: ["experts, judged within the bounds of their own fields, prove right far more often than they are ever wrong","public, outcome-based track records let a layman gauge who is competent without himself sharing the expertise","in practice laymen already defer, most of the time, to the right authorities","genuine charlatans are a good deal rarer than the passage's anxious tone implies"], answer: 1, explanation: "B supplies exactly what the worry calls impossible, a way to judge competence without first being an expert, which dissolves the loop. A leaves the selection problem intact (being right is no help if you cannot tell who is right). C says the problem seldom bites without showing how the layman sorts the cases; D shrinks the danger without giving him any means to tell fraud from master.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-006", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are told to defer to the experts, and in a world too large to know firsthand the advice is sound; yet it conceals a difficulty it cannot itself resolve. To know which experts to trust, one must already know enough to tell the competent from the confident, the discipline from its counterfeit, and that knowledge is precisely what the layman, by hypothesis, lacks. He is asked to choose his authorities by a judgement he is not equipped to make, and so must fall back on signs, the manner, the credential, the chorus of agreement, that the charlatan can wear as easily as the master. Deference is not the opposite of independent judgement; it is one of its hardest exercises.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To tell 'the discipline from its counterfeit' is to distinguish", format: "single_best", options: ["a genuinely rigorous and demanding field of study from one that is slack, soft and undemanding by comparison","an established field of expertise from a sham one dressed in its trappings","a scrupulous practitioner from an unscrupulous one","a mature, settled science from one still finding its feet"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: 'discipline' here is a field of expertise and 'counterfeit' a sham field wearing its forms. A is the elaborate trap, reading 'discipline' as rigour; C shifts from a field to a person's honesty; D reads 'counterfeit' as merely immature.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-testing-007", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central contention is that", format: "single_best", options: ["moral luck is real: chance does help fix how blameworthy we are, and the law is right to track it", "two drivers alike in all they controlled are judged very differently for an outcome neither governed", "the law plainly errs in letting the outcome, not the drivers' choices, decide how harshly each is punished", "our discomfort shows that we never really believed we are answerable only for what we control"], answer: 1, explanation: "B keeps both horns standing: the passage stresses that every resolution 'wounds a conviction we are reluctant to give up'. A and C each seize one horn and settle it (luck counts; or the law is unjust), the move the passage refuses. D reads our unease as proof we never held the control principle, but the passage says we hold it still and are reluctant to give it up.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-008", genre: "testing", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The dilemma the passage poses is that", format: "single_best", options: ["either the diverging outcomes reveal some hidden difference between the two men after all, or the law that parts them has simply blundered","either we give up the principle that we answer only for what we control, or we give up punishing by outcomes, and we are loath to drop either","either both drivers are equally guilty or both are equally innocent, and we cannot say which","either luck is a fiction we should stop invoking, or it governs far more of life than we care to admit"], answer: 1, explanation: "B reproduces the two horns the passage draws: grant luck moral weight and the control principle falls; deny it and the outcome-based punishment is unjust, yet we cling to both. A is the twin trap, smuggling in a 'hidden difference' the passage rules out by stipulating identical carelessness. C flattens the dilemma to a verdict on guilt; D swaps in a general claim about luck.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-009", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The principle 'that we are answerable only for what we govern' means that", format: "single_best", options: ["that responsibility reaches exactly as far as our control, and no further","that we ought to govern our appetites a good deal more strictly than we do","that only a governing authority is entitled to assign blame at all","that we are accountable for every consequence our actions set in motion"], answer: 0, explanation: "A reads 'govern' as control: we answer for what we command, not for what chance adds. B turns it into a counsel of self-discipline; C literalises 'govern' into government; D is the contrary principle, accountability for all effects, the very thing the unlucky driver's case strains.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-010", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The conviction the case is said to threaten is", format: "single_best", options: ["the belief that, taken as a whole, the law gets cases of this kind broadly right","the assumption that the law's treatment of like cases is internally consistent","the comforting idea that luck plays little real part in how our lives turn out","the principle that we are answerable for no more than what we control"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: both horns 'wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up', and that conviction is the control principle. C is genuinely unsettled by the case but is not the belief said to be at stake. B names a value the second horn leans on (consistency), not the conviction both horns wound. A sounds plausible, but the worry is sharper than the law erring in general: it is that responsibility-tracks-control cannot survive either answer.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-011", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which pair best parallels the two drivers?", format: "single_best", options: ["a careful surgeon whose patient recovers and a careless one whose patient dies","two equally careless surgeons, both of whose patients happen to pull through","two surgeons of unequal skill whose patients fare accordingly","two equally negligent surgeons, only one of whose patients happens to die"], answer: 3, explanation: "D matches the structure exactly: identical negligence, outcomes parted by chance. B holds the negligence equal but lets both escape harm, so it loses the very split, one killed and one merely lucky, that makes the puzzle. A and C make the difference earned (different care or skill), not lucky.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-012", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drink the same amount and drive the same road home; one arrives without event, the other, identically careless, meets a child who has wandered into the street, and kills her. We punish the second far more harshly, and call the first merely lucky, though nothing within their control distinguished them. Either luck makes a moral difference, which offends the principle that we are answerable only for what we govern; or it makes none, and the law that treats them so differently is unjust. The case is uncomfortable precisely because both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'both horns wound a conviction we are reluctant to give up' means", format: "single_best", options: ["that both lines of argument are, in the end, equally convincing","that the dilemma has a solution we are merely reluctant to accept","that each of the two available conclusions costs us a belief we would rather keep","that neither conclusion can really be true, since both of them do damage"], answer: 2, explanation: "C reads the metaphor: a dilemma's two 'horns' both gore, so whichever conclusion we take, a cherished belief is injured. A confuses being wounding with being persuasive; B smuggles in an available solution the passage denies; D treats the damage as proof both are false, which does not follow.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-testing-013", genre: "testing", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The uncle's forgiveness is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["a moving and entirely sincere release of a long-held grievance","a coldly calculated deception, carefully staged before the whole family in order to mislead them about his true feelings","an act suspended between a real letting-go and a costless performance of magnanimity","the muddled gesture of a mind failing at the close of life"], answer: 2, explanation: "C holds the ambiguity the passage will not resolve: genuine release or a display that concedes nothing. B is the elaborate trap, hardening the doubt into proven fraud; A takes only the generous reading; D explains the act away as senility.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-014", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The detail that 'the will... was found to be unchanged' chiefly functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["quietly qualify the generous reading, since the forgiveness altered no bequest and so cost him nothing","settle the question against the uncle, showing the reconciliation was a performance from the first","hint that the reconciliation simply came too late to be reflected in a will already drawn","round out the scene with the family's discovery, adding colour rather than judgement"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the pointed placement of the unchanged will checks, without refuting, the generous reading, forgiveness that moves no bequest costs nothing. B inflates that check into settled proof of insincerity, which the passage withholds. C offers an innocent timing excuse, but the will is 'read later' and nothing marks it as closed to revision; the detail is weighted, not incidental. D treats a loaded detail as mere colour.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-015", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything' raises the possibility that the forgiveness", format: "single_best", options: ["was, past any doubt, heartfelt and freely given","amounted, in the end, to a quiet admission that the nephew's long denial had been false","may have been staged to win the credit of magnanimity while surrendering nothing real","was deeply resented by the family who had to sit and watch it"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the clause plants the suspicion that the scene buys the reputation of generosity at no real cost. B is the twin trap, reading the pardon as settling the nephew's guilt, which the passage leaves open ('a wrong the nephew had always denied'). A ignores the doubt the clause raises; D imports the family's feelings, nowhere in view.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-016", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That the narrator 'cannot say; nor, I think, could he' most strongly implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the narrator is simply too tactful to pass judgement on his uncle in public","the truth was plain enough to the uncle, who chose to keep it to himself","no one in the room that day understood what had really passed","the uncle's own motive was hidden even from the uncle"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: if even the dying man could not say what he meant, the motive was opaque to himself, not merely undisclosed. B is the twin trap, which needs a settled motive he concealed, whereas 'nor, I think, could he' denies he had one to hide. A reduces it to the narrator's tact; C shifts the opacity onto the onlookers.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-017", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "At the end my uncle sent for the nephew he had not spoken to in twenty years, and forgave him, before the assembled family, for a wrong the nephew had always denied. It was a beautiful scene; my aunt wept, and the will, read later, was found to be unchanged. Whether the old man had at last let go of a grievance, or had merely arranged, with his last strength, to be seen letting go of it while conceding nothing that cost him anything, I cannot say; nor, I think, could he. He died, as he had lived, leaving others to decide what he had meant.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The narrator's tone is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["wry and suspended, refusing to settle whether the act was sincere","bitter and accusing in its judgement of the uncle","warm and openly approving of the reconciliation","cool and detached, indifferent to what the scene might mean"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the narrator lingers in 'I cannot say', amused and unresolved, which is wry suspension. B is too hostile for a voice that grants the scene its beauty; C is too settled for one that withholds a verdict; D mistakes deliberate withholding for not caring, though the narrator cares enough to weigh both readings.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-testing-018", genre: "testing", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem's governing tension lies in", format: "single_best", options: ["whether the memorial keeps remembrance alive or stages a feeling that quietly takes its place","whether stone, which outlasts us, is a fit medium for a memory that cannot last in us","the duty the living owe to keep faith with the war dead","the grief that the deaths the monument records still rightly command"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the poem's worry is that the rite preserves remembrance or merely performs a sorrow that replaces it ('our easy sorrow'). B fastens on the real stone-outlasts-memory motif but makes it the question, when it is only the means to the deeper one about performed feeling. C and D rest in single earnest readings (duty, grief) the poem unsettles.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-019", genre: "testing", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "That the visitors are 'moved less by them than by the act of moving' presents their grief as essentially", format: "single_best", options: ["maudlin","vicarious","self-regarding","ersatz"], answer: 2, explanation: "Their feeling turns on their own act of mourning rather than on the dead, so it is self-regarding. Vicarious (felt through another) points the wrong way; maudlin (tearfully sentimental) and ersatz (counterfeit) name flaws the poem does not actually assert.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-020", genre: "testing", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The lines 'the stone remembers nothing that we know, / and we remember nothing it is proving' chiefly mean that", format: "single_best", options: ["the inscriptions have, with the years, worn too faint to be read","neither the stone nor the mourners hold the actual lives the memorial stands for","what the stone records and what the mourners feel never quite meet, each missing the other","the visitors come knowing the names but not the history that gave them meaning"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the loss runs both ways, the stone knows nothing of the dead and the mourners know nothing it attests, so the real lives fall through the gap between them. C is the near-twin, naming a mismatch between record and feeling, but the point is not that two things fail to meet so much as that neither holds the lives at all. A literalises it into physical wear; D narrows it to forgotten history.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-021", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The final stanza ('Still, better this than nothing; or perhaps / the nothing would at least be honest')", format: "single_best", options: ["settles, after some hesitation, that the flawed memorial is better than nothing at all","leaves unresolved whether the flawed memorial is better than nothing or worse than an honest blank","demands that so dishonest a memorial be pulled down","embraces the very sorrow the rest of the poem has distrusted"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: 'or perhaps' suspends the verdict between 'better this than nothing' and a blank that 'would at least be honest'. A resolves the balance the poem keeps open; C hardens unease into a call for demolition; D adopts the easy sorrow the poem has just impugned.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-testing-022", genre: "testing", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-test-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "They cut the names in stone to make them last,\nand last they do, though no one left can say\nwhich face went with which name, or what was lost\nthe day the chisel gave them all away.\n\nWe come on Sundays, and are moved, and go,\nmoved less by them than by the act of moving;\nthe stone remembers nothing that we know,\nand we remember nothing it is proving.\n\nStill, better this than nothing; or perhaps\nthe nothing would at least be honest, and\nnot dress our easy sorrow in the gaps\nof lives we never troubled to understand.", attribution: "Original verse" }, stem: "The poem's attitude is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["reverent and quietly consoled by the solemn and dignified act of public remembrance","coldly detached, merely setting down what it sees","angry and contemptuous towards the Sunday visitors","uneasy and self-implicating, distrusting the very grief it shares"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'our easy sorrow' folds the speaker into the charge, so the unease is self-implicating. A is the elaborate trap, too consoled for a poem that calls the sorrow easy; B ignores the implicated 'we'; C turns quiet discomfort into hot contempt.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-001", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is often said that punishment is justified because it deters: the threat of suffering keeps others in line. But the account proves too much, for it would justify punishing a man known to be innocent whenever doing so would frighten enough others into obedience, and this we refuse, even when the sums favour it. The deterrent effect, then, cannot be the whole ground, since we hold to a limit it cannot supply. What the deterrence theorist has shown is not that deterrence justifies punishment, but that a practice already thought justified on other grounds also happens, conveniently, to deter.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage chiefly sets out to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["the deterrence theory, taken to its logical end, would license punishing the innocent","punishment must be justified, if at all, by giving each offender what he deserves rather than by its effects on others","no social practice can be justified by appeal to its consequences alone","deterrence is at best an incidental benefit of a practice already justified on other grounds"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the passage ends by saying a practice justified on other grounds 'happens, conveniently, to deter', making deterrence incidental. B is the near-twin trap, naming desert as the real ground, but the passage says only 'other grounds' and never specifies desert. A inverts the reductio, which uses the innocent-punishment case against the theory; C over-generalises to all consequentialism, wider than the deterrence-specific target.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-002", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is often said that punishment is justified because it deters: the threat of suffering keeps others in line. But the account proves too much, for it would justify punishing a man known to be innocent whenever doing so would frighten enough others into obedience, and this we refuse, even when the sums favour it. The deterrent effect, then, cannot be the whole ground, since we hold to a limit it cannot supply. What the deterrence theorist has shown is not that deterrence justifies punishment, but that a practice already thought justified on other grounds also happens, conveniently, to deter.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In saying the deterrence account 'proves too much', the author objects that it", format: "single_best", options: ["exaggerates how effective the threat of punishment is at deterring wrongdoers", "treats deterring others as a legitimate aim without ever arguing for it", "would license punishing the innocent, which we reject, so it cannot be the real ground", "draws a sweeping conclusion from a single, specially chosen example"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'proves too much' is the logical charge that the principle licenses more than we will accept, here punishing the innocent, so it cannot be the operative ground. A and B are real objections (effectiveness; the aim's legitimacy) but not the over-licensing the phrase names. D mistakes the structure: the innocent-punishment case is not a stray example but the very consequence the principle entails.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-003", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is often said that punishment is justified because it deters: the threat of suffering keeps others in line. But the account proves too much, for it would justify punishing a man known to be innocent whenever doing so would frighten enough others into obedience, and this we refuse, even when the sums favour it. The deterrent effect, then, cannot be the whole ground, since we hold to a limit it cannot supply. What the deterrence theorist has shown is not that deterrence justifies punishment, but that a practice already thought justified on other grounds also happens, conveniently, to deter.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["in genuine emergencies we do knowingly impose grave burdens on the innocent to protect the many, and accept it","no serious deterrence theorist has ever actually recommended punishing someone known to be innocent","certainty of being caught deters more reliably than severity of punishment","punishment quite often fails to deter at all"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the argument turns on the premise 'this we refuse, even when the sums favour it'; if in real emergencies we knowingly burden the innocent and accept it, that refusal is not firm and the reductio loses its grip. B is the twin trap, about what theorists propose rather than what the principle licenses. C is a detail of deterrence mechanics; D actually sits well with the view that deterrence is incidental.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-004", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why does a promise bind? The familiar answer is that it creates an expectation, and that to break it is to disappoint someone who has arranged their affairs around your word. Yet this cannot be the whole story, for it would make the wrong of breaking a promise depend on whether the other had in fact relied on it, so that a promise no one troubled to count on could be broken at no cost. But we think otherwise: the careless promiser, lucky in his victim's indifference, has still done what he ought not. The binding force lies not in the expectation aroused but in the act of binding itself, which the expectation merely, and usually, accompanies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim is", format: "single_best", options: ["breaking a promise is wrong only where someone actually relied on it and arranged their affairs accordingly","since the careless promiser does wrong even when no one relied, the harm a broken promise does cannot be what makes it wrong","what makes promise-breaking wrong is the act of binding oneself by one's word, not the expectation it happens to raise","one ought to keep one's promises so as not to disappoint those who trust one"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage concludes the binding force 'lies not in the expectation aroused but in the act of binding itself'. B is the near-twin trap: true, and the passage's argument against the expectation account, but it states that step (harm is not the source) rather than the positive claim about where the wrong lies. A is the expectation account the passage rejects; D is a prudential maxim, not an analysis of the wrong.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-005", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why does a promise bind? The familiar answer is that it creates an expectation, and that to break it is to disappoint someone who has arranged their affairs around your word. Yet this cannot be the whole story, for it would make the wrong of breaking a promise depend on whether the other had in fact relied on it, so that a promise no one troubled to count on could be broken at no cost. But we think otherwise: the careless promiser, lucky in his victim's indifference, has still done what he ought not. The binding force lies not in the expectation aroused but in the act of binding itself, which the expectation merely, and usually, accompanies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The case of 'the careless promiser, lucky in his victim's indifference' is offered to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["people very often make solemn promises they have no real intention of keeping","reliance is, in practice, extremely hard to measure after the fact","a promise can be wrongly broken even where no expectation was disappointed, so expectation cannot be the source of the wrong","the wrongness of breaking a promise turns on the promiser's carelessness, his state of mind rather than the outcome"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the careless promiser does wrong although no expectation was disappointed, a counter-instance showing expectation cannot be the source. D is the twin trap, fastening on 'careless' to relocate the wrong in the promiser's state of mind, but the example's job is to sever wrongness from disappointed expectation, not to make carelessness the ground. A is a claim about frequency; B about measurement, neither the logical role the example plays.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-006", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why does a promise bind? The familiar answer is that it creates an expectation, and that to break it is to disappoint someone who has arranged their affairs around your word. Yet this cannot be the whole story, for it would make the wrong of breaking a promise depend on whether the other had in fact relied on it, so that a promise no one troubled to count on could be broken at no cost. But we think otherwise: the careless promiser, lucky in his victim's indifference, has still done what he ought not. The binding force lies not in the expectation aroused but in the act of binding itself, which the expectation merely, and usually, accompanies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The argument rests on the unstated assumption that", format: "single_best", options: ["most people do, as a matter of fact, rely heavily on the promises made to them","the promiser's intentions are always known to the person he promises","the duty to keep promises outweighs whatever good might come of breaking them","an act can be wrong independently of any harm or disappointment it actually causes"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the lucky careless promiser does wrong though nothing was disappointed, which follows only if wrongness can be independent of the harm actually caused. C is the twin trap, a weightier-sounding premise the argument never uses; it needs no claim that duty outranks good, only that the wrong does not depend on harm. A is a background claim it does not need; B is unrelated.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-007", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The objection that one who has nothing to hide has nothing to fear treats privacy as a screen for wrongdoing, valuable only to those with something to conceal. But this mistakes what privacy is for. A life lived wholly in view is not merely an exposed life; it is a different kind of life, for there are things one can only become, or think, or try, in the absence of an audience. To be always watched is to be always, in some measure, performing, and the self that performs is not the self that experiments. Privacy protects not the guilty secret but the unfinished thought, the half-formed self that publicity would freeze before it could take shape.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is chiefly concerned to argue", format: "single_best", options: ["people are entitled to keep their own wrongdoing hidden from others", "privacy is valuable above all as room for deliberate self-fashioning, a space to try on identities away from any audience", "people behave differently, and often worse, when they know they are watched", "constant observation does not merely expose the self but changes what it can become, so privacy guards the unfinished self"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the passage makes observation constitutive, freezing 'the half-formed self', so privacy protects the unfinished self rather than the guilty secret. B is the near-twin trap, narrowing the claim to deliberate self-fashioning, where the passage's point is broader, that being watched alters thought and becoming as such. A is the hiding-frame the passage rejects; C states the supporting observation as if it were the conclusion.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-008", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The objection that one who has nothing to hide has nothing to fear treats privacy as a screen for wrongdoing, valuable only to those with something to conceal. But this mistakes what privacy is for. A life lived wholly in view is not merely an exposed life; it is a different kind of life, for there are things one can only become, or think, or try, in the absence of an audience. To be always watched is to be always, in some measure, performing, and the self that performs is not the self that experiments. Privacy protects not the guilty secret but the unfinished thought, the half-formed self that publicity would freeze before it could take shape.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The contrast between 'the self that performs' and 'the self that experiments' is drawn to establish that", format: "single_best", options: ["people grow dishonest when they know they are being observed","an observed life is not a worse life so much as a different one, lived under a constraint the unobserved escape","privacy matters chiefly to artists and original thinkers, whose work needs unobserved trial","observation does not merely reveal the self but alters what the self is able to do and become"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the performing/experimenting contrast makes observation constitutive, not merely revealing. B captures the passage's 'different kind of life' but halts at difference and constraint, missing the contrast's real work, that being watched changes what one can become. A reads 'performing' as dishonesty; C narrows the value to a special class of people.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-009", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The objection that one who has nothing to hide has nothing to fear treats privacy as a screen for wrongdoing, valuable only to those with something to conceal. But this mistakes what privacy is for. A life lived wholly in view is not merely an exposed life; it is a different kind of life, for there are things one can only become, or think, or try, in the absence of an audience. To be always watched is to be always, in some measure, performing, and the self that performs is not the self that experiments. Privacy protects not the guilty secret but the unfinished thought, the half-formed self that publicity would freeze before it could take shape.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's defence of privacy?", format: "single_best", options: ["many people who have done no wrong still feel a strong, lasting desire for privacy","surveillance has lately become cheap and very nearly universal","people raised wholly under observation develop selves as exploratory and unfinished as anyone else","a few people, far from freezing, perform more boldly before an audience than without one"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the defence rests on observation freezing the experimenting self; if those raised wholly watched are no less exploratory, the core claim dissolves. D is the near-miss, a handful of bolder performers, too marginal to unseat the general claim. A actually supports the passage; B bears on how common surveillance is, not on its value.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-010", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity promises that careers be open to talents, that no one be barred by birth from the positions the talented may win. But the promise, kept, only pushes the inequality back a step. For the talents themselves are unequally distributed, and unequally cultivated, by families and circumstances no child has chosen, so that a race made fair at the starting line is run by competitors the prior years have already made unequal. To make the opportunity genuinely equal, one would have to equalise the conditions under which talents are formed, which is to say to reach back into the family itself, the very institution the principle was meant to leave untouched.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's principal contention is that", format: "single_best", options: ["genuine equality of opportunity, pursued to the end, would have to reach into the very family it meant to leave alone", "no race can be fair while the runners reach the line already made unequal by the years before it", "equality of opportunity, being self-undermining when pressed, should be given up as an incoherent ideal", "careers ought to be open to talents whatever a person's birth"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the regress drives to the conclusion that equalising how talents are formed must reach into the family the principle meant to leave untouched. B is the twin trap, a striking restatement of the diagnosis (unequal starts) that stops at the problem, where the contention is the awkward remedy. C overstates into abandoning the ideal, which the passage does not urge; D is the principle under examination, not the claim about it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-011", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity promises that careers be open to talents, that no one be barred by birth from the positions the talented may win. But the promise, kept, only pushes the inequality back a step. For the talents themselves are unequally distributed, and unequally cultivated, by families and circumstances no child has chosen, so that a race made fair at the starting line is run by competitors the prior years have already made unequal. To make the opportunity genuinely equal, one would have to equalise the conditions under which talents are formed, which is to say to reach back into the family itself, the very institution the principle was meant to leave untouched.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "To say the principle, kept, 'only pushes the inequality back a step' is to claim that it", format: "single_best", options: ["removes one barrier only to leave an earlier, deeper inequality untouched","merely relocates the unfairness from the workplace to the school, without lessening it overall","favours the talented at the expense of the untalented","has never been put sincerely into practice by any government"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the starting-line barrier falls, yet the prior inequality in how talents were formed remains, so the inequality is displaced rather than removed. B also reads displacement but fixes it at the school, where the passage pushes it back further, into the family and circumstances that form talent. C is about who benefits; D about historical attempts, neither the backward displacement the phrase names.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-012", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity promises that careers be open to talents, that no one be barred by birth from the positions the talented may win. But the promise, kept, only pushes the inequality back a step. For the talents themselves are unequally distributed, and unequally cultivated, by families and circumstances no child has chosen, so that a race made fair at the starting line is run by competitors the prior years have already made unequal. To make the opportunity genuinely equal, one would have to equalise the conditions under which talents are formed, which is to say to reach back into the family itself, the very institution the principle was meant to leave untouched.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["families differ greatly in how far they cultivate their children's talents", "the state could equalise schooling without reaching into families at all", "some children overcome severe early disadvantage and still succeed", "the talents that decide success are largely innate, barely shaped by upbringing"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the argument needs talents to be formed by family and circumstance; if they are largely innate and scarcely shaped by upbringing, equalising the conditions of formation is neither needed nor sufficient, and the slide into the family does not follow. B offers one equalising route but leaves family cultivation, the real concern, in place. A supports the premise; C is a few exceptions that do not unsettle the general claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-013", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are increasingly asked not merely to tolerate ways of life we find mistaken, but to respect them; and the shift sounds like progress, a warmer and more generous attitude. Yet toleration and respect pull apart. To tolerate a practice is to put up with what one disapproves of, and so it presupposes the disapproval; to respect it is to set the disapproval aside, to grant the practice a standing one's own judgement denies it. The demand for respect, pressed universally, therefore asks us to stop judging at all; and a regard extended to every way of life without discrimination is not respect, which is earned and particular, but indifference wearing its clothes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The central claim the passage defends is that", format: "single_best", options: ["we should merely tolerate the ways of life we disapprove of, not be made to respect them", "respect and toleration are opposed attitudes, the one setting aside a disapproval the other keeps", "the demand to respect every way of life alike, pressed to its end, becomes indifference rather than regard", "real respect is earned by the particular merits of a practice, not owed to all alike"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage concludes that universal respect is 'indifference wearing its clothes', collapsing the warmer-sounding demand into indifference. B is the twin trap, the toleration/respect contrast the argument turns on, mistaken for its destination. A is a prescription the passage implies but does not make its point; D is a premise along the way.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-014", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are increasingly asked not merely to tolerate ways of life we find mistaken, but to respect them; and the shift sounds like progress, a warmer and more generous attitude. Yet toleration and respect pull apart. To tolerate a practice is to put up with what one disapproves of, and so it presupposes the disapproval; to respect it is to set the disapproval aside, to grant the practice a standing one's own judgement denies it. The demand for respect, pressed universally, therefore asks us to stop judging at all; and a regard extended to every way of life without discrimination is not respect, which is earned and particular, but indifference wearing its clothes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the passage's account, toleration differs from respect in that toleration", format: "single_best", options: ["implies a power to suppress that one chooses not to exercise","keeps in place the very disapproval that respect sets aside","is extended to all alike, where respect is selective and earned","is a colder and less generous attitude than respect"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the distinction drawn is that toleration retains the very disapproval respect discards. C reverses the passage, which ties universal respect, not toleration, to indifference; toleration is never called the all-embracing attitude. A names a real feature of toleration but not the contrast pressed; D mislabels toleration as the colder one, where the passage calls universal respect the empty attitude.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-015", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are increasingly asked not merely to tolerate ways of life we find mistaken, but to respect them; and the shift sounds like progress, a warmer and more generous attitude. Yet toleration and respect pull apart. To tolerate a practice is to put up with what one disapproves of, and so it presupposes the disapproval; to respect it is to set the disapproval aside, to grant the practice a standing one's own judgement denies it. The demand for respect, pressed universally, therefore asks us to stop judging at all; and a regard extended to every way of life without discrimination is not respect, which is earned and particular, but indifference wearing its clothes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's conclusion?", format: "single_best", options: ["one can drop one disapproval yet keep judging elsewhere, so respect need not end judgement", "in everyday speech 'tolerance' and 'respect' are used more or less interchangeably", "people sometimes respect practices they never had occasion to disapprove of", "indifference and respect can issue in exactly the same outward conduct"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the conclusion depends on the step that respecting every way of life amounts to not judging at all; if one can set a particular disapproval aside yet keep judging, that step fails and the slide into indifference is blocked. D, that the two look alike from outside, actually supports the author. B is a verbal point about usage; C a side case.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-calibration-016", genre: "calibration", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a temptation to think that what a man believes, so long as he keeps it to himself and acts on it only at his own risk, is his own affair. But no belief is truly private in its effects, for beliefs are the soil from which actions grow, and a habit of believing on insufficient evidence, indulged in the safe cases, does not stay quarantined there: it shapes the mind that will later face the cases that matter. The credulity we excuse in trifles trains the credulity that will not be harmless. What we owe is not a true belief on every question, which no one can promise, but the discipline of proportioning belief to evidence, even where the error would, this once, have cost nothing.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's controlling claim is that", format: "single_best", options: ["we are obliged to reach a true and well-grounded belief on every question that matters", "what a man believes privately, acting only at his own risk, is his own affair", "the discipline we owe is to proportion belief to evidence even where error this once costs nothing", "a single careless belief, even on a trifle, may by itself lead directly to serious harm"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage's positive claim is the duty to proportion belief to evidence 'even where the error would, this once, have cost nothing'. D is the twin trap, overstating the mechanism: the passage does not say one trifling belief directly causes harm, but that the habit of loose belief trains a credulity that later will not be harmless. A is the very thing the passage disclaims ('not a true belief on every question'); B is the opening view it sets out to refute.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-017", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a temptation to think that what a man believes, so long as he keeps it to himself and acts on it only at his own risk, is his own affair. But no belief is truly private in its effects, for beliefs are the soil from which actions grow, and a habit of believing on insufficient evidence, indulged in the safe cases, does not stay quarantined there: it shapes the mind that will later face the cases that matter. The credulity we excuse in trifles trains the credulity that will not be harmless. What we owe is not a true belief on every question, which no one can promise, but the discipline of proportioning belief to evidence, even where the error would, this once, have cost nothing.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of beliefs as 'the soil from which actions grow' chiefly serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["suggest that beliefs, once rooted, are hard to dig out and change","make belief the ground from which conduct springs, so that no belief stays private in its effects","show that a belief, like a plant, needs the steady nourishment of evidence to grow sound","argue that what people do matters more than what they privately believe"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the soil image makes belief the ground from which action grows, so no belief is private in its effects. C extends the metaphor plausibly (evidence as nourishment) but that is not its job here, which is to tie belief to the conduct it issues in. A presses the image toward rootedness, a different point; D inverts the emphasis onto actions over beliefs.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-calibration-018", genre: "calibration", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-cal-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a temptation to think that what a man believes, so long as he keeps it to himself and acts on it only at his own risk, is his own affair. But no belief is truly private in its effects, for beliefs are the soil from which actions grow, and a habit of believing on insufficient evidence, indulged in the safe cases, does not stay quarantined there: it shapes the mind that will later face the cases that matter. The credulity we excuse in trifles trains the credulity that will not be harmless. What we owe is not a true belief on every question, which no one can promise, but the discipline of proportioning belief to evidence, even where the error would, this once, have cost nothing.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "If true, which of the following would most undermine the argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["people can believe loosely on trifles while reasoning strictly on the things that count", "most beliefs people hold never issue in any outward action, but stay idle in the mind", "some false beliefs have in fact led on to important discoveries", "good evidence is, on many questions, genuinely hard to come by"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the argument rests on a habit of careless belief spreading from trifles to the cases that matter; if people can keep the two apart, that spillover is denied and the case falls. B attacks a different premise (that beliefs issue in action) but leaves the habit-forming worry standing. C and D do not touch the spillover claim at all.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-047", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged, above all, to be authentic, to be true to ourselves, as though the self were a fixed text one had only to consult and obey. The counsel sounds like liberation, and it has displaced older counsels, to be dutiful, to be good, to be useful, that now strike the modern ear as quaint or even oppressive. Yet the more one presses on the idea, the less it yields. For the self to which we are to be true is not a finished thing, lying ready beneath the layers of convention like a statue in the marble; it is, in large part, made by the very choices it is supposed to direct. The shy man who forces himself, against his inclination, to speak in meetings does not betray his true self; over years, he becomes a man for whom speaking is natural, and the earlier shyness comes to look like the accident, the false skin, and the acquired confidence like the real grain. Which, then, was the authentic self, the one he found or the one he built?\n\nThe doctrine has a darker convenience, too. To act badly and call it authenticity is to dress a vice as a virtue: the man who is cruel and announces that he is merely being honest, that he refuses to perform a politeness he does not feel, has found a way to make his cruelty sound like courage. Authenticity, so used, excuses whatever one already wished to do, and flatters the wish by calling obedience to it integrity. The older virtues at least pointed outward, to some standard one might fail to meet; this one points only inward, to a self that conveniently wants what it wants.\n\nNone of this is to say the ideal is empty. There is a real thing it gropes toward: the refusal to live a life wholly scripted by others, the insistence that one's commitments be in some sense one's own. But that is a modest and demanding claim, requiring that we shape a self worth being true to, not that we excavate one already there and ratify its every impulse. The trouble is not that authenticity is worthless, but that, left vague, it does the opposite of its promise: it binds us to whatever we happen already to be." }, stem: "What the passage ultimately argues is that", format: "single_best", options: ["the self is not found but largely made by the very choices authenticity was meant to direct","to call one's bad behaviour authentic dresses a vice in the colours of honesty","the older virtues of duty and usefulness still secretly govern conduct beneath the modern talk of self-realisation","left vague, the ideal of authenticity does the reverse of what it promises, binding us to whatever we already happen to be"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the closing thesis is that authenticity, 'left vague... does the opposite of its promise; it binds us to whatever we happen already to be'. A and B are real supporting moves (the self is made, not found; vice dressed as honesty), steps toward the thesis rather than the thesis. C contradicts the passage, which says the older virtues now strike us as 'quaint or even oppressive', that is, displaced.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-048", genre: "prose", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged, above all, to be authentic, to be true to ourselves, as though the self were a fixed text one had only to consult and obey. The counsel sounds like liberation, and it has displaced older counsels, to be dutiful, to be good, to be useful, that now strike the modern ear as quaint or even oppressive. Yet the more one presses on the idea, the less it yields. For the self to which we are to be true is not a finished thing, lying ready beneath the layers of convention like a statue in the marble; it is, in large part, made by the very choices it is supposed to direct. The shy man who forces himself, against his inclination, to speak in meetings does not betray his true self; over years, he becomes a man for whom speaking is natural, and the earlier shyness comes to look like the accident, the false skin, and the acquired confidence like the real grain. Which, then, was the authentic self, the one he found or the one he built?\n\nThe doctrine has a darker convenience, too. To act badly and call it authenticity is to dress a vice as a virtue: the man who is cruel and announces that he is merely being honest, that he refuses to perform a politeness he does not feel, has found a way to make his cruelty sound like courage. Authenticity, so used, excuses whatever one already wished to do, and flatters the wish by calling obedience to it integrity. The older virtues at least pointed outward, to some standard one might fail to meet; this one points only inward, to a self that conveniently wants what it wants.\n\nNone of this is to say the ideal is empty. There is a real thing it gropes toward: the refusal to live a life wholly scripted by others, the insistence that one's commitments be in some sense one's own. But that is a modest and demanding claim, requiring that we shape a self worth being true to, not that we excavate one already there and ratify its every impulse. The trouble is not that authenticity is worthless, but that, left vague, it does the opposite of its promise: it binds us to whatever we happen already to be." }, stem: "The example of the shy man who learns to speak in meetings is offered to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["the self one is to be true to may be one's own construction, not a self already there", "the confidence a person builds is more authentic than the traits he was born with", "people can remake their personalities if they try hard enough", "overcoming shyness is a duty that authenticity wrongly discourages"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the man becomes someone for whom speaking is natural, so the self may be built, not found, the example's point. B is the twin, but the passage leaves it an open question ('Which, then, was the authentic self?') and does not crown the acquired trait the more authentic. C over-generalises into self-help; D imports a duty the passage never asserts.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-049", genre: "prose", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged, above all, to be authentic, to be true to ourselves, as though the self were a fixed text one had only to consult and obey. The counsel sounds like liberation, and it has displaced older counsels, to be dutiful, to be good, to be useful, that now strike the modern ear as quaint or even oppressive. Yet the more one presses on the idea, the less it yields. For the self to which we are to be true is not a finished thing, lying ready beneath the layers of convention like a statue in the marble; it is, in large part, made by the very choices it is supposed to direct. The shy man who forces himself, against his inclination, to speak in meetings does not betray his true self; over years, he becomes a man for whom speaking is natural, and the earlier shyness comes to look like the accident, the false skin, and the acquired confidence like the real grain. Which, then, was the authentic self, the one he found or the one he built?\n\nThe doctrine has a darker convenience, too. To act badly and call it authenticity is to dress a vice as a virtue: the man who is cruel and announces that he is merely being honest, that he refuses to perform a politeness he does not feel, has found a way to make his cruelty sound like courage. Authenticity, so used, excuses whatever one already wished to do, and flatters the wish by calling obedience to it integrity. The older virtues at least pointed outward, to some standard one might fail to meet; this one points only inward, to a self that conveniently wants what it wants.\n\nNone of this is to say the ideal is empty. There is a real thing it gropes toward: the refusal to live a life wholly scripted by others, the insistence that one's commitments be in some sense one's own. But that is a modest and demanding claim, requiring that we shape a self worth being true to, not that we excavate one already there and ratify its every impulse. The trouble is not that authenticity is worthless, but that, left vague, it does the opposite of its promise: it binds us to whatever we happen already to be." }, stem: "In calling the appeal to authenticity a 'darker convenience', the author objects that it", format: "single_best", options: ["is invoked too often by people who have not thought it through", "rules out any politeness or social grace whatsoever", "is the resort of weak characters who shun the older, more demanding virtues", "lets one dress an existing impulse as integrity, excusing rather than examining it"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'to act badly and call it authenticity is to dress a vice as a virtue', so the appeal excuses an impulse already had rather than examining it. C is the twin, a sweeping verdict on the weak character of those who use it that the passage never makes; A reduces it to frequency; B overstates into a blanket war on politeness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-050", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged, above all, to be authentic, to be true to ourselves, as though the self were a fixed text one had only to consult and obey. The counsel sounds like liberation, and it has displaced older counsels, to be dutiful, to be good, to be useful, that now strike the modern ear as quaint or even oppressive. Yet the more one presses on the idea, the less it yields. For the self to which we are to be true is not a finished thing, lying ready beneath the layers of convention like a statue in the marble; it is, in large part, made by the very choices it is supposed to direct. The shy man who forces himself, against his inclination, to speak in meetings does not betray his true self; over years, he becomes a man for whom speaking is natural, and the earlier shyness comes to look like the accident, the false skin, and the acquired confidence like the real grain. Which, then, was the authentic self, the one he found or the one he built?\n\nThe doctrine has a darker convenience, too. To act badly and call it authenticity is to dress a vice as a virtue: the man who is cruel and announces that he is merely being honest, that he refuses to perform a politeness he does not feel, has found a way to make his cruelty sound like courage. Authenticity, so used, excuses whatever one already wished to do, and flatters the wish by calling obedience to it integrity. The older virtues at least pointed outward, to some standard one might fail to meet; this one points only inward, to a self that conveniently wants what it wants.\n\nNone of this is to say the ideal is empty. There is a real thing it gropes toward: the refusal to live a life wholly scripted by others, the insistence that one's commitments be in some sense one's own. But that is a modest and demanding claim, requiring that we shape a self worth being true to, not that we excavate one already there and ratify its every impulse. The trouble is not that authenticity is worthless, but that, left vague, it does the opposite of its promise: it binds us to whatever we happen already to be." }, stem: "In the final paragraph, to 'ratify' the self's every impulse most nearly means to", format: "single_best", options: ["sanction it","broach it","interrogate it","supplant it"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: to ratify an impulse is to give it one's sanction, to approve and authorise it, which is what uncritically obeying the self amounts to. C (interrogate) is its opposite; B (broach) means to raise as a topic; D (supplant) means to replace, unrelated.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-051", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged, above all, to be authentic, to be true to ourselves, as though the self were a fixed text one had only to consult and obey. The counsel sounds like liberation, and it has displaced older counsels, to be dutiful, to be good, to be useful, that now strike the modern ear as quaint or even oppressive. Yet the more one presses on the idea, the less it yields. For the self to which we are to be true is not a finished thing, lying ready beneath the layers of convention like a statue in the marble; it is, in large part, made by the very choices it is supposed to direct. The shy man who forces himself, against his inclination, to speak in meetings does not betray his true self; over years, he becomes a man for whom speaking is natural, and the earlier shyness comes to look like the accident, the false skin, and the acquired confidence like the real grain. Which, then, was the authentic self, the one he found or the one he built?\n\nThe doctrine has a darker convenience, too. To act badly and call it authenticity is to dress a vice as a virtue: the man who is cruel and announces that he is merely being honest, that he refuses to perform a politeness he does not feel, has found a way to make his cruelty sound like courage. Authenticity, so used, excuses whatever one already wished to do, and flatters the wish by calling obedience to it integrity. The older virtues at least pointed outward, to some standard one might fail to meet; this one points only inward, to a self that conveniently wants what it wants.\n\nNone of this is to say the ideal is empty. There is a real thing it gropes toward: the refusal to live a life wholly scripted by others, the insistence that one's commitments be in some sense one's own. But that is a modest and demanding claim, requiring that we shape a self worth being true to, not that we excavate one already there and ratify its every impulse. The trouble is not that authenticity is worthless, but that, left vague, it does the opposite of its promise: it binds us to whatever we happen already to be." }, stem: "Which case would the author most likely regard as the misuse of authenticity he warns against?", format: "single_best", options: ["a woman who, after long reflection, leaves a career that never suited her","a student who practises a manner he admires until it becomes his own","a man who, having built over decades a generous character unlike his early self, takes that made character as truly his and lives by it","a man who breaks a promise and defends it by saying that keeping it would be false to himself"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: defending a broken promise as fidelity to oneself dresses the breach as integrity, the misuse named. C is the twin, the very self-shaping the passage approves (a made character one may rightly own), not a misuse; A and B are likewise legitimate cases of forming or following a considered self.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-052", genre: "prose", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged, above all, to be authentic, to be true to ourselves, as though the self were a fixed text one had only to consult and obey. The counsel sounds like liberation, and it has displaced older counsels, to be dutiful, to be good, to be useful, that now strike the modern ear as quaint or even oppressive. Yet the more one presses on the idea, the less it yields. For the self to which we are to be true is not a finished thing, lying ready beneath the layers of convention like a statue in the marble; it is, in large part, made by the very choices it is supposed to direct. The shy man who forces himself, against his inclination, to speak in meetings does not betray his true self; over years, he becomes a man for whom speaking is natural, and the earlier shyness comes to look like the accident, the false skin, and the acquired confidence like the real grain. Which, then, was the authentic self, the one he found or the one he built?\n\nThe doctrine has a darker convenience, too. To act badly and call it authenticity is to dress a vice as a virtue: the man who is cruel and announces that he is merely being honest, that he refuses to perform a politeness he does not feel, has found a way to make his cruelty sound like courage. Authenticity, so used, excuses whatever one already wished to do, and flatters the wish by calling obedience to it integrity. The older virtues at least pointed outward, to some standard one might fail to meet; this one points only inward, to a self that conveniently wants what it wants.\n\nNone of this is to say the ideal is empty. There is a real thing it gropes toward: the refusal to live a life wholly scripted by others, the insistence that one's commitments be in some sense one's own. But that is a modest and demanding claim, requiring that we shape a self worth being true to, not that we excavate one already there and ratify its every impulse. The trouble is not that authenticity is worthless, but that, left vague, it does the opposite of its promise: it binds us to whatever we happen already to be." }, stem: "The final paragraph ('None of this is to say the ideal is empty') chiefly serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["withdraw the criticism the essay has built","call for the older virtues of duty and usefulness to be restored in authenticity's place","rescue a modest, demanding form of the ideal while holding to the case against its vague form","concede that the critics of authenticity have been right all along"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the paragraph saves 'a modest and demanding claim' (shaping a self worth being true to) while keeping the charge against the vague ideal. B is the twin, reading the salvage as a return to the older virtues, where the essay reforms authenticity itself; A and D misread it as a withdrawal or a surrender.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-053", genre: "prose", skill: "characterisation", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Everyone agreed that Hollis was the only honest man in the firm, and Hollis agreed with them. He said the things others merely thought; he told the chairman to his face that the new logo was hideous, told Marsh that his speech had bored the room, told the junior clerks, kindly, where their work fell short. There was a bracing weather about him, and people sought him out to be told the truth, or rather to be told that what they hoped was true was not, which they took, gratefully, for the same thing.\n\nWhat no one noticed, because it was hidden in plain sight, was that Hollis's candour never cost Hollis anything. His truths were always about other people. When his own project failed, the post-mortem was brief and oddly gentle, conducted by Hollis himself, and concluded that the market had not been ready; when a rival's failed, the inquest was long, thorough, and led, by a route Hollis laid with great fairness, to the rival. He was frank about the chairman's logo because the chairman liked to be thought a man who could take it; he was never frank about the chairman's pension arrangements, on which his own depended. His honesty, in short, was a finely tuned instrument that played only in the keys that flattered the player, and fell silent the moment a true note would have sounded against him.\n\nThe young woman who eventually replaced him saw this within a month, but said nothing, having learned from watching Hollis that the most useful truths are the ones you decline to speak. She was promoted twice in the time it took the firm to notice that its honest man had told it, for twenty years, only the truths that suited him; and even then it did not quite believe it, for he had said so many sharp things, and surely a man who says sharp things must be brave. The reputation outlived the evidence, as reputations do, and Hollis retired full of honours, the last of which was the firm's genuine, and for once unanimous, regret." }, stem: "Hollis is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["an honest man whose plain speaking was unfairly resented","a man whose reputation for honesty rested on a candour carefully confined to truths that cost him nothing","a coward who never told the truth about anything at all","a calculating manipulator who consciously plotted, over two decades, a campaign of selective honesty designed to ruin his rivals and secure his own advancement"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: Hollis's candour 'never cost Hollis anything' and 'played only in the keys that flattered the player', so his honesty was real but confined to safe truths. D is the elaborate trap, hardening this into a conscious twenty-year conspiracy to ruin rivals, where the passage shows a self-serving slant more than a plotted campaign. A adopts his flattering reputation; C overstates into his never telling any truth, though he plainly told many.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-054", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Everyone agreed that Hollis was the only honest man in the firm, and Hollis agreed with them. He said the things others merely thought; he told the chairman to his face that the new logo was hideous, told Marsh that his speech had bored the room, told the junior clerks, kindly, where their work fell short. There was a bracing weather about him, and people sought him out to be told the truth, or rather to be told that what they hoped was true was not, which they took, gratefully, for the same thing.\n\nWhat no one noticed, because it was hidden in plain sight, was that Hollis's candour never cost Hollis anything. His truths were always about other people. When his own project failed, the post-mortem was brief and oddly gentle, conducted by Hollis himself, and concluded that the market had not been ready; when a rival's failed, the inquest was long, thorough, and led, by a route Hollis laid with great fairness, to the rival. He was frank about the chairman's logo because the chairman liked to be thought a man who could take it; he was never frank about the chairman's pension arrangements, on which his own depended. His honesty, in short, was a finely tuned instrument that played only in the keys that flattered the player, and fell silent the moment a true note would have sounded against him.\n\nThe young woman who eventually replaced him saw this within a month, but said nothing, having learned from watching Hollis that the most useful truths are the ones you decline to speak. She was promoted twice in the time it took the firm to notice that its honest man had told it, for twenty years, only the truths that suited him; and even then it did not quite believe it, for he had said so many sharp things, and surely a man who says sharp things must be brave. The reputation outlived the evidence, as reputations do, and Hollis retired full of honours, the last of which was the firm's genuine, and for once unanimous, regret." }, stem: "The two 'post-mortems', on his own project and on the rival's, are juxtaposed chiefly to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["Hollis applied his candour asymmetrically, sparing himself the scrutiny he turned on rivals","Hollis had a real analytical gift for diagnosing failure, sharpest when he was least involved","Hollis was a careful and impartial analyst of failure","the rival's project was in fact the worse of the two"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: his own failure got a brief, gentle inquest blaming the market, the rival's a long one leading to the rival, an asymmetry that spares himself. B is the twin, dressing the bias as an analytical 'gift'. C takes the fairness at face value; D shifts to the projects' actual merits, which the passage never compares.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-055", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Everyone agreed that Hollis was the only honest man in the firm, and Hollis agreed with them. He said the things others merely thought; he told the chairman to his face that the new logo was hideous, told Marsh that his speech had bored the room, told the junior clerks, kindly, where their work fell short. There was a bracing weather about him, and people sought him out to be told the truth, or rather to be told that what they hoped was true was not, which they took, gratefully, for the same thing.\n\nWhat no one noticed, because it was hidden in plain sight, was that Hollis's candour never cost Hollis anything. His truths were always about other people. When his own project failed, the post-mortem was brief and oddly gentle, conducted by Hollis himself, and concluded that the market had not been ready; when a rival's failed, the inquest was long, thorough, and led, by a route Hollis laid with great fairness, to the rival. He was frank about the chairman's logo because the chairman liked to be thought a man who could take it; he was never frank about the chairman's pension arrangements, on which his own depended. His honesty, in short, was a finely tuned instrument that played only in the keys that flattered the player, and fell silent the moment a true note would have sounded against him.\n\nThe young woman who eventually replaced him saw this within a month, but said nothing, having learned from watching Hollis that the most useful truths are the ones you decline to speak. She was promoted twice in the time it took the firm to notice that its honest man had told it, for twenty years, only the truths that suited him; and even then it did not quite believe it, for he had said so many sharp things, and surely a man who says sharp things must be brave. The reputation outlived the evidence, as reputations do, and Hollis retired full of honours, the last of which was the firm's genuine, and for once unanimous, regret." }, stem: "That the young woman 'said nothing, having learned... that the most useful truths are the ones you decline to speak' is best read as", format: "single_best", options: ["a sign she admired Hollis and meant to model herself on his celebrated frankness", "an irony: she rises by taking up the selective silence behind Hollis's method", "evidence she was, at bottom, as dishonest as Hollis", "proof that honesty is always punished in organisations"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: she rises by practising the strategic silence that was Hollis's actual method, a pointed irony. A is the twin, mistaking what she learned (the silence) for the frankness she saw through. C moralises her into mere dishonesty; D inflates one case into a law that honesty is always punished.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-056", genre: "prose", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Everyone agreed that Hollis was the only honest man in the firm, and Hollis agreed with them. He said the things others merely thought; he told the chairman to his face that the new logo was hideous, told Marsh that his speech had bored the room, told the junior clerks, kindly, where their work fell short. There was a bracing weather about him, and people sought him out to be told the truth, or rather to be told that what they hoped was true was not, which they took, gratefully, for the same thing.\n\nWhat no one noticed, because it was hidden in plain sight, was that Hollis's candour never cost Hollis anything. His truths were always about other people. When his own project failed, the post-mortem was brief and oddly gentle, conducted by Hollis himself, and concluded that the market had not been ready; when a rival's failed, the inquest was long, thorough, and led, by a route Hollis laid with great fairness, to the rival. He was frank about the chairman's logo because the chairman liked to be thought a man who could take it; he was never frank about the chairman's pension arrangements, on which his own depended. His honesty, in short, was a finely tuned instrument that played only in the keys that flattered the player, and fell silent the moment a true note would have sounded against him.\n\nThe young woman who eventually replaced him saw this within a month, but said nothing, having learned from watching Hollis that the most useful truths are the ones you decline to speak. She was promoted twice in the time it took the firm to notice that its honest man had told it, for twenty years, only the truths that suited him; and even then it did not quite believe it, for he had said so many sharp things, and surely a man who says sharp things must be brave. The reputation outlived the evidence, as reputations do, and Hollis retired full of honours, the last of which was the firm's genuine, and for once unanimous, regret." }, stem: "The narrator's attitude toward Hollis is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["admiring of his rare honesty","openly furious at his hypocrisy","coolly ironic, letting the pattern of his 'honesty' convict him","sorrowful at the tragedy of a genuinely brave man undone at last by an ungrateful and uncomprehending institution"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the narrator never denounces Hollis; the pattern (candour that 'fell silent the moment a true note would have sounded against him') does the work, cool irony. D is the elaborate trap, recasting him as a wronged brave man, which the irony refuses; A adopts the surface admiration; B overstates the temperature into open fury.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-057", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Everyone agreed that Hollis was the only honest man in the firm, and Hollis agreed with them. He said the things others merely thought; he told the chairman to his face that the new logo was hideous, told Marsh that his speech had bored the room, told the junior clerks, kindly, where their work fell short. There was a bracing weather about him, and people sought him out to be told the truth, or rather to be told that what they hoped was true was not, which they took, gratefully, for the same thing.\n\nWhat no one noticed, because it was hidden in plain sight, was that Hollis's candour never cost Hollis anything. His truths were always about other people. When his own project failed, the post-mortem was brief and oddly gentle, conducted by Hollis himself, and concluded that the market had not been ready; when a rival's failed, the inquest was long, thorough, and led, by a route Hollis laid with great fairness, to the rival. He was frank about the chairman's logo because the chairman liked to be thought a man who could take it; he was never frank about the chairman's pension arrangements, on which his own depended. His honesty, in short, was a finely tuned instrument that played only in the keys that flattered the player, and fell silent the moment a true note would have sounded against him.\n\nThe young woman who eventually replaced him saw this within a month, but said nothing, having learned from watching Hollis that the most useful truths are the ones you decline to speak. She was promoted twice in the time it took the firm to notice that its honest man had told it, for twenty years, only the truths that suited him; and even then it did not quite believe it, for he had said so many sharp things, and surely a man who says sharp things must be brave. The reputation outlived the evidence, as reputations do, and Hollis retired full of honours, the last of which was the firm's genuine, and for once unanimous, regret." }, stem: "The closing detail, that the firm's regret at his retirement was 'genuine, and for once unanimous', chiefly", format: "single_best", options: ["shows the firm had finally seen through him and was glad to be rid of him","implies its earlier doubts were unfounded, a belated tribute to a misjudged but honest servant","sharpens the irony: the firm grieves most sincerely the man it has just been shown never to have grasped","shows Hollis was, after all, a valued and well-loved colleague"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'for once unanimous' lands as irony, the firm grieving most sincerely the man the passage has just exposed it never understood. B is the twin, reading the regret as vindication of his honesty, reversing the verdict; A contradicts the stated 'regret'; D takes the sentiment at face value.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-058", genre: "prose", skill: "main_idea", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a particular pleasure we take in ruins that the buildings, when whole, never gave us, and it is worth asking what the pleasure is made of. A roofless abbey, its windows open to the weather, draws crowds that the working abbey, busy with its monks and its rents, would have turned away or set to prayer. We call the feeling reverence for the past, but reverence is an odd name for an enjoyment that depends so entirely on the building's having failed. Restore the roof, refit the glass, return the monks, and the charm is gone; what we love is precisely the defeat.\n\nPart of it, surely, is that a ruin asks nothing of us. The whole abbey made claims, on one's belief, one's money, one's time; it was an institution with purposes, and to stand inside it was to be enlisted, however faintly, in those purposes. The ruin has laid all that down. It has become scenery, and scenery makes no demands; we can admire it exactly because it can no longer ask us for anything. The feeling we mistake for piety toward the past may be closer to the relief of an heir at a graveside, decently composed, privately unburdened.\n\nAnd part of it is that ruin flatters us with a cheap transcendence. Standing among fallen stones, we are invited to reflect that all things pass, that empires fade, that we too are mortal, and we accept the invitation with a pleasant shiver and then go to lunch. The thought costs nothing because it changes nothing; it is mortality enjoyed as a view. The monk who built the place believed something that organised his every hour; we, gazing at the wreck of his belief, feel ourselves the wiser for surviving it, though all we have done is outlast it, which is not the same as having understood it, still less as having anything to put in its place.\n\nNone of which is to forbid the pleasure. It is a real pleasure, and a harmless one, provided we are honest about its grounds: that we enjoy the past most when it is safely dead, makes no claims, and lends us a borrowed depth at no charge. The danger is only in the flattery, in mistaking the ease of our feeling for the seriousness of the thing we feel it about." }, stem: "The passage sets out to establish that", format: "single_best", options: ["our pleasure in ruins comes less from reverence than from the past's having become harmless", "the contemplation of mortality is the most valuable thing ruins offer", "the modern taste for ruins betrays a culture that has lost the capacity for serious belief", "ruins ought to be restored so they can resume their original purposes"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the passage argues we love ruins because they 'make no demands' and lend 'a borrowed depth at no charge', not from real reverence. C is the trap, inflating the analysis into a sweeping verdict on cultural decline the passage does not deliver. B takes the mortality strand, treated sceptically as 'mortality enjoyed as a view', for the main claim; D misses the point entirely.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-059", genre: "prose", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a particular pleasure we take in ruins that the buildings, when whole, never gave us, and it is worth asking what the pleasure is made of. A roofless abbey, its windows open to the weather, draws crowds that the working abbey, busy with its monks and its rents, would have turned away or set to prayer. We call the feeling reverence for the past, but reverence is an odd name for an enjoyment that depends so entirely on the building's having failed. Restore the roof, refit the glass, return the monks, and the charm is gone; what we love is precisely the defeat.\n\nPart of it, surely, is that a ruin asks nothing of us. The whole abbey made claims, on one's belief, one's money, one's time; it was an institution with purposes, and to stand inside it was to be enlisted, however faintly, in those purposes. The ruin has laid all that down. It has become scenery, and scenery makes no demands; we can admire it exactly because it can no longer ask us for anything. The feeling we mistake for piety toward the past may be closer to the relief of an heir at a graveside, decently composed, privately unburdened.\n\nAnd part of it is that ruin flatters us with a cheap transcendence. Standing among fallen stones, we are invited to reflect that all things pass, that empires fade, that we too are mortal, and we accept the invitation with a pleasant shiver and then go to lunch. The thought costs nothing because it changes nothing; it is mortality enjoyed as a view. The monk who built the place believed something that organised his every hour; we, gazing at the wreck of his belief, feel ourselves the wiser for surviving it, though all we have done is outlast it, which is not the same as having understood it, still less as having anything to put in its place.\n\nNone of which is to forbid the pleasure. It is a real pleasure, and a harmless one, provided we are honest about its grounds: that we enjoy the past most when it is safely dead, makes no claims, and lends us a borrowed depth at no charge. The danger is only in the flattery, in mistaking the ease of our feeling for the seriousness of the thing we feel it about." }, stem: "The comparison to 'the relief of an heir at a graveside, decently composed, privately unburdened' chiefly conveys that", format: "single_best", options: ["our reverence for a ruin may mask a relief that its claims on us are finally over","mourners at funerals are usually, in truth, secretly glad","ruins remind us specifically of the deaths of people we have known","the admiration of the past is at bottom a form of greed, in which we wait, like heirs, to inherit the prestige of what we did nothing to build"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the heir is 'unburdened' because the demands have ended, figuring our relief that the ruin can no longer enlist us. D is the elaborate trap, twisting the image into one about greed and inherited prestige; B literalises it into a claim about real mourners; C reads 'graveside' as literal personal grief.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-060", genre: "prose", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a particular pleasure we take in ruins that the buildings, when whole, never gave us, and it is worth asking what the pleasure is made of. A roofless abbey, its windows open to the weather, draws crowds that the working abbey, busy with its monks and its rents, would have turned away or set to prayer. We call the feeling reverence for the past, but reverence is an odd name for an enjoyment that depends so entirely on the building's having failed. Restore the roof, refit the glass, return the monks, and the charm is gone; what we love is precisely the defeat.\n\nPart of it, surely, is that a ruin asks nothing of us. The whole abbey made claims, on one's belief, one's money, one's time; it was an institution with purposes, and to stand inside it was to be enlisted, however faintly, in those purposes. The ruin has laid all that down. It has become scenery, and scenery makes no demands; we can admire it exactly because it can no longer ask us for anything. The feeling we mistake for piety toward the past may be closer to the relief of an heir at a graveside, decently composed, privately unburdened.\n\nAnd part of it is that ruin flatters us with a cheap transcendence. Standing among fallen stones, we are invited to reflect that all things pass, that empires fade, that we too are mortal, and we accept the invitation with a pleasant shiver and then go to lunch. The thought costs nothing because it changes nothing; it is mortality enjoyed as a view. The monk who built the place believed something that organised his every hour; we, gazing at the wreck of his belief, feel ourselves the wiser for surviving it, though all we have done is outlast it, which is not the same as having understood it, still less as having anything to put in its place.\n\nNone of which is to forbid the pleasure. It is a real pleasure, and a harmless one, provided we are honest about its grounds: that we enjoy the past most when it is safely dead, makes no claims, and lends us a borrowed depth at no charge. The danger is only in the flattery, in mistaking the ease of our feeling for the seriousness of the thing we feel it about." }, stem: "The remark that we reflect on mortality among ruins 'and then go to lunch' functions to", format: "single_best", options: ["criticise tourists for disrespectful behaviour at historic sites", "suggest such reflections would be valuable if only taken more seriously", "contrast the trivial modern sightseer with the grave medieval believer, to the former's discredit", "shows the mortal thought the ruin prompts is pleasant precisely because it costs and changes nothing"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'go to lunch' shows the mortal thought 'costs nothing because it changes nothing', a transcendence enjoyed and dropped. C is the twin, turning the line into a sweeping put-down of moderns against medievals; A reads it as a complaint about tourist manners; B adds a prescription the passage does not make.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-061", genre: "prose", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a particular pleasure we take in ruins that the buildings, when whole, never gave us, and it is worth asking what the pleasure is made of. A roofless abbey, its windows open to the weather, draws crowds that the working abbey, busy with its monks and its rents, would have turned away or set to prayer. We call the feeling reverence for the past, but reverence is an odd name for an enjoyment that depends so entirely on the building's having failed. Restore the roof, refit the glass, return the monks, and the charm is gone; what we love is precisely the defeat.\n\nPart of it, surely, is that a ruin asks nothing of us. The whole abbey made claims, on one's belief, one's money, one's time; it was an institution with purposes, and to stand inside it was to be enlisted, however faintly, in those purposes. The ruin has laid all that down. It has become scenery, and scenery makes no demands; we can admire it exactly because it can no longer ask us for anything. The feeling we mistake for piety toward the past may be closer to the relief of an heir at a graveside, decently composed, privately unburdened.\n\nAnd part of it is that ruin flatters us with a cheap transcendence. Standing among fallen stones, we are invited to reflect that all things pass, that empires fade, that we too are mortal, and we accept the invitation with a pleasant shiver and then go to lunch. The thought costs nothing because it changes nothing; it is mortality enjoyed as a view. The monk who built the place believed something that organised his every hour; we, gazing at the wreck of his belief, feel ourselves the wiser for surviving it, though all we have done is outlast it, which is not the same as having understood it, still less as having anything to put in its place.\n\nNone of which is to forbid the pleasure. It is a real pleasure, and a harmless one, provided we are honest about its grounds: that we enjoy the past most when it is safely dead, makes no claims, and lends us a borrowed depth at no charge. The danger is only in the flattery, in mistaking the ease of our feeling for the seriousness of the thing we feel it about." }, stem: "In 'a cheap transcendence', the word 'cheap' is best understood as", format: "single_best", options: ["inexpensive in terms of money", "obtained without real cost or effort", "vulgar and in poor taste", "widely available to ordinary people"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the transcendence is 'cheap' because it is had at no charge, 'mortality enjoyed as a view' that asks nothing of us. A literalises it into money; C reads it as vulgarity; D as mere commonness, neither of which is the cost-free sense the passage presses.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-prose-062", genre: "prose", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-prose-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a particular pleasure we take in ruins that the buildings, when whole, never gave us, and it is worth asking what the pleasure is made of. A roofless abbey, its windows open to the weather, draws crowds that the working abbey, busy with its monks and its rents, would have turned away or set to prayer. We call the feeling reverence for the past, but reverence is an odd name for an enjoyment that depends so entirely on the building's having failed. Restore the roof, refit the glass, return the monks, and the charm is gone; what we love is precisely the defeat.\n\nPart of it, surely, is that a ruin asks nothing of us. The whole abbey made claims, on one's belief, one's money, one's time; it was an institution with purposes, and to stand inside it was to be enlisted, however faintly, in those purposes. The ruin has laid all that down. It has become scenery, and scenery makes no demands; we can admire it exactly because it can no longer ask us for anything. The feeling we mistake for piety toward the past may be closer to the relief of an heir at a graveside, decently composed, privately unburdened.\n\nAnd part of it is that ruin flatters us with a cheap transcendence. Standing among fallen stones, we are invited to reflect that all things pass, that empires fade, that we too are mortal, and we accept the invitation with a pleasant shiver and then go to lunch. The thought costs nothing because it changes nothing; it is mortality enjoyed as a view. The monk who built the place believed something that organised his every hour; we, gazing at the wreck of his belief, feel ourselves the wiser for surviving it, though all we have done is outlast it, which is not the same as having understood it, still less as having anything to put in its place.\n\nNone of which is to forbid the pleasure. It is a real pleasure, and a harmless one, provided we are honest about its grounds: that we enjoy the past most when it is safely dead, makes no claims, and lends us a borrowed depth at no charge. The danger is only in the flattery, in mistaking the ease of our feeling for the seriousness of the thing we feel it about." }, stem: "The final paragraph makes clear that the author's complaint is directed not at the pleasure itself but at", format: "single_best", options: ["the people who visit ruins without knowing their history","the self-flattery of mistaking an easy feeling for a serious engagement with the past","the dishonesty of those who feign a reverence they do not feel, performing an emotion they lack","governments that fail to preserve old ruins adequately"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the danger is 'the flattery, in mistaking the ease of our feeling for the seriousness of the thing'. C is the twin, recasting the charge as feigning an absent emotion, but the passage grants the pleasure is 'real', only over-rated. A and D shift the target to ignorant visitors or neglectful governments.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },

  { id: "gs1-dialectic-001", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The intellectual virtues are commonly sorted into the cautious and the bold, and the temperate mind is urged to balance them. The picture is too tidy. Doubt is praised as the engine of inquiry; yet a doubt that never settles is not rigour but paralysis, and the perpetual sceptic, forever suspending judgement, leaves behind nothing he could ever be shown to be wrong about. Conviction, by contrast, is cast as the enemy of the open mind, and so it can be; but it is also the only thing that is ever tested, for a claim no one will commit to is a claim no one will trouble to refute. The discipline worth having is therefore not a temperate blend of the two but a division of labour between them: the nerve to commit to a position fully enough that its failure will teach you something, joined to the readiness to abandon it the instant it fails.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's position is best captured as", format: "single_best", options: ["a call to hold conviction and doubt in continuous balance, the boldness to assert tempered at every turn by a standing readiness to revise","the claim that the sceptic who commits to nothing forfeits what inquiry depends on, since a position no one will defend is one no one can correct","a rehabilitation of conviction as the precondition of testing, the commitment that exposes a claim to refutation being inseparable from the willingness to abandon it once refuted","the view that because commitment is what renders a claim refutable, conviction is the senior of the two virtues, doubt arriving only afterward to dismantle what conviction has built"], answer: 2, explanation: "C holds the passage's two anchors together: conviction is 'the only thing that is ever tested' and the commitment is 'joined to the readiness to abandon it the instant it fails'. A is the conventional balance the passage explicitly rejects ('not a temperate blend'). B states only the negative half, a premise mistaken for the position. D is the near-twin that tips the division of labour into a hierarchy ('the senior'), which the passage does not assert.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-031", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The intellectual virtues are commonly sorted into the cautious and the bold, and the temperate mind is urged to balance them. The picture is too tidy. Doubt is praised as the engine of inquiry; yet a doubt that never settles is not rigour but paralysis, and the perpetual sceptic, forever suspending judgement, leaves behind nothing he could ever be shown to be wrong about. Conviction, by contrast, is cast as the enemy of the open mind, and so it can be; but it is also the only thing that is ever tested, for a claim no one will commit to is a claim no one will trouble to refute. The discipline worth having is therefore not a temperate blend of the two but a division of labour between them: the nerve to commit to a position fully enough that its failure will teach you something, joined to the readiness to abandon it the instant it fails.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The remark that the perpetual sceptic 'leaves behind nothing he could ever be shown to be wrong about' functions in the argument to", format: "single_best", options: ["concede that the sceptic, whatever inquiry loses by him, at least secures the one advantage of never being caught in a position the evidence could later overturn", "establish that doubt is of no value to inquiry, being merely the refusal to think a question through", "show that the sceptic secretly holds convictions he is unwilling to state and defend", "fault the sceptic by the passage's own test: committing to nothing, he offers nothing that inquiry could correct"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the line turns the passage's own measure ('a claim no one will commit to is a claim no one will trouble to refute') against the sceptic, so his invulnerability is sterility, not rigour. A is the trap, dressing that same invulnerability as a genuine advantage. B over-reaches into doubt being worthless, though the passage calls it the engine of inquiry; C invents a hidden hypocrisy the passage never alleges.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-032", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The intellectual virtues are commonly sorted into the cautious and the bold, and the temperate mind is urged to balance them. The picture is too tidy. Doubt is praised as the engine of inquiry; yet a doubt that never settles is not rigour but paralysis, and the perpetual sceptic, forever suspending judgement, leaves behind nothing he could ever be shown to be wrong about. Conviction, by contrast, is cast as the enemy of the open mind, and so it can be; but it is also the only thing that is ever tested, for a claim no one will commit to is a claim no one will trouble to refute. The discipline worth having is therefore not a temperate blend of the two but a division of labour between them: the nerve to commit to a position fully enough that its failure will teach you something, joined to the readiness to abandon it the instant it fails.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most undermine the passage's case for 'a division of labour' rather than a balance?", format: "single_best", options: ["claims are regularly tested by those who hold them only as hypotheses, at arm's length, so as to probe them without committing", "many thinkers cling to a committed position well past the point where the evidence has plainly turned against it", "the balanced mind that tempers boldness with caution is, in practice, the more fruitful inquirer than either extreme", "the most consequential claims are often abandoned only long after the evidence against them has piled up"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the passage's pivot is that only a committed claim gets tested; if claims are tested precisely by being held as uncommitted hypotheses, that pivot fails. B and D fault the abandonment side, which the passage already guards with 'the readiness to abandon it the instant it fails'. C merely re-asserts the temperate-blend view the passage rejects, without touching its mechanism.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-033", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The intellectual virtues are commonly sorted into the cautious and the bold, and the temperate mind is urged to balance them. The picture is too tidy. Doubt is praised as the engine of inquiry; yet a doubt that never settles is not rigour but paralysis, and the perpetual sceptic, forever suspending judgement, leaves behind nothing he could ever be shown to be wrong about. Conviction, by contrast, is cast as the enemy of the open mind, and so it can be; but it is also the only thing that is ever tested, for a claim no one will commit to is a claim no one will trouble to refute. The discipline worth having is therefore not a temperate blend of the two but a division of labour between them: the nerve to commit to a position fully enough that its failure will teach you something, joined to the readiness to abandon it the instant it fails.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'not a temperate blend of the two', 'temperate' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["judicious, guided by sound practical wisdom", "moderate, a measured mean between extremes", "abstemious, sparing in its indulgences", "tepid, wanting in real conviction"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: a 'temperate blend' is a moderate mixture, a measured mean of doubt and conviction, the balance the passage names and rejects. A (judicious) trades on temperate's warm connotation of good judgement, not its sense here, which is one of degree. C (abstemious) is the appetite sense of temperate, wrong register; D (tepid) imports a dismissiveness the neutral word does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-034", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s1", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The intellectual virtues are commonly sorted into the cautious and the bold, and the temperate mind is urged to balance them. The picture is too tidy. Doubt is praised as the engine of inquiry; yet a doubt that never settles is not rigour but paralysis, and the perpetual sceptic, forever suspending judgement, leaves behind nothing he could ever be shown to be wrong about. Conviction, by contrast, is cast as the enemy of the open mind, and so it can be; but it is also the only thing that is ever tested, for a claim no one will commit to is a claim no one will trouble to refute. The discipline worth having is therefore not a temperate blend of the two but a division of labour between them: the nerve to commit to a position fully enough that its failure will teach you something, joined to the readiness to abandon it the instant it fails.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Whose practice would the passage most approve as the 'division of labour' it recommends?", format: "single_best", options: ["a scholar who, once persuaded, throws the whole of his energy into defending his thesis against every objection and counts it a weakness ever to surrender the ground he has taken", "a thinker who suspends judgement on every disputed question until the evidence is wholly decisive", "a researcher who weighs every hypothesis against its rivals and is careful never to back one more than the others", "a scientist who stakes all on a definite conjecture, presses it until it is tested, then drops it the instant an experiment tells against it"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the endorsed discipline is 'the nerve to commit to a position fully enough that its failure will teach you something, joined to the readiness to abandon it the instant it fails', which D enacts. A is the elaborate trap, the committed half without the abandonment, the dogmatist the passage warns of. C is the temperate blend the passage rejects; B is the perpetual sceptic who commits to nothing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-002", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Tolerance is praised as a kind of openness, and its enemy is taken to be conviction: the tolerant man, we are told, is the one who holds no view strongly enough to mind another's. But this confuses tolerance with indifference. To tolerate a thing is precisely to put up with it, and one can only put up with what one objects to; where there is no objection there is nothing to tolerate, only a shrug. The tolerant man is therefore not the man without convictions but the man who has them and declines to enforce them, who keeps the disapproval and forgoes the coercion. What looks like his mildness is in fact a standing restraint, and a restraint is only worth anything in someone with the power, and the reason, to do otherwise.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim is that tolerance", format: "single_best", options: ["requires a genuine disapproval that one deliberately refrains from acting on, so that it presupposes, rather than excludes, conviction","is a restraint available only to those with the power to suppress what they dislike, and so belongs properly to the strong rather than to the weak","consists in holding no conviction firmly enough to be troubled by its rejection, a mildness of temperament rather than an exercise of will","is the highest of the social virtues, since every other virtue can be practised from indifference but tolerance alone cannot"], answer: 0, explanation: "A rests on the anchor 'keeps the disapproval and forgoes the coercion'. B inflates the closing aside about power into the thesis, true to a phrase but not the point. C is the indifference the passage names and rejects ('confuses tolerance with indifference'). D is an over-reach into a ranking of the virtues the passage never makes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-035", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Tolerance is praised as a kind of openness, and its enemy is taken to be conviction: the tolerant man, we are told, is the one who holds no view strongly enough to mind another's. But this confuses tolerance with indifference. To tolerate a thing is precisely to put up with it, and one can only put up with what one objects to; where there is no objection there is nothing to tolerate, only a shrug. The tolerant man is therefore not the man without convictions but the man who has them and declines to enforce them, who keeps the disapproval and forgoes the coercion. What looks like his mildness is in fact a standing restraint, and a restraint is only worth anything in someone with the power, and the reason, to do otherwise.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing remark that 'a restraint is only worth anything in someone with the power... to do otherwise' chiefly serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["concede that those without any power to suppress what they dislike cannot be tolerant at all, so that tolerance turns out to be a virtue available only to rulers and the strong", "imply that tolerance counts as a virtue only where one could have suppressed what one dislikes, so that it presupposes a power held in check", "warn that the tolerant man may at any moment abandon his restraint and resort to force", "suggest that tolerance is valued chiefly by the strong, who can afford to indulge it"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: a restraint means something only where one could have done otherwise, so tolerance presupposes a checked power, reinforcing that it is no mere mildness. A is the trap, hardening the point into a claim that only rulers can be tolerant, which the passage does not assert. C reads the aside as a threat of relapse; D shifts to who values tolerance, a sociological point the passage does not make.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-036", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Tolerance is praised as a kind of openness, and its enemy is taken to be conviction: the tolerant man, we are told, is the one who holds no view strongly enough to mind another's. But this confuses tolerance with indifference. To tolerate a thing is precisely to put up with it, and one can only put up with what one objects to; where there is no objection there is nothing to tolerate, only a shrug. The tolerant man is therefore not the man without convictions but the man who has them and declines to enforce them, who keeps the disapproval and forgoes the coercion. What looks like his mildness is in fact a standing restraint, and a restraint is only worth anything in someone with the power, and the reason, to do otherwise.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's claim that tolerance presupposes disapproval?", format: "single_best", options: ["many who claim to tolerate a practice in fact quietly disapprove of those who follow it", "people regularly tolerate practices they regard with pure indifference, neither approving nor objecting", "some objects of disapproval are so trivial that putting up with them costs almost nothing at all", "the powerful often tolerate what they could suppress, while the weak tolerate only because they must"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the passage insists 'where there is no objection there is nothing to tolerate'; if people genuinely tolerate things toward which they feel pure indifference, that claim fails. A actually supports the passage by finding disapproval present. C concedes the disapproval and only minimises its cost; D restates the closing point about power, not the disapproval claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-037", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Tolerance is praised as a kind of openness, and its enemy is taken to be conviction: the tolerant man, we are told, is the one who holds no view strongly enough to mind another's. But this confuses tolerance with indifference. To tolerate a thing is precisely to put up with it, and one can only put up with what one objects to; where there is no objection there is nothing to tolerate, only a shrug. The tolerant man is therefore not the man without convictions but the man who has them and declines to enforce them, who keeps the disapproval and forgoes the coercion. What looks like his mildness is in fact a standing restraint, and a restraint is only worth anything in someone with the power, and the reason, to do otherwise.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'keeps the disapproval and forgoes the coercion', 'coercion' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["persuasion by argument", "compulsion by force", "punishment after the fact", "concealment of one's view"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: to forgo coercion is to refrain from compelling by force the practice one disapproves of, the restraint the passage describes. A is coercion's opposite, winning by reasons not force; C narrows it to after-the-fact penalty; D confuses forgoing force with hiding one's opinion, which the tolerant man precisely does not do.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-038", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s2", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Tolerance is praised as a kind of openness, and its enemy is taken to be conviction: the tolerant man, we are told, is the one who holds no view strongly enough to mind another's. But this confuses tolerance with indifference. To tolerate a thing is precisely to put up with it, and one can only put up with what one objects to; where there is no objection there is nothing to tolerate, only a shrug. The tolerant man is therefore not the man without convictions but the man who has them and declines to enforce them, who keeps the disapproval and forgoes the coercion. What looks like his mildness is in fact a standing restraint, and a restraint is only worth anything in someone with the power, and the reason, to do otherwise.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which person best fits the passage's account of the genuinely tolerant man?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man who has no settled views and so is never bothered by anyone else's", "a man who privately finds his neighbour's religion absurd and seizes every chance to say so plainly, on the principle that honesty about one's disapproval is itself a kind of respect", "a man who thinks his neighbour's religion mistaken, has the standing to make trouble for him over it, and deliberately declines to", "a man who changes his own opinion to match his neighbour's so that no disagreement remains"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the tolerant man 'has them and declines to enforce them, who keeps the disapproval and forgoes the coercion', exactly C. A is the indifferent shrug the passage denies is tolerance; B keeps the disapproval but airs it aggressively, which is not the forbearance described; D dissolves the disagreement, leaving nothing to tolerate.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-003", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The radical presents reform and tradition as enemies, and asks us to choose. But the choice is not available in the form he offers it. To call a change an improvement is to measure it against some standard of better and worse, and that standard is not invented in the moment of reform; it is inherited, part of the very tradition the reformer proposes to sweep away. A wholesale rejection of the past would carry off, along with its errors, the criteria by which we recognised them as errors, leaving nothing by which the new could be judged superior to the old. The reformer is thus not the enemy of tradition but its most demanding heir: he keeps faith with its standards by refusing its present failures to meet them.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central argument is that", format: "single_best", options: ["tradition and reform are opposed forces, and the wise course is to temper the appetite for change with a due respect for what has been inherited","because every standard of judgement is inherited, no genuinely radical reform is ever possible, and all change is merely the tradition rearranging itself","the reformer should retain the sound parts of a tradition and discard its errors, since any tradition is a mixture of the valuable and the worthless","reform presupposes the very tradition it opposes, since the standards by which a change counts as an improvement are themselves inherited from that tradition"], answer: 3, explanation: "D rests on 'that standard ... is inherited' and 'keeps faith with its standards'. A is the choose-and-temper framing the passage refuses. B over-reaches: the passage allows radical reform, only insisting it borrows inherited standards, not that reform is impossible. C relocates the point from the standard of judgement to the keeping of good 'parts', a different and weaker claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-039", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The radical presents reform and tradition as enemies, and asks us to choose. But the choice is not available in the form he offers it. To call a change an improvement is to measure it against some standard of better and worse, and that standard is not invented in the moment of reform; it is inherited, part of the very tradition the reformer proposes to sweep away. A wholesale rejection of the past would carry off, along with its errors, the criteria by which we recognised them as errors, leaving nothing by which the new could be judged superior to the old. The reformer is thus not the enemy of tradition but its most demanding heir: he keeps faith with its standards by refusing its present failures to meet them.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The description of the reformer as tradition's 'most demanding heir' chiefly serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["soften the radical's position by granting that some reverence for the past must always temper even the boldest programme of change", "concede that reformers, despite themselves, usually end by preserving more of the old order than they overturn", "recast the reformer not as tradition's enemy but as the one who holds it to its own inherited standards by refusing its present failures", "praise the reformer's superior seriousness over those content merely to conserve the past"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: an heir inherits, so the phrase makes the reformer the keeper of the tradition's own standards, 'refusing its present failures to meet them'. A is the trap, reading the line as the temper-your-zeal balance the passage rejects. B turns it into an empirical claim about how much survives; D reduces it to a compliment about seriousness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-040", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The radical presents reform and tradition as enemies, and asks us to choose. But the choice is not available in the form he offers it. To call a change an improvement is to measure it against some standard of better and worse, and that standard is not invented in the moment of reform; it is inherited, part of the very tradition the reformer proposes to sweep away. A wholesale rejection of the past would carry off, along with its errors, the criteria by which we recognised them as errors, leaving nothing by which the new could be judged superior to the old. The reformer is thus not the enemy of tradition but its most demanding heir: he keeps faith with its standards by refusing its present failures to meet them.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most undermine the passage's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["a reformer can appeal to a standard of better and worse that he reasons out from first principles, owing nothing to the tradition he rejects", "most actual reformers in fact retain large parts of the traditions they claim to oppose", "traditions frequently contain standards that flatly contradict one another, so that 'the tradition' speaks with no single voice", "some reforms have made things worse rather than better when judged after the fact"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the argument turns on every standard of improvement being inherited; if a reformer can ground one in first principles independent of the tradition, that claim fails. B concedes the inheritance point rather than denying it. C complicates 'the tradition' but still leaves the standard inherited; D is about reforms' outcomes, not the source of the standard.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-041", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The radical presents reform and tradition as enemies, and asks us to choose. But the choice is not available in the form he offers it. To call a change an improvement is to measure it against some standard of better and worse, and that standard is not invented in the moment of reform; it is inherited, part of the very tradition the reformer proposes to sweep away. A wholesale rejection of the past would carry off, along with its errors, the criteria by which we recognised them as errors, leaving nothing by which the new could be judged superior to the old. The reformer is thus not the enemy of tradition but its most demanding heir: he keeps faith with its standards by refusing its present failures to meet them.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'A wholesale rejection of the past', 'wholesale' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["gradual and piecemeal", "done in bulk for resale to traders", "complete and indiscriminate", "reluctant and half-hearted"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: a wholesale rejection is a total, across-the-board one, sweeping away the whole past at once. B is the trap, the literal commercial sense of wholesale (selling in bulk). A is its opposite, a partial rejection; D imports a hesitancy the word does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-042", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s3", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The radical presents reform and tradition as enemies, and asks us to choose. But the choice is not available in the form he offers it. To call a change an improvement is to measure it against some standard of better and worse, and that standard is not invented in the moment of reform; it is inherited, part of the very tradition the reformer proposes to sweep away. A wholesale rejection of the past would carry off, along with its errors, the criteria by which we recognised them as errors, leaving nothing by which the new could be judged superior to the old. The reformer is thus not the enemy of tradition but its most demanding heir: he keeps faith with its standards by refusing its present failures to meet them.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best illustrates the self-defeat the passage attributes to wholesale rejection?", format: "single_best", options: ["a reformer who keeps the tradition's ideal of justice, improves the law in its name, and so quietly proves himself the heir the passage describes rather than the radical it criticises", "a radical who discards every inherited standard as superstition and then has no measure left by which to call his new order better than the old", "a conservative who resists all change because the old ways have lasted and so must be sound", "a reformer whose sound proposals are rejected by people too attached to custom to weigh them"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: stripping away the inherited criteria leaves 'nothing by which the new could be judged superior to the old', the self-defeat the passage names. A is the trap, a real case but of the demanding heir the passage approves, not the radical it faults. C illustrates mere conservatism; D is about reform's reception, not its incoherence.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-004", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Those who would replace retribution with deterrence think they are removing cruelty from punishment. In fact they remove the possibility of mercy. To deter is to set the penalty that will best discourage the offence; on that calculation there is no room for mercy, for to punish less than deterrence requires is simply to miscalculate, and to punish more is mere waste. Mercy can enter only where desert has first set a ceiling: where we can say the offender deserves this much, and then, for reasons of our own, exact less. Strip out desert and you strip out the gap between what is owed and what is taken in which mercy lives. The humane reformer, abolishing the harsh idea of just deserts, abolishes with it the gentlest thing he hoped to keep.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central contention is that", format: "single_best", options: ["punishment should be founded on what the offender deserves rather than on its social usefulness, since usefulness alone could justify any cruelty","a purely deterrent justification of punishment leaves no room for mercy, because mercy requires a measure of desert from which one may then choose to fall short","deterrence and desert should both inform punishment, the one fixing its purpose and the other its limit, so that neither alone suffices","deterrence theories are incoherent, since one cannot know in advance which penalty will in fact discourage an offence"], answer: 1, explanation: "B rests on 'Mercy can enter only where desert has first set a ceiling'. A is a genuine retributivist thesis but not this one; the passage's specific point is about mercy, not a slope to cruelty. C is a balance the passage does not propose: it makes desert the precondition of mercy, not a co-equal partner. D is a different, epistemic objection the passage never raises.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-043", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Those who would replace retribution with deterrence think they are removing cruelty from punishment. In fact they remove the possibility of mercy. To deter is to set the penalty that will best discourage the offence; on that calculation there is no room for mercy, for to punish less than deterrence requires is simply to miscalculate, and to punish more is mere waste. Mercy can enter only where desert has first set a ceiling: where we can say the offender deserves this much, and then, for reasons of our own, exact less. Strip out desert and you strip out the gap between what is owed and what is taken in which mercy lives. The humane reformer, abolishing the harsh idea of just deserts, abolishes with it the gentlest thing he hoped to keep.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The observation that 'to punish less than deterrence requires is simply to miscalculate' is meant to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["a purely deterrent frame has no place for leniency as such, since any downward departure can only count as an error in the sum", "deterrence, rightly applied, will always tend toward the severest penalties available, because the harsher the threat the more effectively it discourages the offence", "those who calculate deterrence are, in practice, worse at the arithmetic than they suppose", "deterrence and mercy can be reconciled once the penalty is set a little below the deterring level"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: if punishing below the deterring level is just miscalculation, the frame leaves room only for error, not for a deliberate merciful softening, the passage's point. B is the trap, sliding into maximum severity, where the passage says deterrence fixes a precise level, neither less nor more. C takes 'miscalculate' as poor arithmetic; D invents a reconciliation the passage denies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-044", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Those who would replace retribution with deterrence think they are removing cruelty from punishment. In fact they remove the possibility of mercy. To deter is to set the penalty that will best discourage the offence; on that calculation there is no room for mercy, for to punish less than deterrence requires is simply to miscalculate, and to punish more is mere waste. Mercy can enter only where desert has first set a ceiling: where we can say the offender deserves this much, and then, for reasons of our own, exact less. Strip out desert and you strip out the gap between what is owed and what is taken in which mercy lives. The humane reformer, abolishing the harsh idea of just deserts, abolishes with it the gentlest thing he hoped to keep.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's claim that deterrence leaves no room for mercy?", format: "single_best", options: ["even systems built on desert are, in practice, frequently administered with no mercy at all", "the penalty that would best deter a given offence can rarely be known with any precision", "a deterrent system can publish fixed grounds of exception on which it imposes less than the deterring penalty, answering to compassion, not recalculation", "most offenders, the evidence suggests, are deterred far less by how harsh a penalty looks on paper than by their sense of how likely they are to be caught and brought to court at all"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: mercy, the passage says, needs a desert-ceiling to fall short of; if a deterrent system can build in compassionate exceptions that are not disguised recalculations, mercy enters without desert and the claim fails. D is the longest and most topical but concerns what deters, not whether mercy is possible. A grants desert yet notes mercy is often unused, a different point; B is an epistemic objection to deterrence generally.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-045", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Those who would replace retribution with deterrence think they are removing cruelty from punishment. In fact they remove the possibility of mercy. To deter is to set the penalty that will best discourage the offence; on that calculation there is no room for mercy, for to punish less than deterrence requires is simply to miscalculate, and to punish more is mere waste. Mercy can enter only where desert has first set a ceiling: where we can say the offender deserves this much, and then, for reasons of our own, exact less. Strip out desert and you strip out the gap between what is owed and what is taken in which mercy lives. The humane reformer, abolishing the harsh idea of just deserts, abolishes with it the gentlest thing he hoped to keep.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'for reasons of our own, exact less', the word 'exact' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["to weigh up precisely", "to remit and forgo", "to demand and take", "to deserve"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'exact less' means to demand and take less than is owed, the verb exact meaning to extract or levy. B is the trap, importing the sentence's mercy into the word itself, but to exact is to take, not to forgo. A leans on the adjective exact (precise); D confuses exacting with the desert behind it.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-046", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s4", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Those who would replace retribution with deterrence think they are removing cruelty from punishment. In fact they remove the possibility of mercy. To deter is to set the penalty that will best discourage the offence; on that calculation there is no room for mercy, for to punish less than deterrence requires is simply to miscalculate, and to punish more is mere waste. Mercy can enter only where desert has first set a ceiling: where we can say the offender deserves this much, and then, for reasons of our own, exact less. Strip out desert and you strip out the gap between what is owed and what is taken in which mercy lives. The humane reformer, abolishing the harsh idea of just deserts, abolishes with it the gentlest thing he hoped to keep.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best illustrates the mercy the author says a deterrent system cannot accommodate?", format: "single_best", options: ["a judge who cuts a sentence on concluding that a lighter penalty will discourage the offence just as surely as a heavier one would have done", "a judge who raises a sentence above the usual level to make an example that will deter others", "a parole board that releases an offender early once it judges he no longer poses any risk of reoffending", "a judge who, having settled what the offence deserves, imposes less than that out of compassion for the offender's circumstances"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: mercy is to fix what is deserved and then 'for reasons of our own, exact less', which D does out of compassion. A is the near-twin trap: lowering the penalty because a lighter one deters equally is a deterrent recalculation, not mercy. B is deterrent severity; C turns on future risk, a forward-looking judgement rather than mercy against desert.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-005", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against privacy is put in a single phrase: if you have nothing to hide, you have nothing to fear. The phrase assumes that what privacy protects is secrets, and that a secret is a thing one would be ashamed to have known. But most of what we keep private is not shameful at all; it is merely ours to place. A medical fact is not disgraceful, yet it means one thing told to a doctor and another posted to an employer; the same words, true in both mouths, carry a different force in different rooms. What privacy guards is not the concealment of the discreditable but the authority to decide the context in which true things about us appear. To lose it is not to be exposed in one's vices but to be deprived of that authorship, even where one has done no wrong.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is primarily concerned to argue that privacy", format: "single_best", options: ["protects not the hiding of shameful secrets but a person's authority over the context in which true information about them is disclosed","is breached whenever any information is moved from the setting in which it was given to any other, since meaning depends entirely on context","matters chiefly to those with something discreditable to conceal, and so need not greatly concern the honest","is best understood as control over personal information, the right to determine what others may collect and store about oneself"], answer: 0, explanation: "A rests on 'the authority to decide the context in which true things about us appear'. B takes the context point and absolutises it ('whenever ... any other ... entirely'), a stronger claim than the passage makes. C is the 'nothing to hide' view the passage rebuts. D is the near-twin: a real privacy theory about collection and storage, where the passage's claim is specifically about authorship of the context of disclosure.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-047", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against privacy is put in a single phrase: if you have nothing to hide, you have nothing to fear. The phrase assumes that what privacy protects is secrets, and that a secret is a thing one would be ashamed to have known. But most of what we keep private is not shameful at all; it is merely ours to place. A medical fact is not disgraceful, yet it means one thing told to a doctor and another posted to an employer; the same words, true in both mouths, carry a different force in different rooms. What privacy guards is not the concealment of the discreditable but the authority to decide the context in which true things about us appear. To lose it is not to be exposed in one's vices but to be deprived of that authorship, even where one has done no wrong.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The example of the medical fact (told to a doctor, posted to an employer) chiefly serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["show that medical information is especially sensitive and deserves the law's strongest protection", "illustrate that the same true statement carries a different force in different settings, so that what privacy protects is control of context, not concealment", "establish that no fact about a person has any fixed meaning at all, its significance being created entirely by the audience that happens to receive it", "prove that information, once disclosed to anyone, can no longer be kept private from anyone else"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: 'the same words, true in both mouths, carry a different force in different rooms', so the example shows privacy guards context, not secrecy. C is the trap, inflating context-dependence into the claim that facts have no fixed meaning at all, which the passage does not say. A reduces it to medical sensitivity; D draws a spread-of-information moral the example does not support.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-048", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against privacy is put in a single phrase: if you have nothing to hide, you have nothing to fear. The phrase assumes that what privacy protects is secrets, and that a secret is a thing one would be ashamed to have known. But most of what we keep private is not shameful at all; it is merely ours to place. A medical fact is not disgraceful, yet it means one thing told to a doctor and another posted to an employer; the same words, true in both mouths, carry a different force in different rooms. What privacy guards is not the concealment of the discreditable but the authority to decide the context in which true things about us appear. To lose it is not to be exposed in one's vices but to be deprived of that authorship, even where one has done no wrong.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's account of privacy?", format: "single_best", options: ["some true facts about a person genuinely do mean the same thing in every setting they are repeated in", "people often share private information carelessly, undercutting any authority they might have had over it", "in nearly every case people treat as private, what they protect is something they would be embarrassed to have known", "employers can usually infer medical facts from other information even when they are not told them directly"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage's case rests on most private matters being 'not shameful at all'; if what people guard is almost always something embarrassing, the rival 'nothing to hide' account it rejects is largely restored. A grants the odd context-free fact but leaves the general claim standing; B is about carelessness, not what privacy protects; D is a side point about inference.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-049", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against privacy is put in a single phrase: if you have nothing to hide, you have nothing to fear. The phrase assumes that what privacy protects is secrets, and that a secret is a thing one would be ashamed to have known. But most of what we keep private is not shameful at all; it is merely ours to place. A medical fact is not disgraceful, yet it means one thing told to a doctor and another posted to an employer; the same words, true in both mouths, carry a different force in different rooms. What privacy guards is not the concealment of the discreditable but the authority to decide the context in which true things about us appear. To lose it is not to be exposed in one's vices but to be deprived of that authorship, even where one has done no wrong.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'the concealment of the discreditable', 'discreditable' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["bringing shame or disgrace", "impossible to believe", "yielding no profit", "kept deliberately hidden"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the discreditable is what would shame one if known, which the passage says privacy is wrongly assumed to hide. B is the trap, reading discreditable as 'not credible, hard to believe'; C confuses it with unprofitable; D restates concealment rather than defining the word.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-050", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s5", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The case against privacy is put in a single phrase: if you have nothing to hide, you have nothing to fear. The phrase assumes that what privacy protects is secrets, and that a secret is a thing one would be ashamed to have known. But most of what we keep private is not shameful at all; it is merely ours to place. A medical fact is not disgraceful, yet it means one thing told to a doctor and another posted to an employer; the same words, true in both mouths, carry a different force in different rooms. What privacy guards is not the concealment of the discreditable but the authority to decide the context in which true things about us appear. To lose it is not to be exposed in one's vices but to be deprived of that authorship, even where one has done no wrong.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best fits the loss of privacy the passage describes, even where 'one has done no wrong'?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man caught concealing a genuine fraud, who complains that his privacy has been invaded", "a woman whose ordinary, blameless medical history is passed from her clinic to her employer without her leave", "a public official whose expense claims, made with public money, are published in full despite his strong preference that the details of his spending be kept from the voters who funded it", "a man who freely tells a stranger his salary and later wishes he had not"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: a blameless fact moved from clinic to employer strips the 'authority to decide the context', the very loss the passage names, even where one has done no wrong. A involves real wrongdoing, the shame-hiding case the passage sets aside; C concerns public money owed to public scrutiny, where the authorship claim is weakest; D is a disclosure the man chose, not one taken from him.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-006", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We admire the soldier who feels no fear, and we call him brave; but the words sit badly together. Courage is not the absence of fear but its mastery: it is shown in doing the thing while afraid, in the will overruling the flinch. The man who feels nothing has nothing to overrule; his steadiness costs him no effort and proves no strength, for there was never anything in him pulling the other way. We may envy his composure, but we should not credit him with a virtue, any more than we credit a man with temperance who simply has no appetites. What looks like the highest courage, the perfect calm under fire, may be the one case where courage is wholly absent, there being nothing for it to do.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim is that the fearless man", format: "single_best", options: ["cannot possess any of the virtues, since every virtue consists in the mastery of a contrary impulse it presupposes","displays the highest form of courage, doing the dangerous thing without the inner struggle that troubles lesser men","cannot be called brave, because courage consists in mastering a fear he does not feel, and where there is nothing to overcome there is no courage to show","deserves our envy but not our imitation, since his composure is a matter of temperament rather than a discipline that others could acquire"], answer: 2, explanation: "C rests on 'Courage is not the absence of fear but its mastery'. A over-extends the temperance analogy to all the virtues; the passage uses it only to illuminate courage. B is the admiring view the passage opens by rejecting. D is a near-twin about temperament versus discipline, where the passage's claim is the stronger one that he lacks the virtue, not merely that he is inimitable.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-051", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We admire the soldier who feels no fear, and we call him brave; but the words sit badly together. Courage is not the absence of fear but its mastery: it is shown in doing the thing while afraid, in the will overruling the flinch. The man who feels nothing has nothing to overrule; his steadiness costs him no effort and proves no strength, for there was never anything in him pulling the other way. We may envy his composure, but we should not credit him with a virtue, any more than we credit a man with temperance who simply has no appetites. What looks like the highest courage, the perfect calm under fire, may be the one case where courage is wholly absent, there being nothing for it to do.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The comparison with 'a man... who simply has no appetites' chiefly works to", format: "single_best", options: ["show by parallel that a steadiness costing no struggle is no more courage than appetite-free abstinence is temperance", "concede that the fearless soldier does possess one virtue at least, namely the temperance that comes of wanting nothing he ought not to want, even if courage is denied him", "suggest that the truly virtuous person must feel and master every passion, fear and appetite alike, in a single discipline", "imply that temperance, like courage, is admired more than it really deserves to be"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: as the appetite-free man earns no credit for temperance, so the fearless man earns none for courage, the parallel's point that virtue is the mastery of a contrary pull. B is the trap, misreading the comparison as granting the soldier temperance. C universalises into mastering every passion at once; D turns it into a debunking of temperance's standing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-052", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We admire the soldier who feels no fear, and we call him brave; but the words sit badly together. Courage is not the absence of fear but its mastery: it is shown in doing the thing while afraid, in the will overruling the flinch. The man who feels nothing has nothing to overrule; his steadiness costs him no effort and proves no strength, for there was never anything in him pulling the other way. We may envy his composure, but we should not credit him with a virtue, any more than we credit a man with temperance who simply has no appetites. What looks like the highest courage, the perfect calm under fire, may be the one case where courage is wholly absent, there being nothing for it to do.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's claim that the fearless man cannot be brave?", format: "single_best", options: ["soldiers who feel no fear at all are extremely rare, most courage being shown by the frightened", "we rightly credit virtues so settled they cost no inner struggle, as with the honest man who feels no pull to steal", "fear can be so overwhelming that no amount of will could master it, so that some who flee are not cowards", "the fearless soldier may have conquered his fear so long ago that he has simply forgotten ever feeling it"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the passage holds that where there is no struggle there is no virtue; if we rightly honour effortless, settled virtue elsewhere, the no-struggle-no-courage rule is undercut at its root. A concedes the case is rare without denying it; C is about excusable flight, a different issue; D suggests hidden past fear rather than challenging the principle.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-053", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We admire the soldier who feels no fear, and we call him brave; but the words sit badly together. Courage is not the absence of fear but its mastery: it is shown in doing the thing while afraid, in the will overruling the flinch. The man who feels nothing has nothing to overrule; his steadiness costs him no effort and proves no strength, for there was never anything in him pulling the other way. We may envy his composure, but we should not credit him with a virtue, any more than we credit a man with temperance who simply has no appetites. What looks like the highest courage, the perfect calm under fire, may be the one case where courage is wholly absent, there being nothing for it to do.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'we credit a man with temperance', 'temperance' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["an even, unexcitable disposition", "self-restraint in the face of appetite", "total abstinence from all indulgence", "calmness under provocation"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: temperance here is the mastering of appetite, which the passage parallels with mastering fear. A is the trap, confusing temperance with a placid temperament, a matter of inborn temper rather than discipline. C overstates it into total abstinence; D slides toward patience under provocation.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-054", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s6", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We admire the soldier who feels no fear, and we call him brave; but the words sit badly together. Courage is not the absence of fear but its mastery: it is shown in doing the thing while afraid, in the will overruling the flinch. The man who feels nothing has nothing to overrule; his steadiness costs him no effort and proves no strength, for there was never anything in him pulling the other way. We may envy his composure, but we should not credit him with a virtue, any more than we credit a man with temperance who simply has no appetites. What looks like the highest courage, the perfect calm under fire, may be the one case where courage is wholly absent, there being nothing for it to do.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Whom would the passage most readily credit with courage?", format: "single_best", options: ["a soldier so constituted that danger stirs nothing in him at all, who walks through fire with the same calm he would bring to a stroll, and is decorated for a composure that costs him no effort whatever", "a soldier who feels no fear but performs his duty flawlessly under the heaviest fire", "a soldier who is badly frightened under fire and makes himself go forward anyway", "a soldier who avoids dangerous postings and so is never really tested at all"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: courage is 'doing the thing while afraid, the will overruling the flinch', exactly C. A is the elaborate trap, the effortless calm the passage calls 'the one case where courage is wholly absent'. B is the same fearless case in plainer dress; D is never tested, so shows nothing either way.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-007", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a kind of giver who keeps an account. He confers a benefit and waits, and what he waits for is return: not the same coin, perhaps, but its equivalent in deference, or service, or a benefit back. We call this generosity, but it is trade conducted on a long settlement. The true gift is known by the impossibility of repaying it, for repayment would convert it into the very transaction it was meant to escape; the moment a kindness can be squared, it was a loan. Hence the peculiar logic of gratitude: it is owed precisely where it cannot be discharged, and the attempt to discharge it, to be quits with one's benefactor, is not the fulfilment of gratitude but its refusal, a wish to owe nothing and so to have received nothing freely.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central paradox is that gratitude", format: "single_best", options: ["is a debt like any other, to be acknowledged and then, as soon as one is able, repaid in full so that the parties stand equal again","is never genuinely felt, since every benefactor secretly expects a return and every beneficiary secretly resents the obligation incurred","should be expressed in feeling rather than in repayment, since a benefactor values the recipient's warmth more than any material return","is properly owed only where it cannot be repaid, since to repay a kindness is to convert it into the very transaction a true gift was meant to escape"], answer: 3, explanation: "D rests on 'it is owed precisely where it cannot be discharged'. A is the settlement view the passage rejects. B is a cynical over-claim about motives the passage does not make. C is a sentimental near-miss: the passage's point is structural, that repayment cancels the gift, not merely that warmth is preferred to material return.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-055", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a kind of giver who keeps an account. He confers a benefit and waits, and what he waits for is return: not the same coin, perhaps, but its equivalent in deference, or service, or a benefit back. We call this generosity, but it is trade conducted on a long settlement. The true gift is known by the impossibility of repaying it, for repayment would convert it into the very transaction it was meant to escape; the moment a kindness can be squared, it was a loan. Hence the peculiar logic of gratitude: it is owed precisely where it cannot be discharged, and the attempt to discharge it, to be quits with one's benefactor, is not the fulfilment of gratitude but its refusal, a wish to owe nothing and so to have received nothing freely.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that 'the moment a kindness can be squared, it was a loan' chiefly works to", format: "single_best", options: ["mark the true gift off from exchange by its very unrepayability, so that to settle the account would show it had been a transaction all along", "establish that anyone who accepts a kindness incurs a debt he is morally bound to discharge as soon as he is able, lest the giver be left out of pocket by his generosity", "warn that benefactors often disguise loans as gifts in order to secure a return without seeming to ask for one", "suggest that gratitude is best expressed by promptly returning a benefit of equal value"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: if a kindness that can be squared 'was a loan', then the genuine gift is precisely the one that cannot be repaid, the passage's distinction. B is the trap, turning the gift back into the debt-to-be-paid the passage denies it is. C imports a charge of disguised self-interest; D recommends the very squaring the passage calls a refusal of gratitude.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-056", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a kind of giver who keeps an account. He confers a benefit and waits, and what he waits for is return: not the same coin, perhaps, but its equivalent in deference, or service, or a benefit back. We call this generosity, but it is trade conducted on a long settlement. The true gift is known by the impossibility of repaying it, for repayment would convert it into the very transaction it was meant to escape; the moment a kindness can be squared, it was a loan. Hence the peculiar logic of gratitude: it is owed precisely where it cannot be discharged, and the attempt to discharge it, to be quits with one's benefactor, is not the fulfilment of gratitude but its refusal, a wish to owe nothing and so to have received nothing freely.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's account of the true gift?", format: "single_best", options: ["benefactors usually do hope, however faintly, for some eventual return on their generosity", "the word gift is often used loosely for what are really loans or trades", "genuine gifts are freely returned in kind between equals without becoming a mere settling of accounts", "feelings of gratitude tend to fade once a favour has been repaid"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage defines the true gift by the impossibility of repayment; if free mutual giving among equals is genuine gift-giving without becoming mere exchange, that defining mark fails. A grants the accountant-giver the passage already sets aside; B is a point about loose usage; D concerns the duration of a feeling, not whether repayment cancels the gift.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-057", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a kind of giver who keeps an account. He confers a benefit and waits, and what he waits for is return: not the same coin, perhaps, but its equivalent in deference, or service, or a benefit back. We call this generosity, but it is trade conducted on a long settlement. The true gift is known by the impossibility of repaying it, for repayment would convert it into the very transaction it was meant to escape; the moment a kindness can be squared, it was a loan. Hence the peculiar logic of gratitude: it is owed precisely where it cannot be discharged, and the attempt to discharge it, to be quits with one's benefactor, is not the fulfilment of gratitude but its refusal, a wish to owe nothing and so to have received nothing freely.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'the attempt to discharge it, to be quits with one's benefactor', 'discharge' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["to release from employment", "to pay off and so be free of", "to perform a required duty", "to unburden oneself of a feeling"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: to discharge a debt of gratitude is to pay it off so as to 'be quits', which the passage glosses directly. A is the trap, the dismiss-from-a-post sense of discharge; C takes the carry-out-a-duty sense; D the emotional-release sense, neither of which is the squaring of an account meant here.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-058", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s7", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a kind of giver who keeps an account. He confers a benefit and waits, and what he waits for is return: not the same coin, perhaps, but its equivalent in deference, or service, or a benefit back. We call this generosity, but it is trade conducted on a long settlement. The true gift is known by the impossibility of repaying it, for repayment would convert it into the very transaction it was meant to escape; the moment a kindness can be squared, it was a loan. Hence the peculiar logic of gratitude: it is owed precisely where it cannot be discharged, and the attempt to discharge it, to be quits with one's benefactor, is not the fulfilment of gratitude but its refusal, a wish to owe nothing and so to have received nothing freely.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Whose conduct would the passage count as a refusal of gratitude rather than its fulfilment?", format: "single_best", options: ["a woman who, deeply moved by a stranger's help, spends years quietly looking for some chance to do an equal kindness to a stranger of her own, so as to pass the benefit on rather than hold it", "a man who, helped in a crisis by a friend, insists on at once paying him a sum that cancels the favour and leaves the two of them exactly even", "a man who thanks his benefactor warmly and acknowledges a debt he knows he cannot repay", "a woman who accepts a gift gracefully and never thinks about it again"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: insisting on squaring the favour so the two are 'exactly even' is the wish 'to owe nothing and so to have received nothing freely', which the passage calls the refusal of gratitude. A passes the benefit on without claiming to cancel it, not a settling of the account; C is the gratitude the passage endorses, owed where it cannot be discharged; D is mere forgetfulness, not the refusal described.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-008", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why must a promise be kept? The useful answer is that promise-keeping does good: it lets people rely on one another, and a world of reliable people goes better than a world of liars. But this answer, pressed, dissolves the thing it would explain. If the reason to keep a promise is the good that keeping does, then where breaking would do more good, one ought to break; and a promise one may break whenever breaking pays is not a promise but a forecast of one's likely conduct. The binding force of a promise must therefore lie not in the benefits of keeping it but in the act of having given one's word, which creates an obligation that holds even, and especially, when keeping it costs more than it returns. The useful defence of promising, taken to the end, leaves no promises to defend.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author argues that the obligation to keep a promise", format: "single_best", options: ["rests partly on the good that keeping promises does and partly on the word given, the two together accounting for a force neither could supply alone","cannot rest on the benefits of keeping it, since that ground would license breaking it whenever breaking did more good, leaving no genuine promise at all","is justified by the social usefulness of a world in which people can rely on one another's word","shows that consequences are irrelevant to morality, and that the rightness of an act never depends on what it brings about"], answer: 1, explanation: "B rests on 'a promise one may break whenever breaking pays is not a promise'. A is a balance the passage refuses; the useful ground, it argues, dissolves the obligation rather than half-supporting it. C is the useful answer the passage refutes. D over-reaches from this one case to the whole of ethics, a leap the passage does not take.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-059", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why must a promise be kept? The useful answer is that promise-keeping does good: it lets people rely on one another, and a world of reliable people goes better than a world of liars. But this answer, pressed, dissolves the thing it would explain. If the reason to keep a promise is the good that keeping does, then where breaking would do more good, one ought to break; and a promise one may break whenever breaking pays is not a promise but a forecast of one's likely conduct. The binding force of a promise must therefore lie not in the benefits of keeping it but in the act of having given one's word, which creates an obligation that holds even, and especially, when keeping it costs more than it returns. The useful defence of promising, taken to the end, leaves no promises to defend.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The remark that a promise one may break whenever breaking pays 'is not a promise but a forecast of one's likely conduct' chiefly serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["show that grounding the obligation in good consequences empties the promise of binding force, reducing it to a prediction one is free to revise", "concede that promises are, in the end, simply reliable predictions about future behaviour, which is all that those who depend on them really need them to be", "warn that people who break promises for gain are merely behaving as anyone would have predicted of them", "imply that a promise is worth keeping only when others have come to expect it to be kept"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: if the duty rests on the good that keeping does, one may break whenever breaking does more good, so the 'promise' becomes a mere forecast, the passage's reductio. B is the trap, accepting that reduction as all a promise ever was, which the passage advances precisely to reject. C reads 'forecast' as a remark about the breaker's character; D grounds the duty in others' expectations, a consequence the argument rules out.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-060", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why must a promise be kept? The useful answer is that promise-keeping does good: it lets people rely on one another, and a world of reliable people goes better than a world of liars. But this answer, pressed, dissolves the thing it would explain. If the reason to keep a promise is the good that keeping does, then where breaking would do more good, one ought to break; and a promise one may break whenever breaking pays is not a promise but a forecast of one's likely conduct. The binding force of a promise must therefore lie not in the benefits of keeping it but in the act of having given one's word, which creates an obligation that holds even, and especially, when keeping it costs more than it returns. The useful defence of promising, taken to the end, leaves no promises to defend.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["people who break promises for gain are usually found out and come to be distrusted", "most promises are in fact kept, whatever theory one holds about why they bind", "always keeping one's word beats breaking when it pays, so usefulness need not permit breach", "some promises are extracted by deceit and ought not to be kept at all"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the argument assumes the useful defence judges each act by its own payoff; if usefulness is better served by a standing rule of keeping one's word than by case-by-case calculation, the slide from 'useful' to 'breakable whenever breaking pays' is blocked. A and B describe what happens in practice without touching the principle; D notes an exception that concedes the general binding force.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-061", genre: "dialectic", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why must a promise be kept? The useful answer is that promise-keeping does good: it lets people rely on one another, and a world of reliable people goes better than a world of liars. But this answer, pressed, dissolves the thing it would explain. If the reason to keep a promise is the good that keeping does, then where breaking would do more good, one ought to break; and a promise one may break whenever breaking pays is not a promise but a forecast of one's likely conduct. The binding force of a promise must therefore lie not in the benefits of keeping it but in the act of having given one's word, which creates an obligation that holds even, and especially, when keeping it costs more than it returns. The useful defence of promising, taken to the end, leaves no promises to defend.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Calling such a promise 'a forecast of one's likely conduct' rather than a promise implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["it is an unreliable guess that frequently turns out to be mistaken", "it merely predicts what the speaker will probably do, binding him to nothing he is not already inclined to do", "the one who makes it is engaged in a kind of fraud, issuing a solemn-sounding undertaking while privately reserving the right to abandon it the moment it suits him to do so", "promising and predicting are, properly understood, one and the same speech act"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: a forecast only says what one will likely do, so it creates no obligation that holds when keeping costs more than it returns, the point of the contrast. C is the trap, reading the line as an accusation of conscious fraud, where the passage makes a structural point about obligation. A takes forecast as merely inaccurate; D collapses the very distinction the passage is drawing.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-062", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s8", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Why must a promise be kept? The useful answer is that promise-keeping does good: it lets people rely on one another, and a world of reliable people goes better than a world of liars. But this answer, pressed, dissolves the thing it would explain. If the reason to keep a promise is the good that keeping does, then where breaking would do more good, one ought to break; and a promise one may break whenever breaking pays is not a promise but a forecast of one's likely conduct. The binding force of a promise must therefore lie not in the benefits of keeping it but in the act of having given one's word, which creates an obligation that holds even, and especially, when keeping it costs more than it returns. The useful defence of promising, taken to the end, leaves no promises to defend.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which view of promising does the passage finally endorse?", format: "single_best", options: ["that a promise binds because, and only as long as, keeping it produces more good than breaking it", "that consequences have no bearing whatever on what one ought to do, the rightness of keeping a promise being entirely independent of every result that keeping or breaking it might bring about", "that a promise binds in virtue of the word having been given, an obligation that holds even when keeping it costs more than it returns", "that promises should be made only when one is confident that keeping them will prove worthwhile"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage locates the binding force 'in the act of having given one's word, which creates an obligation that holds even... when keeping it costs more than it returns'. B is the trap, overshooting into the claim that consequences never matter to morality at all, which the passage does not assert. A is the useful defence it rejects; D makes the duty conditional on expected payoff, the very thing argued against.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-009", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Be true to yourself, we are told, as though the self were a fixed text and sincerity a matter of accurate quotation. But which self? The counsel assumes that there is, beneath the choices, a settled person to whom one might be faithful or false. Yet much of what we are is made in the choosing: a man becomes patient by acting patiently before he feels it, and the self he is true to at fifty is in good part the deposit of decisions his younger self could have gone either way on. To be told to express a self that the expressing helps create is to be sent in a circle. Authenticity cannot then be fidelity to a self already there; at best it is a kind of authorship, the taking of responsibility for the self one is in the course of becoming.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central contention is that the counsel to 'be true to yourself'", format: "single_best", options: ["misdescribes authenticity as fidelity to a pre-existing self, when much of the self is made by the very choices meant to express it", "is unhelpful because people rarely know themselves well enough to say which of their competing impulses is their true self", "rightly directs us to act from our settled character rather than from passing moods or the expectations of others", "shows that there is no such thing as a self at all, only a sequence of choices with nothing underlying them"], answer: 0, explanation: "A rests on 'much of what we are is made in the choosing' and the closing 'authorship'. B is an epistemic near-miss about the difficulty of self-knowledge; the passage's claim is that there is no fixed prior self to be faithful to, not that it is hard to discern. C is the quotation picture the passage unsettles. D over-reaches into denying any self, where the passage says the self is partly made, not non-existent.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-063", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Be true to yourself, we are told, as though the self were a fixed text and sincerity a matter of accurate quotation. But which self? The counsel assumes that there is, beneath the choices, a settled person to whom one might be faithful or false. Yet much of what we are is made in the choosing: a man becomes patient by acting patiently before he feels it, and the self he is true to at fifty is in good part the deposit of decisions his younger self could have gone either way on. To be told to express a self that the expressing helps create is to be sent in a circle. Authenticity cannot then be fidelity to a self already there; at best it is a kind of authorship, the taking of responsibility for the self one is in the course of becoming.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The example of the man who 'becomes patient by acting patiently before he feels it' is offered to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["people can deliberately reinvent their characters from scratch whenever they wish, becoming whatever they decide to be by the simple expedient of acting the part until it takes", "feelings reliably follow actions, so that to change how one behaves is the surest way to change how one feels", "the self one is to be true to is in part produced by one's choices, so it cannot be a fixed thing lying ready to be expressed", "patience is a more authentic trait when it has been worked for than when it comes naturally"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the man acquires the trait by acting it, so the self is 'made in the choosing', which is why being true to a settled self cannot be what authenticity means. A is the trap, inflating gradual self-shaping into reinvention at will. B draws a general psychological moral about feeling and action; D ranks worked-for traits as more authentic, a claim the passage does not make.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-064", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Be true to yourself, we are told, as though the self were a fixed text and sincerity a matter of accurate quotation. But which self? The counsel assumes that there is, beneath the choices, a settled person to whom one might be faithful or false. Yet much of what we are is made in the choosing: a man becomes patient by acting patiently before he feels it, and the self he is true to at fifty is in good part the deposit of decisions his younger self could have gone either way on. To be told to express a self that the expressing helps create is to be sent in a circle. Authenticity cannot then be fidelity to a self already there; at best it is a kind of authorship, the taking of responsibility for the self one is in the course of becoming.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["people often act out of character for years without ever coming to feel the part they play", "the advice to be true to oneself is, in practice, interpreted in many different ways", "some choices change us far more than others, and most leave the self much as it was", "beneath acquired traits lies a stable character, fixed early, shaping which choices and traits stick"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the argument needs the self to be largely made by choice; if a fixed underlying character governs the choices and what sticks, there is after all a settled self to be true to, and the circle the passage alleges is broken. A concerns whether feeling follows action, not whether the self is made; B is about the advice's reception; C limits the effect without denying a made self.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-065", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Be true to yourself, we are told, as though the self were a fixed text and sincerity a matter of accurate quotation. But which self? The counsel assumes that there is, beneath the choices, a settled person to whom one might be faithful or false. Yet much of what we are is made in the choosing: a man becomes patient by acting patiently before he feels it, and the self he is true to at fifty is in good part the deposit of decisions his younger self could have gone either way on. To be told to express a self that the expressing helps create is to be sent in a circle. Authenticity cannot then be fidelity to a self already there; at best it is a kind of authorship, the taking of responsibility for the self one is in the course of becoming.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'the self he is true to at fifty is in good part the deposit of decisions', 'deposit' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["a sum placed somewhere for safekeeping", "an accumulated residue laid down over time", "a pledge given as security for a debt", "a sudden and unexpected windfall"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the self is the deposit of decisions in the geological sense, a residue built up by what one has chosen over the years. A is the trap, the banking sense of a deposit lodged for safekeeping; C the security-for-a-loan sense; D mistakes a slow accumulation for a sudden gain.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-066", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s9", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Be true to yourself, we are told, as though the self were a fixed text and sincerity a matter of accurate quotation. But which self? The counsel assumes that there is, beneath the choices, a settled person to whom one might be faithful or false. Yet much of what we are is made in the choosing: a man becomes patient by acting patiently before he feels it, and the self he is true to at fifty is in good part the deposit of decisions his younger self could have gone either way on. To be told to express a self that the expressing helps create is to be sent in a circle. Authenticity cannot then be fidelity to a self already there; at best it is a kind of authorship, the taking of responsibility for the self one is in the course of becoming.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "On the passage's view, what would 'authenticity' best consist in?", format: "single_best", options: ["faithfully expressing the settled self one already is, beneath the layers of convention", "taking responsibility for the self one is in the course of becoming through one's choices", "discovering, by long and honest introspection, the one true self that lies hidden beneath one's habits and roles, and then refusing ever to act against it", "acting always on one's strongest present impulse, since that is what one most truly is"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the passage ends that authenticity 'at best is a kind of authorship, the taking of responsibility for the self one is in the course of becoming'. C is the trap, the excavate-the-hidden-self picture the passage rejects as circular. A is the same pre-existing-self view; D equates the self with whatever one happens to feel, which the made-self account denies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-010", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The charge against nostalgia is that it lies about the past, gilding what was grim. But the nostalgic rarely invents; press him and every particular he offers is true. The summers were long; the bread was good; the street was safe. His falsification is not in the facts but in the editing: he remembers the long summers and forgets the longer winters, keeps the good bread and drops the rationing that made it scarce. Nostalgia is thus a lie told entirely in truths, a distortion of proportion rather than of fact, and this is why it cannot be corrected by correction. Show the nostalgic that his memories are accurate and you only confirm him; the error was never in any one of them, but in the silent omission of all that would have set them in their place.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central point about nostalgia is that", format: "single_best", options: ["it falsifies the past by exaggerating its virtues and inventing comforts that never existed, and so can be answered by an honest record","every memory is necessarily selective, so all recollection of the past is a form of nostalgia and equally unreliable","its distortion lies not in any false particular but in a selective omission of context, so that it cannot be refuted by verifying the memories it offers","it is harmful chiefly because it makes the present seem worse by comparison with a past from which all hardship has been removed"], answer: 2, explanation: "C rests on 'a lie told entirely in truths' and 'cannot be corrected by correction'. A is the invents-and-exaggerates view the passage denies. B over-generalises selectivity to all memory, a stronger claim than the passage's. D names a consequence of nostalgia rather than the structure of its distortion, which is the passage's actual subject.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-067", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The charge against nostalgia is that it lies about the past, gilding what was grim. But the nostalgic rarely invents; press him and every particular he offers is true. The summers were long; the bread was good; the street was safe. His falsification is not in the facts but in the editing: he remembers the long summers and forgets the longer winters, keeps the good bread and drops the rationing that made it scarce. Nostalgia is thus a lie told entirely in truths, a distortion of proportion rather than of fact, and this is why it cannot be corrected by correction. Show the nostalgic that his memories are accurate and you only confirm him; the error was never in any one of them, but in the silent omission of all that would have set them in their place.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Calling nostalgia 'a lie told entirely in truths' chiefly serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["establish that all memory is a kind of lying, since every recollection selects and arranges and so can never give an undistorted picture of what was", "locate its falsity not in any false particular but in what it leaves out, so that each remembered fact can be accurate and the whole still misleading", "concede that the nostalgic is, after all, strictly honest, and so to be acquitted of the charge of falsehood", "show that the nostalgic deceives others while sincerely deceiving himself first"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the distortion is 'in the editing', a matter of omission, so true particulars can compose a false whole, which is why correction cannot reach it. A is the trap, generalising from nostalgia to all memory whatever, further than the passage goes. C takes 'told in truths' as full acquittal, missing that it is still called a lie; D shifts to deceiving others, which the passage does not raise.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-068", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The charge against nostalgia is that it lies about the past, gilding what was grim. But the nostalgic rarely invents; press him and every particular he offers is true. The summers were long; the bread was good; the street was safe. His falsification is not in the facts but in the editing: he remembers the long summers and forgets the longer winters, keeps the good bread and drops the rationing that made it scarce. Nostalgia is thus a lie told entirely in truths, a distortion of proportion rather than of fact, and this is why it cannot be corrected by correction. Show the nostalgic that his memories are accurate and you only confirm him; the error was never in any one of them, but in the silent omission of all that would have set them in their place.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's account of nostalgia?", format: "single_best", options: ["people differ widely in which features of the past they choose to dwell on", "some nostalgic memories do, on examination, turn out to contain outright factual errors", "reminded of the hardships they left out, most nostalgics promptly revise their rosy picture", "the present really is, by many measures, harder than the period the nostalgic recalls"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage insists nostalgia 'cannot be corrected by correction' because the error is omission, not false fact; if supplying the omitted hardships does correct the nostalgic, that central claim fails. A notes variation without denying the omission; B finds false particulars, which would make it a simpler, refutable error; D concerns whether the past was better, not the mechanism of distortion.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-069", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The charge against nostalgia is that it lies about the past, gilding what was grim. But the nostalgic rarely invents; press him and every particular he offers is true. The summers were long; the bread was good; the street was safe. His falsification is not in the facts but in the editing: he remembers the long summers and forgets the longer winters, keeps the good bread and drops the rationing that made it scarce. Nostalgia is thus a lie told entirely in truths, a distortion of proportion rather than of fact, and this is why it cannot be corrected by correction. Show the nostalgic that his memories are accurate and you only confirm him; the error was never in any one of them, but in the silent omission of all that would have set them in their place.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'gilding what was grim', 'gilding' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["stripping of all its value", "exaggerating beyond all recognition", "fabricating out of nothing", "overlaying with a falsely attractive sheen"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: to gild the grim past is to coat it in a fine, flattering surface, making it look better than it was. A is the opposite; B reads gilding as mere exaggeration of scale; C as invention from nothing, which the passage expressly denies the nostalgic does ('every particular he offers is true').", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-070", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s10", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The charge against nostalgia is that it lies about the past, gilding what was grim. But the nostalgic rarely invents; press him and every particular he offers is true. The summers were long; the bread was good; the street was safe. His falsification is not in the facts but in the editing: he remembers the long summers and forgets the longer winters, keeps the good bread and drops the rationing that made it scarce. Nostalgia is thus a lie told entirely in truths, a distortion of proportion rather than of fact, and this is why it cannot be corrected by correction. Show the nostalgic that his memories are accurate and you only confirm him; the error was never in any one of them, but in the silent omission of all that would have set them in their place.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which response would the passage predict to be useless against a nostalgic?", format: "single_best", options: ["pointing out that other people remember the same period quite differently", "supplying the hardships and the rationing his account silently omits", "mounting a careful, document-by-document demonstration that conditions in the remembered period were in fact, by the measurable indicators of health and income, considerably worse than he supposes them to have been", "checking and confirming the accuracy of each fond memory he offers, which only ratifies the picture"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: since the error 'was never in any one of them', confirming the memories only 'confirms him', the response the passage says is useless. B is the corrective the passage actually recommends, restoring the omitted context. C is the elaborate trap, but disputing the facts attacks particulars that are true, missing that the distortion is one of proportion; A appeals to other memories rather than the missing context.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-011", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Optimism and hope are treated as the same sunny disposition, but they part company under pressure. Optimism is a forecast: it judges that things will probably turn out well, and like any forecast it stands or falls with the evidence. Let the odds worsen and the honest optimist must give ground; his cheer was a reading of the probabilities, and the probabilities have changed. Hope makes no such reading. It is not the expectation that the good will come but the refusal to let its unlikelihood be the last word, a commitment to act as if the door were open without any wager that it is. This is why hope can live exactly where optimism dies, in the worst cases, against the evidence; for it was never grounded in the evidence, and so has nothing there to lose.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage distinguishes hope from optimism chiefly by holding that hope", format: "single_best", options: ["is a stronger and more resilient form of confidence that things will work out, one less easily shaken by temporary setbacks", "like optimism, rests on a favourable reading of how events are likely to unfold, but reaches that reading more steadily", "is irrational, since it persists in the face of the very evidence that ought to extinguish it", "is not a prediction about outcomes at all, and so can persist against the evidence that defeats optimism"], answer: 3, explanation: "D rests on 'It is not the expectation that the good will come but the refusal to let its unlikelihood be the last word'. A makes hope merely a tougher optimism, the same kind more durable, where the passage makes it a different kind. B keeps hope a forecast, the conflation the passage separates. C supplies a verdict (irrational) the passage withholds; it explains hope's independence from evidence without condemning it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-071", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Optimism and hope are treated as the same sunny disposition, but they part company under pressure. Optimism is a forecast: it judges that things will probably turn out well, and like any forecast it stands or falls with the evidence. Let the odds worsen and the honest optimist must give ground; his cheer was a reading of the probabilities, and the probabilities have changed. Hope makes no such reading. It is not the expectation that the good will come but the refusal to let its unlikelihood be the last word, a commitment to act as if the door were open without any wager that it is. This is why hope can live exactly where optimism dies, in the worst cases, against the evidence; for it was never grounded in the evidence, and so has nothing there to lose.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The point that the optimist 'must give ground' when the odds worsen serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["concede that the optimist's cheer was never sincere, but only a pose maintained while the odds stayed favourable", "show that optimism, being a forecast, stands or falls with the evidence, so that worsening odds must erode it as they cannot erode hope", "warn that the optimist is dishonest if he does not drop his cheer the very moment the probabilities cease to support it, however much he would prefer to keep it", "suggest that the optimist gives up too easily, where the hopeful person presses on"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: optimism 'stands or falls with the evidence', so a fall in the odds must cost the optimist his cheer, marking the contrast with hope, which was never grounded in the evidence. A denies the optimist's sincerity, though the passage calls him honest; C overstates the contrast into a charge of dishonesty; D reduces it to a difference of willpower.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-072", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Optimism and hope are treated as the same sunny disposition, but they part company under pressure. Optimism is a forecast: it judges that things will probably turn out well, and like any forecast it stands or falls with the evidence. Let the odds worsen and the honest optimist must give ground; his cheer was a reading of the probabilities, and the probabilities have changed. Hope makes no such reading. It is not the expectation that the good will come but the refusal to let its unlikelihood be the last word, a commitment to act as if the door were open without any wager that it is. This is why hope can live exactly where optimism dies, in the worst cases, against the evidence; for it was never grounded in the evidence, and so has nothing there to lose.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's distinction between hope and optimism?", format: "single_best", options: ["in ordinary speech the words hope and optimism are used more or less interchangeably", "some optimists do cling to their cheer well past the point the evidence supports", "what we call hope carries a tacit estimate that the good is possible, and so reads the odds", "hope, for all its resilience, frequently fails to issue in any action at all"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage rests on hope making 'no such reading' of the probabilities; if hope always smuggles in an estimate of the odds, the clean line between it and optimism collapses. A is a point about usage; B describes bad optimism without touching hope; D concerns hope's effects, not whether it predicts.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-073", genre: "dialectic", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Optimism and hope are treated as the same sunny disposition, but they part company under pressure. Optimism is a forecast: it judges that things will probably turn out well, and like any forecast it stands or falls with the evidence. Let the odds worsen and the honest optimist must give ground; his cheer was a reading of the probabilities, and the probabilities have changed. Hope makes no such reading. It is not the expectation that the good will come but the refusal to let its unlikelihood be the last word, a commitment to act as if the door were open without any wager that it is. This is why hope can live exactly where optimism dies, in the worst cases, against the evidence; for it was never grounded in the evidence, and so has nothing there to lose.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of acting 'as if the door were open' implies that hope is", format: "single_best", options: ["a commitment to act toward a possibility one does not claim to predict, the open door standing for a chance kept available rather than a likelihood assessed", "a passive waiting for the longed-for outcome to arrive of its own accord", "a confident inner assurance that the door is in fact open and the desired outcome already on its way, the image expressing a serene certainty that in the end all must be well", "a stubborn refusal to admit that the door has plainly been shut"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: hope is 'a commitment to act as if the door were open without any wager that it is', so the open door is a possibility kept live, not a prediction. C is the trap, reading the image as confident certainty, which is optimism, not hope. B makes hope passive, where the passage makes it a way of acting; D reduces it to denial of the facts.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-074", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s11", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Optimism and hope are treated as the same sunny disposition, but they part company under pressure. Optimism is a forecast: it judges that things will probably turn out well, and like any forecast it stands or falls with the evidence. Let the odds worsen and the honest optimist must give ground; his cheer was a reading of the probabilities, and the probabilities have changed. Hope makes no such reading. It is not the expectation that the good will come but the refusal to let its unlikelihood be the last word, a commitment to act as if the door were open without any wager that it is. This is why hope can live exactly where optimism dies, in the worst cases, against the evidence; for it was never grounded in the evidence, and so has nothing there to lose.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best exemplifies hope as the passage defines it, as against optimism?", format: "single_best", options: ["a patient who, having studied the survival statistics for his illness, works out that his own case falls on the favourable side of them and so expects, on the balance of probabilities, to recover", "a gambler who feels sure, against all the odds, that his luck is about to turn", "a man who refuses to read his prognosis at all, so as to keep his spirits up", "a prisoner told his appeal will almost certainly fail who files it nonetheless and lives as though acquittal mattered, making no wager that it will come"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: hope 'can live exactly where optimism dies', committing to act without betting on the outcome, which the prisoner does. A is the trap, a reading of the odds, which is optimism. B is mere unfounded confidence in a good outcome; C is evasion of the evidence, not hope against it.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-012", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Sentimentality is not simply an excess of feeling; a great grief is not sentimental however large. The mark of the sentimental is that the feeling has come loose from its object and begun to feed on itself. The sentimentalist weeping over the dying child is, at the crucial moment, attending less to the child than to the fineness of his own tears; the object has become an occasion, a thing valued for the emotion it affords rather than for itself. This is why sentimentality and cruelty keep such easy company: the man who loves his own tender feeling will resent whatever interrupts it, and the real child, with its inconvenient needs, interrupts. What looks like an overflow of the heart is in truth a kind of theft, the conversion of another's plight into a private indulgence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim about sentimentality is that", format: "single_best", options: ["it consists not in too much feeling but in feeling detached from its object and valued for its own sake, so that the object serves merely as a pretext","all strong emotion is suspect, since any intense feeling tends to become more interesting to its possessor than the thing that occasioned it","it is a fault of degree, an overflowing of the heart that simply feels more than an occasion warrants","it is dangerous because it numbs us to real suffering, substituting a pleasant emotion for the action that suffering demands"], answer: 0, explanation: "A rests on 'the feeling has come loose from its object and begun to feed on itself'. B over-generalises to all strong emotion, which the passage expressly exempts ('a great grief is not sentimental'). C is the excess-of-degree view the passage opens by rejecting. D names an adjacent critique about numbing and inaction, where the passage's defining claim is the feeding-on-itself that turns to cruelty.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-075", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Sentimentality is not simply an excess of feeling; a great grief is not sentimental however large. The mark of the sentimental is that the feeling has come loose from its object and begun to feed on itself. The sentimentalist weeping over the dying child is, at the crucial moment, attending less to the child than to the fineness of his own tears; the object has become an occasion, a thing valued for the emotion it affords rather than for itself. This is why sentimentality and cruelty keep such easy company: the man who loves his own tender feeling will resent whatever interrupts it, and the real child, with its inconvenient needs, interrupts. What looks like an overflow of the heart is in truth a kind of theft, the conversion of another's plight into a private indulgence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The observation that 'sentimentality and cruelty keep such easy company' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["warn that strong emotion of any kind tends to cloud a person's moral judgement", "observe, as a curiosity, that cruel people are often the ones who weep most readily at a sad story", "support the thesis that the sentimentalist prizes his own feeling above its object, since he comes to resent the real object when it interrupts that feeling", "prove that anyone disposed to tender feeling is, beneath the surface, a cruel person merely awaiting his occasion, sentiment and cruelty being two faces of a single vicious temperament"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: cruelty follows because 'the man who loves his own tender feeling will resent whatever interrupts it', which shows the feeling has come loose from its object, the thesis. D is the trap, hardening an 'easy company' into an identity of sentiment and cruelty. A generalises to all strong emotion, which the passage excludes ('a great grief is not sentimental'); B takes the link as a mere curiosity.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-076", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Sentimentality is not simply an excess of feeling; a great grief is not sentimental however large. The mark of the sentimental is that the feeling has come loose from its object and begun to feed on itself. The sentimentalist weeping over the dying child is, at the crucial moment, attending less to the child than to the fineness of his own tears; the object has become an occasion, a thing valued for the emotion it affords rather than for itself. This is why sentimentality and cruelty keep such easy company: the man who loves his own tender feeling will resent whatever interrupts it, and the real child, with its inconvenient needs, interrupts. What looks like an overflow of the heart is in truth a kind of theft, the conversion of another's plight into a private indulgence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's account of sentimentality?", format: "single_best", options: ["people are moved to sentimental feeling by fictional characters as readily as by real ones", "the sentimentalist, once moved, in fact takes real trouble to relieve the suffering, not resenting it", "even a great and genuine grief can, over time, become absorbed in itself", "sentimental novels and pictures have always been popular with the public"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the charge is that the feeling feeds on itself and the real object, with its needs, becomes an unwelcome interruption; if the sentimentalist actually shoulders the cost of relief, that detachment-from-object claim fails. A is about what triggers feeling; C concedes that even real grief can sour, not touching the definition; D is about popularity.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-077", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Sentimentality is not simply an excess of feeling; a great grief is not sentimental however large. The mark of the sentimental is that the feeling has come loose from its object and begun to feed on itself. The sentimentalist weeping over the dying child is, at the crucial moment, attending less to the child than to the fineness of his own tears; the object has become an occasion, a thing valued for the emotion it affords rather than for itself. This is why sentimentality and cruelty keep such easy company: the man who loves his own tender feeling will resent whatever interrupts it, and the real child, with its inconvenient needs, interrupts. What looks like an overflow of the heart is in truth a kind of theft, the conversion of another's plight into a private indulgence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'the conversion of another's plight into a private indulgence', 'indulgence' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["a lenient tolerance extended to another's faults", "a remission of penance granted by the church", "an expensive and unnecessary luxury", "a gratifying of oneself"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the sentimentalist turns the other's plight into a private indulgence, a self-gratification, the feeling savoured for its own sake. B is the trap, the ecclesiastical indulgence (a pardon for sin); A is the indulgent-of-others sense; C the luxury sense, neither of which fits the self-pleasuring the passage means.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-078", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s12", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Sentimentality is not simply an excess of feeling; a great grief is not sentimental however large. The mark of the sentimental is that the feeling has come loose from its object and begun to feed on itself. The sentimentalist weeping over the dying child is, at the crucial moment, attending less to the child than to the fineness of his own tears; the object has become an occasion, a thing valued for the emotion it affords rather than for itself. This is why sentimentality and cruelty keep such easy company: the man who loves his own tender feeling will resent whatever interrupts it, and the real child, with its inconvenient needs, interrupts. What looks like an overflow of the heart is in truth a kind of theft, the conversion of another's plight into a private indulgence.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case is sentimental in the passage's sense, rather than merely strongly felt?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man who weeps at a beggar's tale yet is plainly irritated when the beggar then asks him for actual help, the tears being the thing he came for", "a soldier who grieves a fallen friend in silence for years afterward", "a mother who sits up night after night in real exhaustion beside a gravely ill child, overwhelmed by a grief so large that it leaves no room in her for any thought of herself at all", "a reader who weeps at a tragic novel one evening and has forgotten it by the next"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the feeling has detached from its object and feeds on itself, so the real beggar's request 'interrupts' and is resented, the mark of sentimentality. C is the trap, a great grief wholly fixed on its object, which the passage says is not sentimental however large. B is genuine, object-directed grief; D is a passing emotion, neither self-feeding nor cruel.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-013", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Irony begins as honesty's ally. To say one thing and mean its opposite can puncture cant, exposing the gap between a pretension and the truth. But as a settled habit it turns into the very thing it began by attacking. The permanent ironist commits to nothing, for everything he says is held at arm's length, available to be disowned: if challenged, he meant it as a joke; if praised, he half meant it after all. He purchases an immunity the sincere man never has, who can be pinned to his words and shown wrong. And immunity, not insight, becomes the point. What looked like a sharper form of truthfulness has become a way of never being caught holding anything, a refusal of the exposure that any real claim invites.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's chief charge against the permanent ironist is that", format: "single_best", options: ["irony is a corrosive force that undermines sincere conviction and ought to be abandoned in favour of plain speech", "by holding everything he says at arm's length, he buys immunity from being held to any claim, turning irony into evasion", "he can no longer be understood by others, since no one can tell when he means what he says and when he does not", "irony is incompatible with sincerity, so that no ironic remark can ever express a genuine belief"], answer: 1, explanation: "B rests on 'a way of never being caught holding anything'. A condemns irony as such, where the passage grants it 'begins as honesty's ally' and indicts only the permanent habit. C names a real consequence, unintelligibility, but not the charge, which is evasion and immunity. D is an absolutist claim the passage contradicts by allowing irony to start as honesty's ally.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-079", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Irony begins as honesty's ally. To say one thing and mean its opposite can puncture cant, exposing the gap between a pretension and the truth. But as a settled habit it turns into the very thing it began by attacking. The permanent ironist commits to nothing, for everything he says is held at arm's length, available to be disowned: if challenged, he meant it as a joke; if praised, he half meant it after all. He purchases an immunity the sincere man never has, who can be pinned to his words and shown wrong. And immunity, not insight, becomes the point. What looked like a sharper form of truthfulness has become a way of never being caught holding anything, a refusal of the exposure that any real claim invites.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The contrast between the ironist who 'if challenged, meant it as a joke; if praised, half meant it after all' and 'the sincere man... who can be pinned to his words' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["show that the ironist secures an immunity the sincere man lacks, never caught holding anything, so that immunity rather than insight has become his point", "concede that the permanent ironist is, for all his evasion, simply cleverer than the sincere man he runs rings around", "prove that the ironist never believes a single thing he says, his every statement being equally empty whether he later chooses to call it a joke or to claim he half meant it after all", "illustrate that irony, pressed far enough, makes ordinary communication between people impossible"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the joke-or-earnest escape lets the ironist disown whatever he likes, buying 'an immunity the sincere man never has', so immunity, not insight, becomes the point. C is the trap, hardening evasion into the claim that he believes nothing whatever, stronger than the passage's charge. B concedes a cleverness the passage does not grant; D turns it into a breakdown of communication, which the passage does not claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-080", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Irony begins as honesty's ally. To say one thing and mean its opposite can puncture cant, exposing the gap between a pretension and the truth. But as a settled habit it turns into the very thing it began by attacking. The permanent ironist commits to nothing, for everything he says is held at arm's length, available to be disowned: if challenged, he meant it as a joke; if praised, he half meant it after all. He purchases an immunity the sincere man never has, who can be pinned to his words and shown wrong. And immunity, not insight, becomes the point. What looked like a sharper form of truthfulness has become a way of never being caught holding anything, a refusal of the exposure that any real claim invites.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's charge against the permanent ironist?", format: "single_best", options: ["irony is a long-established literary device with a distinguished history", "some celebrated wits have been admired precisely for their unbroken irony", "on what he cares about, the habitual ironist drops irony and commits plainly", "sincere people are quite often wrong, and are then shown to be so"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the charge is that the ironist can never be 'pinned to his words' or caught holding anything; if he commits plainly on what matters to him, that immunity is not the settled habit the passage describes. A and B are points about irony's standing and reputation; D notes that sincerity carries the risk of being wrong, which actually fits the passage's contrast.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-081", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Irony begins as honesty's ally. To say one thing and mean its opposite can puncture cant, exposing the gap between a pretension and the truth. But as a settled habit it turns into the very thing it began by attacking. The permanent ironist commits to nothing, for everything he says is held at arm's length, available to be disowned: if challenged, he meant it as a joke; if praised, he half meant it after all. He purchases an immunity the sincere man never has, who can be pinned to his words and shown wrong. And immunity, not insight, becomes the point. What looked like a sharper form of truthfulness has become a way of never being caught holding anything, a refusal of the exposure that any real claim invites.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'To say one thing and mean its opposite can puncture cant', 'cant' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["a tilt or sloping angle", "a lively and rapid chatter", "the private jargon of a trade or group", "pious or insincere humbug"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: cant here is sanctimonious, hollow talk, the pretension irony 'punctures'. A is the trap, the unrelated homonym cant meaning a slant or tilt; B and C take the chatter and the in-group-jargon senses of cant, neither of which is the hypocrisy the passage means.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-082", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s13", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Irony begins as honesty's ally. To say one thing and mean its opposite can puncture cant, exposing the gap between a pretension and the truth. But as a settled habit it turns into the very thing it began by attacking. The permanent ironist commits to nothing, for everything he says is held at arm's length, available to be disowned: if challenged, he meant it as a joke; if praised, he half meant it after all. He purchases an immunity the sincere man never has, who can be pinned to his words and shown wrong. And immunity, not insight, becomes the point. What looked like a sharper form of truthfulness has become a way of never being caught holding anything, a refusal of the exposure that any real claim invites.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which figure matches the permanent ironist the passage criticises?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man who states his views bluntly and is, as often as not, shown to be mistaken", "a commentator who never lets himself be held to any view, treating every position as something to be smiled at from a safe distance", "a satirist who turns a sharp irony on a particular hypocrisy and then, the target named and the point landed, drops the mask to say plainly and answerably what he thinks ought to be done instead", "a comedian whose jokes are plainly jokes, understood as such by everyone who hears them"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the criticised ironist keeps everything at arm's length and is 'never caught holding anything', exactly B. C is the trap, irony used as honesty's ally and then set aside for plain commitment, the good use the passage contrasts. A is mere bluntness; D is ordinary, undisguised joking, not the evasive permanent irony.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-014", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is said that on technical questions the layman should defer to the experts, and so, on technical questions, he should. But the counsel hides a difficulty. The question of whether a given matter is one for the experts, and which experts, and whether they have here overstepped their competence into questions of value where their training gives them no special authority, is not itself a technical question that the experts can settle. To let them settle it would be to make them judges in their own cause. So the layman cannot, even in principle, hand the whole business over; he retains an ineliminable judgement, the judgement of when and whom to trust, and this judgement is his to exercise however little he knows of the science. Deference to expertise, fully thought through, requires a competence that no expertise supplies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The case the passage makes is that", format: "single_best", options: ["laymen should defer to experts on technical matters, since on such matters expert judgement is more reliable than their own", "expert judgement is no more reliable than lay opinion, since experts are as prone to error and self-interest as anyone else", "the layman cannot wholly defer, because the prior judgement of when and whom to trust is not itself a technical matter the experts can decide", "experts frequently overstep the bounds of their competence, pronouncing on questions of value where their training gives them no authority"], answer: 2, explanation: "C rests on 'an ineliminable judgement, the judgement of when and whom to trust'. A is the opening counsel, which the passage grants but qualifies; taking it as the thesis ignores the 'but'. B is a debunking the passage refuses, since it accepts deference on technical questions. D is a true supporting observation in the passage, not its central claim, which is the layman's ineliminable judgement.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-083", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is said that on technical questions the layman should defer to the experts, and so, on technical questions, he should. But the counsel hides a difficulty. The question of whether a given matter is one for the experts, and which experts, and whether they have here overstepped their competence into questions of value where their training gives them no special authority, is not itself a technical question that the experts can settle. To let them settle it would be to make them judges in their own cause. So the layman cannot, even in principle, hand the whole business over; he retains an ineliminable judgement, the judgement of when and whom to trust, and this judgement is his to exercise however little he knows of the science. Deference to expertise, fully thought through, requires a competence that no expertise supplies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The worry that letting experts decide whether a matter is for them 'would be to make them judges in their own cause' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["establish that experts are so generally moved by self-interest that nothing they pronounce on any subject whatever should be accepted without the gravest suspicion", "concede that, on the genuinely technical questions, the experts remain the ones to be trusted", "warn that experts frequently stray beyond their competence into questions of value", "show that the prior question of the experts' own jurisdiction cannot be handed to them without circularity, so the layman keeps a judgement he cannot give away"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: to let experts settle whether a matter is theirs is to make them 'judges in their own cause', so that prior judgement stays with the layman, however little he knows of the science. A is the trap, inflating a point about jurisdiction into a blanket distrust of experts. C names a real sub-case (overstepping into value) but not the structural point; B is the concession the passage grants in passing, not what the phrase is doing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-084", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is said that on technical questions the layman should defer to the experts, and so, on technical questions, he should. But the counsel hides a difficulty. The question of whether a given matter is one for the experts, and which experts, and whether they have here overstepped their competence into questions of value where their training gives them no special authority, is not itself a technical question that the experts can settle. To let them settle it would be to make them judges in their own cause. So the layman cannot, even in principle, hand the whole business over; he retains an ineliminable judgement, the judgement of when and whom to trust, and this judgement is his to exercise however little he knows of the science. Deference to expertise, fully thought through, requires a competence that no expertise supplies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["in practice laymen usually do end up trusting the appropriate experts", "experts frequently disagree among themselves on the very questions they are consulted about", "modern science is far too complex for any layman to follow in detail", "an impartial procedure needing no lay judgement can settle which experts to trust"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the claim is that the layman 'cannot, even in principle, hand the whole business over'; if a procedure needing no judgement of his can settle whom to trust, that ineliminable judgement is eliminated after all. A is about what laymen do, not whether they must judge; B and C make deference harder, not less necessary, leaving the structural point intact.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-085", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is said that on technical questions the layman should defer to the experts, and so, on technical questions, he should. But the counsel hides a difficulty. The question of whether a given matter is one for the experts, and which experts, and whether they have here overstepped their competence into questions of value where their training gives them no special authority, is not itself a technical question that the experts can settle. To let them settle it would be to make them judges in their own cause. So the layman cannot, even in principle, hand the whole business over; he retains an ineliminable judgement, the judgement of when and whom to trust, and this judgement is his to exercise however little he knows of the science. Deference to expertise, fully thought through, requires a competence that no expertise supplies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'he retains an ineliminable judgement', 'ineliminable' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["that cannot be explained or accounted for", "that cannot be done away with", "that calls for no special skill to exercise", "that no one is willing to acknowledge"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: an ineliminable judgement is one that cannot be removed or eliminated, which is why the layman cannot hand the whole business over. A reads the prefix as inexplicable; C and D import an ease or an unacknowledgedness the word does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-086", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s14", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is said that on technical questions the layman should defer to the experts, and so, on technical questions, he should. But the counsel hides a difficulty. The question of whether a given matter is one for the experts, and which experts, and whether they have here overstepped their competence into questions of value where their training gives them no special authority, is not itself a technical question that the experts can settle. To let them settle it would be to make them judges in their own cause. So the layman cannot, even in principle, hand the whole business over; he retains an ineliminable judgement, the judgement of when and whom to trust, and this judgement is his to exercise however little he knows of the science. Deference to expertise, fully thought through, requires a competence that no expertise supplies.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which best illustrates the 'ineliminable judgement' the passage says the layman keeps?", format: "single_best", options: ["a patient deciding whether a question his doctor presses on him is really a medical matter or a personal choice about how he wants to live", "a student accepting, on his textbook's authority, a settled and uncontested point of chemistry", "a juror with no scientific training who sets himself to master the forensic evidence in full and to second-guess the expert witnesses on the technical details of their own discipline", "a man who ignores sound expert advice purely out of stubbornness and to his own cost"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: deciding whether a matter is the expert's to settle, or a question of value reserved to oneself, is exactly 'the judgement of when and whom to trust' the passage says cannot be handed over. C is the trap, the layman overreaching into the technical questions the passage grants are the experts'; B is straightforward deference on a technical point; D is not judgement but its refusal.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-015", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Charity is honoured as the warmer virtue, justice as the colder; and so, in the giving, it can feel. But there are cases where to give in charity is to insult in justice. If a man has been underpaid, and his employer, moved, makes him a generous gift, the gift does a subtle violence: it reclassifies as benevolence what was owed as a debt, and asks for gratitude where an apology was due. The recipient is made to receive as a favour what he should have been able to claim as a right, and to thank the very person who wronged him. Charity of this kind is not the supplement to justice but its concealment, and the glow that surrounds the giver is borrowed from the wrong he is quietly declining to put right.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim is that charity", format: "single_best", options: ["is never genuinely virtuous, since the impulse to give always springs from a wish to feel superior to the one who receives", "is a warmer and more admirable virtue than justice, because it gives more than is strictly owed", "should always be preceded by justice, so that one first pays what is owed and only then gives freely beyond it", "can serve to conceal an injustice, when what is offered as a gift was in fact owed as a debt, benevolence standing in for the apology due"], answer: 3, explanation: "D rests on 'it reclassifies as benevolence what was owed as a debt'. A is a cynical over-claim about all charity, where the passage targets a specific case. B is the honoured view the passage complicates. C is a sensible adjacent maxim about ordering the two, but milder than the passage's point that such charity actively disguises a wrong.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-087", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Charity is honoured as the warmer virtue, justice as the colder; and so, in the giving, it can feel. But there are cases where to give in charity is to insult in justice. If a man has been underpaid, and his employer, moved, makes him a generous gift, the gift does a subtle violence: it reclassifies as benevolence what was owed as a debt, and asks for gratitude where an apology was due. The recipient is made to receive as a favour what he should have been able to claim as a right, and to thank the very person who wronged him. Charity of this kind is not the supplement to justice but its concealment, and the glow that surrounds the giver is borrowed from the wrong he is quietly declining to put right.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The example of the underpaid man given 'a generous gift' by his employer serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["argue that employers ought to pay fair wages before they think of giving gifts at all", "show that charity can recast a debt as benevolence, exacting gratitude where an apology was the thing owed", "suggest that the recipient was ungrateful, failing to value a gift freely given", "prove that no act of giving is ever genuinely generous, every gift being, at bottom, a device by which the giver places the receiver under an obligation he did not seek"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the gift 'reclassifies as benevolence what was owed as a debt, and asks for gratitude where an apology was due', exactly the concealment the example shows. D is the trap, generalising into the claim that all giving is manipulation, far beyond the passage's point about a debt disguised. A draws a policy moral; C blames the recipient, reversing the passage's sympathy.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-088", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Charity is honoured as the warmer virtue, justice as the colder; and so, in the giving, it can feel. But there are cases where to give in charity is to insult in justice. If a man has been underpaid, and his employer, moved, makes him a generous gift, the gift does a subtle violence: it reclassifies as benevolence what was owed as a debt, and asks for gratitude where an apology was due. The recipient is made to receive as a favour what he should have been able to claim as a right, and to thank the very person who wronged him. Charity of this kind is not the supplement to justice but its concealment, and the glow that surrounds the giver is borrowed from the wrong he is quietly declining to put right.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's account of charity?", format: "single_best", options: ["the employer pays the wages owed and then makes the gift, so nothing owed is passed as a favour", "many gifts are given in situations where the giver owes the recipient nothing at all", "the underpaid man was, in the event, genuinely glad to receive the gift", "gratitude for a kindness is in general a virtue worth cultivating"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the charge holds only where the gift stands in for the debt; if the debt is paid in full and the gift comes on top, charity is no longer concealing an injustice and the example dissolves. B concerns gifts where nothing is owed, which the passage does not deny are genuine; C is about the recipient's feeling; D is a general remark about gratitude.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-089", genre: "dialectic", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Charity is honoured as the warmer virtue, justice as the colder; and so, in the giving, it can feel. But there are cases where to give in charity is to insult in justice. If a man has been underpaid, and his employer, moved, makes him a generous gift, the gift does a subtle violence: it reclassifies as benevolence what was owed as a debt, and asks for gratitude where an apology was due. The recipient is made to receive as a favour what he should have been able to claim as a right, and to thank the very person who wronged him. Charity of this kind is not the supplement to justice but its concealment, and the glow that surrounds the giver is borrowed from the wrong he is quietly declining to put right.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image of a 'borrowed' glow surrounding the giver implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the giver has taken the credit that properly belonged to some other, more generous person", "the giver shines with a warmth that is genuinely his own and fully deserved, dimmed only a little by his having failed to prevent the original wrong from ever occurring in the first place", "the giver's look of virtue is not his own but is drawn, illegitimately, from the very injustice he is declining to put right", "the giver's reputation for kindness will fade as soon as the particular gift is forgotten"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: a borrowed glow is not the giver's to keep; his air of generosity is taken from the wrong he leaves unrighted, which is why charity here 'conceals' an injustice. B is the trap, treating the glow as genuinely earned, the opposite of 'borrowed'. A makes it credit stolen from another giver; D turns it into a point about the gift being forgotten.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-090", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s15", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Charity is honoured as the warmer virtue, justice as the colder; and so, in the giving, it can feel. But there are cases where to give in charity is to insult in justice. If a man has been underpaid, and his employer, moved, makes him a generous gift, the gift does a subtle violence: it reclassifies as benevolence what was owed as a debt, and asks for gratitude where an apology was due. The recipient is made to receive as a favour what he should have been able to claim as a right, and to thank the very person who wronged him. Charity of this kind is not the supplement to justice but its concealment, and the glow that surrounds the giver is borrowed from the wrong he is quietly declining to put right.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case matches the concealed injustice the passage warns of?", format: "single_best", options: ["a firm that, having underpaid its cleaners for years, sets up a fund for low-paid workers and is widely praised for its philanthropy", "a man who repays a loan promptly and in full on the day it falls due", "a wealthy man under no obligation to anyone who endows a hospital out of nothing but a wish to do some good, and is warmly thanked by the many whom his gift will go on to help", "a charity that gives aid to distant strangers it has never had any dealings with or done any wrong"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the firm offers as charity to the underpaid what it owed them as wages, 'benevolence substituted for the apology due', the concealment the passage names. C is the trap, real generosity where nothing was owed, which the passage does not impugn. B is the plain discharge of a debt; D is charity to those one has not wronged, again outside the charge.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-016", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Readers complain of difficulty in a poem as of a fault, as though the poet, had he tried, could have said the same thing plainly and spared them the labour. Sometimes that is just: obscurity can be mere fog, a failure to think clearly dressed up as depth. But not always. There are understandings that cannot be handed over ready-made, that exist only in the act of being worked for, so that to paraphrase them into plainness is not to clarify them but to destroy them, leaving a husk that is clear precisely because it is no longer the thing. Here the difficulty is not a barrier between the reader and the meaning but the very medium in which the meaning lives. The labour the poem demands is not a toll exacted before entry; it is the entry.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim is that the difficulty of some art", format: "single_best", options: ["is not an obstacle between reader and meaning but the medium in which the meaning lives, so removing it destroys the meaning", "is a fault the artist could and should remove, since anything worth saying can be said plainly to a patient enough reader", "shows that the harder a work is to understand, the more profound its meaning is likely to be", "rewards the effort of the reader, who values a meaning the more for having had to work to reach it"], answer: 0, explanation: "A rests on 'the very medium in which the meaning lives' and 'it is the entry'. B is the complaint the passage answers. C is the inverse fallacy the passage guards against ('obscurity can be mere fog'). D is a psychological near-miss about effort enhancing appreciation, where the passage's claim is that the meaning simply is the difficulty.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-091", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Readers complain of difficulty in a poem as of a fault, as though the poet, had he tried, could have said the same thing plainly and spared them the labour. Sometimes that is just: obscurity can be mere fog, a failure to think clearly dressed up as depth. But not always. There are understandings that cannot be handed over ready-made, that exist only in the act of being worked for, so that to paraphrase them into plainness is not to clarify them but to destroy them, leaving a husk that is clear precisely because it is no longer the thing. Here the difficulty is not a barrier between the reader and the meaning but the very medium in which the meaning lives. The labour the poem demands is not a toll exacted before entry; it is the entry.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The distinction between obscurity that is 'mere fog' and difficulty that is 'the very medium in which the meaning lives' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["argue that obscurity in art is, more often than not, a failure of clear thinking dressed up as depth", "establish that difficulty in a work is always the surest sign of its depth, so that the harder a thing is to grasp, the more certainly it will repay the labour of grasping it", "grant that some difficulty is a real fault while insisting that other difficulty is inseparable from the meaning, so that the two must not be run together", "suggest that readers ought to be a good deal more patient with hard works than they commonly are"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage allows that 'obscurity can be mere fog' yet holds that elsewhere difficulty is 'the very medium in which the meaning lives', a distinction it draws precisely so the two are not confused. B is the trap, the harder-means-deeper view the passage refuses ('Sometimes that is just'). A keeps only the fault half; D draws a moral about patience the passage does not press.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-092", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Readers complain of difficulty in a poem as of a fault, as though the poet, had he tried, could have said the same thing plainly and spared them the labour. Sometimes that is just: obscurity can be mere fog, a failure to think clearly dressed up as depth. But not always. There are understandings that cannot be handed over ready-made, that exist only in the act of being worked for, so that to paraphrase them into plainness is not to clarify them but to destroy them, leaving a husk that is clear precisely because it is no longer the thing. Here the difficulty is not a barrier between the reader and the meaning but the very medium in which the meaning lives. The labour the poem demands is not a toll exacted before entry; it is the entry.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's central claim?", format: "single_best", options: ["some celebrated difficult poems are in fact admired by only a handful of readers", "whatever a hard poem means can be put plainly without loss, so the difficulty is never the meaning's medium", "obscure works are frequently praised for reasons that have nothing to do with their actual merit", "many readers positively enjoy the effort that a difficult work demands of them"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the claim is that some meanings 'exist only in the act of being worked for', so paraphrase 'destroys' rather than clarifies them; if every such meaning can after all be put plainly without loss, that claim fails. A and C are points about reputation and reception; D is about readers' enjoyment, not whether the meaning survives paraphrase.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-093", genre: "dialectic", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Readers complain of difficulty in a poem as of a fault, as though the poet, had he tried, could have said the same thing plainly and spared them the labour. Sometimes that is just: obscurity can be mere fog, a failure to think clearly dressed up as depth. But not always. There are understandings that cannot be handed over ready-made, that exist only in the act of being worked for, so that to paraphrase them into plainness is not to clarify them but to destroy them, leaving a husk that is clear precisely because it is no longer the thing. Here the difficulty is not a barrier between the reader and the meaning but the very medium in which the meaning lives. The labour the poem demands is not a toll exacted before entry; it is the entry.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Paraphrase leaves 'a husk that is clear precisely because it is no longer the thing'; the husk image implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["the plain restatement is an empty shell, clear only because the living meaning has gone out of it", "the original poem was, after all, mostly empty show beneath its difficult surface", "the plain restatement keeps the essential kernel of the meaning while stripping away only the inessential difficulty that had surrounded it, much as one removes a husk to reach the nourishing seed inside", "clarity and meaning are, in art, simply incompatible with one another"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the husk is what is left when the life has gone, 'clear precisely because it is no longer the thing', so paraphrase yields a dead shell. C is the trap, reversing the image into husk-as-inessential-wrapping around a recoverable kernel, exactly what the passage denies. B impugns the original; D overstates into a blanket opposition of clarity and meaning.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-094", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s16", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Readers complain of difficulty in a poem as of a fault, as though the poet, had he tried, could have said the same thing plainly and spared them the labour. Sometimes that is just: obscurity can be mere fog, a failure to think clearly dressed up as depth. But not always. There are understandings that cannot be handed over ready-made, that exist only in the act of being worked for, so that to paraphrase them into plainness is not to clarify them but to destroy them, leaving a husk that is clear precisely because it is no longer the thing. Here the difficulty is not a barrier between the reader and the meaning but the very medium in which the meaning lives. The labour the poem demands is not a toll exacted before entry; it is the entry.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best fits the difficulty the passage defends, as opposed to mere fog?", format: "single_best", options: ["a lecture made hard to follow because the speaker mumbles and loses his thread", "a tax form written in such tangled officialese that its one plain instruction can be, and routinely is, set out again in a single clear sentence that any reader takes in at once", "a poem widely admired only because it has become fashionable to admire it", "a poem whose sense a reader can reach only by working through its images, and which goes flat the instant it is summarised"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: here the labour is 'the entry', the meaning living only in the working-for and lost in summary, the difficulty the passage defends. B is the trap, difficulty that is mere fog around a plain message a paraphrase fully captures. A is obscurity from poor delivery; C is a point about fashion, not difficulty at all.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-017", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The whistleblower is accused of disloyalty, and the charge assumes that loyalty means standing by one's own whatever they do. But a loyalty that no conduct could forfeit is not loyalty at all; it is servility, the attachment of a dog, which does not depend on what the master is. To be loyal to a person or an institution is to be loyal to something one takes to be worth it, and that estimate carries a standard within it: the very grounds on which I am loyal are grounds on which I can be betrayed. The man who exposes his colleagues' wrongdoing may thus be keeping faith with the institution against its present officers, loyal to what it was supposed to be. Unconditional loyalty, far from being the purest kind, is the kind that has stopped paying attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's principal claim is that", format: "single_best", options: ["loyalty requires standing by one's own people and institutions regardless of what they have done", "genuine loyalty holds a standard by which its object can be judged, so exposing wrongdoing can itself be an act of loyalty", "loyalty is never a genuine virtue, since one should be guided by justice alone and judge each act simply on its merits", "one's loyalty to justice must always outweigh one's loyalty to particular people when the two come into conflict"], answer: 1, explanation: "B rests on 'the very grounds on which I am loyal are grounds on which I can be betrayed'. A is the view behind the accusation, which the passage rejects. C eliminates loyalty entirely, where the passage defends a genuine kind. D ranks two loyalties against each other, but the passage's claim is internal: loyalty itself contains the standard, not that one loyalty trumps another.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-095", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The whistleblower is accused of disloyalty, and the charge assumes that loyalty means standing by one's own whatever they do. But a loyalty that no conduct could forfeit is not loyalty at all; it is servility, the attachment of a dog, which does not depend on what the master is. To be loyal to a person or an institution is to be loyal to something one takes to be worth it, and that estimate carries a standard within it: the very grounds on which I am loyal are grounds on which I can be betrayed. The man who exposes his colleagues' wrongdoing may thus be keeping faith with the institution against its present officers, loyal to what it was supposed to be. Unconditional loyalty, far from being the purest kind, is the kind that has stopped paying attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Calling unconditional loyalty 'the attachment of a dog, which does not depend on what the master is' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["deny that a loyalty no conduct could forfeit is loyalty at all, marking it as servility because it carries no standard within it", "warn that those who are loyal are often treated no better than animals for their pains", "hold up the steadfast devotion of a dog, which never wavers however badly its master may come to behave, as the very model on which human loyalty ought to form itself", "suggest that loyalty is at bottom a lower instinct that human beings share with the beasts"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the dog's attachment 'does not depend on what the master is', so loyalty that no conduct could forfeit is 'servility', not loyalty, because it holds no standard. C is the trap, taking the dog as a model to admire, the reverse of the passage's point. B and D moralise about how the loyal are treated or about loyalty's animal roots, neither the contrast being drawn.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-096", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The whistleblower is accused of disloyalty, and the charge assumes that loyalty means standing by one's own whatever they do. But a loyalty that no conduct could forfeit is not loyalty at all; it is servility, the attachment of a dog, which does not depend on what the master is. To be loyal to a person or an institution is to be loyal to something one takes to be worth it, and that estimate carries a standard within it: the very grounds on which I am loyal are grounds on which I can be betrayed. The man who exposes his colleagues' wrongdoing may thus be keeping faith with the institution against its present officers, loyal to what it was supposed to be. Unconditional loyalty, far from being the purest kind, is the kind that has stopped paying attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["whistleblowers are, as often as not, moved by personal grievance rather than principle", "institutions in fact rarely live up to the ideals they profess", "loyalty is owed to the thing itself, not to a standard, so withdrawing it is mere approval", "loyalty and justice, in most ordinary cases, happen to point in the same direction"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage makes loyalty contain a standard by which its object can be judged; if loyalty is instead owed to the particular as such, then withdrawing it on judgement is not a deeper loyalty but its abandonment, and the whistleblower's claim to loyalty fails. A questions motives without touching the argument; B and D are observations that leave the structure untouched.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-097", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The whistleblower is accused of disloyalty, and the charge assumes that loyalty means standing by one's own whatever they do. But a loyalty that no conduct could forfeit is not loyalty at all; it is servility, the attachment of a dog, which does not depend on what the master is. To be loyal to a person or an institution is to be loyal to something one takes to be worth it, and that estimate carries a standard within it: the very grounds on which I am loyal are grounds on which I can be betrayed. The man who exposes his colleagues' wrongdoing may thus be keeping faith with the institution against its present officers, loyal to what it was supposed to be. Unconditional loyalty, far from being the purest kind, is the kind that has stopped paying attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'it is servility, the attachment of a dog', 'servility' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["a useful readiness to be of service to others", "loyalty that holds firm under pressure", "an excessive and self-abasing modesty", "slavish, cringing submissiveness"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: servility is the abject, slavish submission of one who attaches himself regardless of merit, like the dog to any master. A is the trap, the serviceableness sense (readiness to serve), which carries no abjectness; B confuses servility with steadfast loyalty, the very thing the passage distinguishes it from; C narrows it to mere modesty.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-098", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s17", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The whistleblower is accused of disloyalty, and the charge assumes that loyalty means standing by one's own whatever they do. But a loyalty that no conduct could forfeit is not loyalty at all; it is servility, the attachment of a dog, which does not depend on what the master is. To be loyal to a person or an institution is to be loyal to something one takes to be worth it, and that estimate carries a standard within it: the very grounds on which I am loyal are grounds on which I can be betrayed. The man who exposes his colleagues' wrongdoing may thus be keeping faith with the institution against its present officers, loyal to what it was supposed to be. Unconditional loyalty, far from being the purest kind, is the kind that has stopped paying attention.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Whom would the passage count as loyal in the genuine sense?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man who abandons a friend the instant the friend's reputation begins to suffer", "an officer who reports the abuses of his own unit because they betray what the service is supposed to stand for", "a courtier who defends his prince's every act, however unjust, on the settled principle that a true servant questions nothing and deserts no one, whatever his master may come to do", "a citizen who transfers his allegiance to whichever faction happens to hold power at the time"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: exposing the abuses keeps faith 'with the institution against its present officers, loyal to what it was supposed to be', the genuine loyalty the passage describes. C is the trap, the unconditional servility the passage calls a loyalty that 'has stopped paying attention'. A is disloyalty at the first cost; D is mere accommodation to power.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-018", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drive home equally drunk. One reaches his door; the other, through no difference in himself, meets a child crossing in the dark and kills her. We punish the second far more gravely, and we feel the difference to be just. Yet what they chose was the same; the child was a matter of luck, present on one road and not the other. If desert tracks the will, the two deserve alike, and our practice wrongs the unlucky one. If our practice is right, then desert is partly a matter of luck, of what the world happens to do with a choice once it leaves our hands, and the comforting idea that a man is answerable only for what was up to him cannot survive. We cannot keep both, and we are reluctant to give up either.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is primarily concerned to show that", format: "single_best", options: ["the drunk driver who kills deserves graver punishment, since the gravity of an offence depends on the harm it actually causes", "punishment is never just, since the outcomes for which we hold people answerable always depend on factors beyond their control", "our practice of judging by outcomes cannot be squared with the principle that one answers only for what one controlled, and we abandon neither", "a person can be answerable only for what was up to him, so the two drivers, having chosen alike, deserve exactly the same"], answer: 2, explanation: "C rests on 'We cannot keep both, and we are reluctant to give up either'. A and D each assert one horn of the dilemma as if it were the conclusion, and both are textually supported, which is the trap; the passage endorses neither, holding them in tension. B is a sweeping scepticism the passage declines, since it says we will not give up the practice.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-099", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drive home equally drunk. One reaches his door; the other, through no difference in himself, meets a child crossing in the dark and kills her. We punish the second far more gravely, and we feel the difference to be just. Yet what they chose was the same; the child was a matter of luck, present on one road and not the other. If desert tracks the will, the two deserve alike, and our practice wrongs the unlucky one. If our practice is right, then desert is partly a matter of luck, of what the world happens to do with a choice once it leaves our hands, and the comforting idea that a man is answerable only for what was up to him cannot survive. We cannot keep both, and we are reluctant to give up either.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The detail that the two drivers' difference was 'no difference in himself' and 'a matter of luck' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["sharpen the dilemma by holding the two men's choices identical, so that the heavier punishment of the one can rest on nothing but luck", "suggest that drunk driving ought to be punished according to the risk run rather than the harm that happens to follow", "prove that the second driver cannot really be to blame for the death at all, since the child's presence was entirely beyond his control and formed no part of anything that he actually chose to do", "show, by the by, that an element of luck enters into every human action whatever"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: stressing that nothing differed 'in himself' isolates luck as the only thing separating the two, which is what makes our unequal treatment of them a puzzle. C is the trap, settling the dilemma on the will side ('no blame for the death'), where the passage insists we will abandon neither horn. B advances one policy answer; D states a general truth without the dilemma's bite.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-100", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drive home equally drunk. One reaches his door; the other, through no difference in himself, meets a child crossing in the dark and kills her. We punish the second far more gravely, and we feel the difference to be just. Yet what they chose was the same; the child was a matter of luck, present on one road and not the other. If desert tracks the will, the two deserve alike, and our practice wrongs the unlucky one. If our practice is right, then desert is partly a matter of luck, of what the world happens to do with a choice once it leaves our hands, and the comforting idea that a man is answerable only for what was up to him cannot survive. We cannot keep both, and we are reluctant to give up either.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the dilemma the passage presses?", format: "single_best", options: ["people's intuitions about how the two drivers should be treated in fact vary a good deal", "the driver who kills usually feels far guiltier himself than the one who gets home safely", "juries are well known to be swayed by the sight of a visible, concrete harm", "the different punishments may rest on deterrence alone, claiming no greater desert, so no clash arises"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the dilemma assumes the heavier punishment expresses greater desert, which then conflicts with the control principle; if the practice rests instead on deterrence or administrability and makes no claim about desert, both horns can be kept and there is nothing to reconcile. A and B are about intuitions and feelings; C is about what sways juries, not whether desert tracks luck.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-101", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drive home equally drunk. One reaches his door; the other, through no difference in himself, meets a child crossing in the dark and kills her. We punish the second far more gravely, and we feel the difference to be just. Yet what they chose was the same; the child was a matter of luck, present on one road and not the other. If desert tracks the will, the two deserve alike, and our practice wrongs the unlucky one. If our practice is right, then desert is partly a matter of luck, of what the world happens to do with a choice once it leaves our hands, and the comforting idea that a man is answerable only for what was up to him cannot survive. We cannot keep both, and we are reluctant to give up either.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'If desert tracks the will', 'tracks' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["keeps a written record of", "hunts down and pursues", "corresponds to and follows", "trails along behind"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: to say desert tracks the will is to say it follows and matches the will, varying with what was chosen. B is the trap, the trail-and-hunt sense of track; A takes the record-keeping sense; D the lagging-behind sense, neither of which is the correspondence the conditional asserts.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-102", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s18", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Two men drive home equally drunk. One reaches his door; the other, through no difference in himself, meets a child crossing in the dark and kills her. We punish the second far more gravely, and we feel the difference to be just. Yet what they chose was the same; the child was a matter of luck, present on one road and not the other. If desert tracks the will, the two deserve alike, and our practice wrongs the unlucky one. If our practice is right, then desert is partly a matter of luck, of what the world happens to do with a choice once it leaves our hands, and the comforting idea that a man is answerable only for what was up to him cannot survive. We cannot keep both, and we are reluctant to give up either.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage presents us as holding two commitments it says we will not surrender. They are best stated as", format: "single_best", options: ["that luck should never affect desert, and that the outcome of an act is all that finally matters", "that we rightly punish by the outcome, and that a person is answerable only for what was within his control", "that punishment should chiefly deter, and that mercy should always be allowed to temper it", "that the drunk driver who kills deserves the graver penalty, and that drunk driving is in every instance so reckless that whatever harm it happens to cause should be visited in full upon whoever caused it"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the passage sets 'judging by outcomes' against the principle that one is 'answerable only for what was up to him' and says 'we are reluctant to give up either', exactly the two commitments. D is the trap, an elaborate one-sided gloss that quietly takes the outcome horn and abandons the control one. A pairs two views that do not clash; C names deterrence and mercy, which the passage does not raise here.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-019", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s19", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The blunt man flatters himself that he alone tells the truth, and that politeness is a kind of lying. But consider what his bluntness actually conveys. When he announces an unflattering opinion no one asked for, he communicates, accurately, that he does not much care how his words land, and this too is a truth, a truth about how he regards his hearer. Politeness is not the suppression of truth but the management of which truths to utter and when; and the reticence it counsels is often itself truthful, an honest signal that the relationship matters more than the scoring of a point. The cult of total candour, examined, frequently turns out to be aggression wearing honesty's coat: it is not that the blunt man cannot lie, but that he has found a form of unkindness he can call a virtue.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim is that", format: "single_best", options: ["honesty requires us to speak our true opinions plainly, and politeness, by concealing them, is a refined form of dishonesty", "one should never voice an unwelcome truth, since doing so always signals contempt for the hearer", "politeness is valuable because it spares people's feelings, and kindness should usually be preferred to a hurtful truth", "politeness is not opposed to honesty but chooses which truths to tell, while the demand for total candour often disguises aggression"], answer: 3, explanation: "D rests on 'the management of which truths to utter and when' and 'aggression wearing honesty's coat'. A is the blunt man's view, rejected. B is an absolutist 'never' the passage avoids: it manages which truths and when, not a blanket ban. C is the kindness-over-truth maxim, milder and different from the passage's claim that politeness is itself a form of truthfulness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-103", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s19", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The blunt man flatters himself that he alone tells the truth, and that politeness is a kind of lying. But consider what his bluntness actually conveys. When he announces an unflattering opinion no one asked for, he communicates, accurately, that he does not much care how his words land, and this too is a truth, a truth about how he regards his hearer. Politeness is not the suppression of truth but the management of which truths to utter and when; and the reticence it counsels is often itself truthful, an honest signal that the relationship matters more than the scoring of a point. The cult of total candour, examined, frequently turns out to be aggression wearing honesty's coat: it is not that the blunt man cannot lie, but that he has found a form of unkindness he can call a virtue.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The point that the blunt man 'communicates, accurately, that he does not much care how his words land' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["argue that one ought always to weigh carefully how one's words are going to land before speaking", "turn the bluntness back on itself, since it too conveys a truth, namely the blunt man's disregard for his hearer, so candour is not all on his side", "concede that the blunt man does, at the very least, have the merit of saying what he actually thinks", "prove that the blunt man is in truth the most dishonest of all, since beneath his show of frankness he is busy concealing a deep contempt for his hearer that he never quite dares to state outright"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: his bluntness 'communicates, accurately, that he does not much care how his words land', itself a truth about how he regards the hearer, so honesty is not his monopoly. D is the trap, recasting him as secretly the most dishonest, a charge the passage does not make, since it calls his message accurate. A draws a prudential rule; C grants him a merit the passage is busy qualifying.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-104", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s19", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The blunt man flatters himself that he alone tells the truth, and that politeness is a kind of lying. But consider what his bluntness actually conveys. When he announces an unflattering opinion no one asked for, he communicates, accurately, that he does not much care how his words land, and this too is a truth, a truth about how he regards his hearer. Politeness is not the suppression of truth but the management of which truths to utter and when; and the reticence it counsels is often itself truthful, an honest signal that the relationship matters more than the scoring of a point. The cult of total candour, examined, frequently turns out to be aggression wearing honesty's coat: it is not that the blunt man cannot lie, but that he has found a form of unkindness he can call a virtue.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["people who are habitually blunt are, as a rule, not much liked", "some unwelcome truths genuinely do need to be said, however badly they land", "politeness often requires suppressing a truth, so it can be opposed to honesty", "what counts as polite varies a good deal from one culture to another"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the claim is that politeness is 'not the suppression of truth but the management of which truths to utter'; if politeness regularly demands suppressing truths outright, then it does stand opposed to honesty, against the passage. A is about the blunt man's reception; B grants that some truths need saying, which the passage allows; D is about cultural variation, not the truth-management claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-105", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s19", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The blunt man flatters himself that he alone tells the truth, and that politeness is a kind of lying. But consider what his bluntness actually conveys. When he announces an unflattering opinion no one asked for, he communicates, accurately, that he does not much care how his words land, and this too is a truth, a truth about how he regards his hearer. Politeness is not the suppression of truth but the management of which truths to utter and when; and the reticence it counsels is often itself truthful, an honest signal that the relationship matters more than the scoring of a point. The cult of total candour, examined, frequently turns out to be aggression wearing honesty's coat: it is not that the blunt man cannot lie, but that he has found a form of unkindness he can call a virtue.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'the reticence it counsels is often itself truthful', 'reticence' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["a deliberate withholding meant to deceive", "a reluctance that springs from fear", "a holding back from speech", "a quiet, unspoken resentment"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: reticence is reserve, a holding back of what one might say, which the passage calls 'often itself truthful'. B colours it with fear; A makes it a deception, the opposite of the truthful signal the passage describes; D reads it as resentment, an attitude the word does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-106", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s19", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The blunt man flatters himself that he alone tells the truth, and that politeness is a kind of lying. But consider what his bluntness actually conveys. When he announces an unflattering opinion no one asked for, he communicates, accurately, that he does not much care how his words land, and this too is a truth, a truth about how he regards his hearer. Politeness is not the suppression of truth but the management of which truths to utter and when; and the reticence it counsels is often itself truthful, an honest signal that the relationship matters more than the scoring of a point. The cult of total candour, examined, frequently turns out to be aggression wearing honesty's coat: it is not that the blunt man cannot lie, but that he has found a form of unkindness he can call a virtue.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best fits the passage's view of politeness as choosing which truths to tell?", format: "single_best", options: ["a guest who, asked what he thought of a clumsy meal his host had cooked with care, praises the effort and says nothing of the taste", "a man who flatly lies, calling a poor meal excellent when he found it inedible", "a restaurant critic who, writing up a meal for a newspaper, quietly suppresses every fault he found in the cooking so as to spare the feelings of a chef he has never met and is never likely to meet", "a man who, unasked, recites to his host every single fault he could find in the meal"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the guest manages which truths to utter, the truthful reticence the passage praises, where the relationship 'matters more than the scoring of a point'. C is the trap, suppressing truths owed to readers in a public review, where candour is the duty, not a kindness. B is the outright lie politeness is not; D is the unkind bluntness the passage criticises.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-020", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s20", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We picture self-knowledge as a looking inward, the mind turning a lamp on its own contents and reporting what is there. But the inner life is not a room that stays the same when the light goes on. To watch one's anger is already to cool it; to attend to a spontaneous joy is to make it self-conscious and so, a little, to spoil it; the observation does not find a state but disturbs one. What is more, the feelings do not come labelled, and to say what a given disquiet is, jealousy, or wounded pride, or fear, is not to read off a fact but to venture an interpretation that may itself reshape the feeling. Self-knowledge, then, is less like inspecting an object than like reading a difficult text, one that the reading helps to write.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim about self-knowledge is that it", format: "single_best", options: ["cannot be neutral observation, since attending to a feeling alters it and naming it interprets it", "is a matter of looking honestly inward and faithfully reporting the feelings one finds there", "is impossible, since we can never really know our own minds at all", "is difficult because our feelings are often mixed and hard to tell apart from one another"], answer: 0, explanation: "A rests on 'the observation does not find a state but disturbs one' and 'the reading helps to write'. B is the lamp-in-a-room picture the passage unsettles. C over-reaches into impossibility, where the passage offers a revised model (interpretation), not a denial of self-knowledge. D names a real difficulty about mixed feelings, but a different one from the passage's point that observing disturbs and naming reshapes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-107", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s20", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We picture self-knowledge as a looking inward, the mind turning a lamp on its own contents and reporting what is there. But the inner life is not a room that stays the same when the light goes on. To watch one's anger is already to cool it; to attend to a spontaneous joy is to make it self-conscious and so, a little, to spoil it; the observation does not find a state but disturbs one. What is more, the feelings do not come labelled, and to say what a given disquiet is, jealousy, or wounded pride, or fear, is not to read off a fact but to venture an interpretation that may itself reshape the feeling. Self-knowledge, then, is less like inspecting an object than like reading a difficult text, one that the reading helps to write.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that 'to watch one's anger is already to cool it' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["recommend the watching of one's anger as a useful technique for calming oneself down", "suggest that anger in particular is an unusually fleeting and short-lived emotion", "show that observing a feeling alters it, so that introspection disturbs the state rather than neutrally recording what is there", "prove that we can never come to know our own feelings at all, since the very act of turning to look at them destroys them entirely before they can ever be seen"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: watching the anger cools it, so 'the observation does not find a state but disturbs one', the passage's point against neutral introspection. D is the trap, pushing disturbance into the stronger claim that self-knowledge is impossible, where the passage says it is interpretive, not that it cannot occur. A takes the line as practical advice; B as a remark about anger's brevity.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-108", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s20", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We picture self-knowledge as a looking inward, the mind turning a lamp on its own contents and reporting what is there. But the inner life is not a room that stays the same when the light goes on. To watch one's anger is already to cool it; to attend to a spontaneous joy is to make it self-conscious and so, a little, to spoil it; the observation does not find a state but disturbs one. What is more, the feelings do not come labelled, and to say what a given disquiet is, jealousy, or wounded pride, or fear, is not to read off a fact but to venture an interpretation that may itself reshape the feeling. Self-knowledge, then, is less like inspecting an object than like reading a difficult text, one that the reading helps to write.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's claim about self-knowledge?", format: "single_best", options: ["people quite often give the wrong name to what they are feeling", "our feelings are strongly coloured by our passing moods", "introspection is a skill that takes long practice to do well", "a settled grief can be watched at length without altering under the gaze"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the case is that attending to a feeling disturbs it; if important inner states can be watched steadily without changing, then introspection can after all be the neutral observation the passage denies. A and B concern misnaming and the influence of mood, not whether observation alters the state; C makes introspection merely hard, not self-disturbing.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-109", genre: "dialectic", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s20", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We picture self-knowledge as a looking inward, the mind turning a lamp on its own contents and reporting what is there. But the inner life is not a room that stays the same when the light goes on. To watch one's anger is already to cool it; to attend to a spontaneous joy is to make it self-conscious and so, a little, to spoil it; the observation does not find a state but disturbs one. What is more, the feelings do not come labelled, and to say what a given disquiet is, jealousy, or wounded pride, or fear, is not to read off a fact but to venture an interpretation that may itself reshape the feeling. Self-knowledge, then, is less like inspecting an object than like reading a difficult text, one that the reading helps to write.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The image that the inner life 'is not a room that stays the same when the light goes on' implies that", format: "single_best", options: ["turning one's attention on a feeling changes what is there, so introspection cannot find its object lying undisturbed", "our feelings stay hidden from us until we deliberately decide to examine them", "the mind is a dark and cluttered room whose contents simply need lighting before they can be inspected, the whole difficulty of self-knowledge being that we so rarely trouble to turn the light on at all", "the mind holds far more than anyone could ever take in or survey at a single glance"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: a room that changes when the light goes on is one the looking disturbs, so attending to a feeling alters it. C is the trap, taking the lamp image at face value as a mere matter of illuminating a fixed room, which is the neutral-observation picture the passage rejects. B makes feelings merely hidden; D makes the mind merely vast.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-110", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s20", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We picture self-knowledge as a looking inward, the mind turning a lamp on its own contents and reporting what is there. But the inner life is not a room that stays the same when the light goes on. To watch one's anger is already to cool it; to attend to a spontaneous joy is to make it self-conscious and so, a little, to spoil it; the observation does not find a state but disturbs one. What is more, the feelings do not come labelled, and to say what a given disquiet is, jealousy, or wounded pride, or fear, is not to read off a fact but to venture an interpretation that may itself reshape the feeling. Self-knowledge, then, is less like inspecting an object than like reading a difficult text, one that the reading helps to write.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which best illustrates the difficulty of self-knowledge the passage describes?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man who can no longer remember how he felt about some event many years ago", "a man who, trying to decide whether what he feels toward a rival is envy or honest disapproval, finds the feeling shift as he frames it first one way and then the other", "a man who keeps a meticulous daily journal of his moods, setting each one down the moment he notices it, in the confidence that an exact written record will in time yield him a complete and accurate map of his whole inner life", "a man whose friends seem to understand his moods rather better than he does himself"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: to name the feeling envy or disapproval 'is not to read off a fact but to venture an interpretation that may itself reshape the feeling', exactly the man's predicament. C is the trap, assuming feelings can be recorded undisturbed like fixed data, the neutral-observation model the passage denies. A is mere forgetting; D is about others' insight, not the act of self-observation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-021", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s21", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged never to forget, and against certain wrongs the injunction is right. But a society that forgets nothing cannot end a quarrel. Every peace after a civil war has rested on a measure of deliberate forgetting, an agreement not to keep the full account, because a community in which each remembers exactly what each did can only go on settling scores. The ancient amnesties understood this: to declare that certain wrongs would not be recalled was not to deny that they happened but to refuse them a future, to stop the past from continuing to act. The duty to remember, pressed without limit, becomes the enemy of any common life among former enemies; there are things a people must consent not to know about itself in order to remain one people.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "What the author centrally claims is that", format: "single_best", options: ["the past should never be forgotten, since to forget a wrong is to deny it and to wrong its victims a second time", "a deliberate public forgetting can be the condition of peace, since a community that keeps every score cannot stop avenging it", "the past is best forgotten, since dwelling on old wrongs only perpetuates the very hatreds that first caused them", "victims should be willing to forgive their former enemies for the sake of restoring a common life among them"], answer: 1, explanation: "B rests on 'an agreement not to keep the full account' and 'to refuse them a future'. A is the unlimited injunction the passage qualifies. C is a blanket 'forget the past' that is cruder and stronger than the passage, which grants some wrongs must not be forgotten. D shifts from collective political forgetting (amnesty) to the personal moral act of forgiving.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-111", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s21", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged never to forget, and against certain wrongs the injunction is right. But a society that forgets nothing cannot end a quarrel. Every peace after a civil war has rested on a measure of deliberate forgetting, an agreement not to keep the full account, because a community in which each remembers exactly what each did can only go on settling scores. The ancient amnesties understood this: to declare that certain wrongs would not be recalled was not to deny that they happened but to refuse them a future, to stop the past from continuing to act. The duty to remember, pressed without limit, becomes the enemy of any common life among former enemies; there are things a people must consent not to know about itself in order to remain one people.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The appeal to 'the ancient amnesties' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["prove that the wrongs of the past never really mattered very much in the first place, since societies have always found it easy enough to set them quietly aside and move on whenever it happened to suit them", "show that ancient societies were, on the whole, more forgiving than our own", "argue that the amnesty is a narrow legal device of little use in modern conditions", "offer a precedent for deliberate forgetting as the refusal of a future to past wrongs, not a denial that they ever happened"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the amnesties 'did not deny that the wrongs happened but refused them a future', the model of deliberate forgetting the passage commends. A is the trap, turning a chosen forgetting into the claim that the wrongs were trivial, which the passage explicitly resists. B and C reduce the example to a comparison of eras or a remark on legal technique.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-112", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s21", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged never to forget, and against certain wrongs the injunction is right. But a society that forgets nothing cannot end a quarrel. Every peace after a civil war has rested on a measure of deliberate forgetting, an agreement not to keep the full account, because a community in which each remembers exactly what each did can only go on settling scores. The ancient amnesties understood this: to declare that certain wrongs would not be recalled was not to deny that they happened but to refuse them a future, to stop the past from continuing to act. The duty to remember, pressed without limit, becomes the enemy of any common life among former enemies; there are things a people must consent not to know about itself in order to remain one people.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["victims of a wrong usually want it to be remembered, not quietly set aside", "deliberately forgetting a painful past is, psychologically, very hard to do", "societies that aired the full record of past wrongs have made the most durable peace", "some wrongs are so great that no one could be expected to forget them at all"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage holds that a community that remembers exactly what each did 'can only go on settling scores', so peace needs forgetting; if full public remembrance is what actually produces lasting peace, that claim is directly contradicted. A is about what victims want; B about the difficulty of forgetting; D concedes a limiting case the passage already allows ('against certain wrongs the injunction is right').", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-113", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s21", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged never to forget, and against certain wrongs the injunction is right. But a society that forgets nothing cannot end a quarrel. Every peace after a civil war has rested on a measure of deliberate forgetting, an agreement not to keep the full account, because a community in which each remembers exactly what each did can only go on settling scores. The ancient amnesties understood this: to declare that certain wrongs would not be recalled was not to deny that they happened but to refuse them a future, to stop the past from continuing to act. The duty to remember, pressed without limit, becomes the enemy of any common life among former enemies; there are things a people must consent not to know about itself in order to remain one people.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'The ancient amnesties understood this', 'amnesty' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["a loss of memory brought on by injury or illness", "a truce or ceasefire agreed in the middle of a war", "a pardon for one's sins sought from a god", "an official decision to overlook past offences"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: an amnesty is a public, deliberate decision to pass over past offences, which is why the passage offers it as the model of chosen forgetting. A is the trap, the near-homonym amnesia (memory lost involuntarily through injury); B narrows it to a battlefield truce; C takes it as religious absolution, none of which is the official overlooking meant.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-114", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s21", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We are urged never to forget, and against certain wrongs the injunction is right. But a society that forgets nothing cannot end a quarrel. Every peace after a civil war has rested on a measure of deliberate forgetting, an agreement not to keep the full account, because a community in which each remembers exactly what each did can only go on settling scores. The ancient amnesties understood this: to declare that certain wrongs would not be recalled was not to deny that they happened but to refuse them a future, to stop the past from continuing to act. The duty to remember, pressed without limit, becomes the enemy of any common life among former enemies; there are things a people must consent not to know about itself in order to remain one people.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best fits the deliberate forgetting the passage defends?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man who, through age, genuinely forgets a bitter quarrel he was once involved in", "a country emerging from civil war that agrees not to prosecute the combatants on either side, so that former enemies can live together again", "a government that destroys the archives of its predecessor's crimes and forbids any mention of them, so that the citizens of the next generation will grow up believing that the crimes were never committed at all", "a community that holds an annual ceremony to recall and mourn a past atrocity"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: agreeing not to keep the full account so as to remain one people is the deliberate, consented forgetting the passage defends, a refusal of a future to the wrongs. C is the trap, not a chosen overlooking but a denial 'that they happened', precisely what the passage says amnesty is not. A is involuntary forgetting; D is the determination to remember the passage sets itself against.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-022", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s22", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ambition is defended as the engine of great achievement, and so it can be; but it carries a quiet corruption that success disguises. The ambitious reformer wants the reform, but he also wants to be its author, and these two wants, though they run together for a while, are not the same and can come apart. Let another body propose the same reform, and the wish that it be done is suddenly at war with the wish that he do it; the purer the ambition, the sharper the pang at a rival's success in the very cause he professes to serve. There is a simple test of which want is uppermost: whether a man is glad when his end is reached by hands not his own. Few who call themselves servants of a cause can pass it, and the failing is invisible to them precisely because the cause is good.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim about ambition is that", format: "single_best", options: ["it is the engine of great achievement and should be cultivated in anyone who hopes to do some good in the world", "no one who pursues a cause is ever truly moved by the cause itself, but only by the wish for personal glory", "ambition for a worthy end can corrupt it, since the wish to be its author competes with the wish that the end be achieved", "the desire for recognition makes people work harder for a cause than they otherwise would, and so should be harnessed rather than condemned"], answer: 2, explanation: "C rests on 'the wish that it be done is suddenly at war with the wish that he do it'. A is the defence the passage grants then qualifies. B is a cynical absolutism the passage avoids, saying the two wants 'run together for a while' rather than that the cause is always a pretext. D is a managerial near-miss with the opposite emphasis to the passage's warning about corruption.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-115", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s22", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ambition is defended as the engine of great achievement, and so it can be; but it carries a quiet corruption that success disguises. The ambitious reformer wants the reform, but he also wants to be its author, and these two wants, though they run together for a while, are not the same and can come apart. Let another body propose the same reform, and the wish that it be done is suddenly at war with the wish that he do it; the purer the ambition, the sharper the pang at a rival's success in the very cause he professes to serve. There is a simple test of which want is uppermost: whether a man is glad when his end is reached by hands not his own. Few who call themselves servants of a cause can pass it, and the failing is invisible to them precisely because the cause is good.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'simple test of which want is uppermost', whether a man is glad when his end is reached 'by hands not his own', serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["prove that no one who works for any cause is ever in truth moved by anything other than the wish for personal glory, since hardly a single person alive could actually manage to pass the test", "suggest that ambition makes people work harder for a cause and so ought to be encouraged", "warn that two people pursuing the same good cause will always end as enemies", "supply a way to tell genuine devotion to a cause from the disguised wish to be its author, since only the first rejoices when a rival brings the end about"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: gladness at the end reached 'by hands not his own' separates wanting the reform from wanting to be its author, the test's purpose. A is the trap, sliding from 'few... can pass it' to the universal claim that everyone is moved only by glory, which the passage does not assert. B recommends harnessing ambition; C predicts enmity, neither the test's function.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-116", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s22", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ambition is defended as the engine of great achievement, and so it can be; but it carries a quiet corruption that success disguises. The ambitious reformer wants the reform, but he also wants to be its author, and these two wants, though they run together for a while, are not the same and can come apart. Let another body propose the same reform, and the wish that it be done is suddenly at war with the wish that he do it; the purer the ambition, the sharper the pang at a rival's success in the very cause he professes to serve. There is a simple test of which want is uppermost: whether a man is glad when his end is reached by hands not his own. Few who call themselves servants of a cause can pass it, and the failing is invisible to them precisely because the cause is good.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's claim about ambition?", format: "single_best", options: ["ambition has been behind a great many of the world's finest achievements", "the wish to be recognised for one's work is a perfectly natural human desire", "some causes happen to attract more ambitious people than others do", "people who want to author a reform are often glad when another achieves it"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the argument turns on the wish to be author competing with the wish that the end be reached; if those who most want the credit are nonetheless glad when others succeed, that competition is not the rule the passage makes it, and the corruption it diagnoses does not follow. A and B grant ambition's uses and naturalness without touching the point; C is about who is drawn to causes.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-117", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s22", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ambition is defended as the engine of great achievement, and so it can be; but it carries a quiet corruption that success disguises. The ambitious reformer wants the reform, but he also wants to be its author, and these two wants, though they run together for a while, are not the same and can come apart. Let another body propose the same reform, and the wish that it be done is suddenly at war with the wish that he do it; the purer the ambition, the sharper the pang at a rival's success in the very cause he professes to serve. There is a simple test of which want is uppermost: whether a man is glad when his end is reached by hands not his own. Few who call themselves servants of a cause can pass it, and the failing is invisible to them precisely because the cause is good.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'it carries a quiet corruption that success disguises', 'corruption' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["the taking of bribes by those in office", "a spoiling of something otherwise good", "a physical rotting or decay", "an error that creeps into a text or record"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the corruption here is the inward spoiling of a worthy motive, the cause corrupted from within by the wish for authorship. A is the trap, the bribery sense of corruption; C the literal decay sense; D the data-error sense, none of which is the moral spoiling the passage means.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-118", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s22", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Ambition is defended as the engine of great achievement, and so it can be; but it carries a quiet corruption that success disguises. The ambitious reformer wants the reform, but he also wants to be its author, and these two wants, though they run together for a while, are not the same and can come apart. Let another body propose the same reform, and the wish that it be done is suddenly at war with the wish that he do it; the purer the ambition, the sharper the pang at a rival's success in the very cause he professes to serve. There is a simple test of which want is uppermost: whether a man is glad when his end is reached by hands not his own. Few who call themselves servants of a cause can pass it, and the failing is invisible to them precisely because the cause is good.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Who, by the passage's test, shows the corruption it describes?", format: "single_best", options: ["a campaigner who has worked for years for a particular law and feels a sharp pang of resentment when a rival group is the one to get it passed", "a campaigner who is simply glad when the reform he had wanted is at last achieved", "a scientist who, having raced for years to be first to a discovery and then been narrowly beaten to it by another laboratory, publishes a generous tribute to his rivals and turns at once to the next problem without a backward glance", "a man who openly admits that he wants fame and works hard in the hope of winning it"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: 'the sharper the pang at a rival's success in the very cause he professes to serve', the precise mark of the corruption, failing the test of gladness at another's hand. C is the trap, a man who passes the test, glad the end is reached though not by him. B is the uncorrupted case; D is open ambition, not the hidden corruption of a professed servant of the cause.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-023", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s23", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is tempting to mark off curiosity from prurience by their objects, as though there were wholesome things to want to know and unwholesome ones. But the same fact, a stranger's grief, a scandal, the inside of a marriage, can be the object of either, and the difference lies not in what is wanted but in how. Curiosity wants to understand, and understanding submits itself to its object, takes the trouble to get the thing right, and is checked by the reality of the person it concerns. Prurience wants the frisson, and the object is for it merely the occasion of a sensation; it does not care to understand and would be disappointed by an explanation that dispelled the thrill. The two can fix on the identical fact and remain opposite, the one an act of respect for a reality, the other a use of it.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central distinction between curiosity and prurience is that", format: "single_best", options: ["they differ in their objects, curiosity seeking wholesome knowledge and prurience fixing on the scandalous and the private", "any interest in the private affairs of others is at bottom a form of prurience, however it dresses itself up as a wish to understand", "curiosity is patient and disciplined where prurience is impulsive, the one willing to do the work of understanding that the other shirks", "they are distinguished not by their object but by the knower's relation to it, curiosity submitting to the thing while prurience merely uses it"], answer: 3, explanation: "D rests on 'the difference lies not in what is wanted but in how' and 'an act of respect for a reality, the other a use of it'. A is the object-based criterion the passage rejects. B collapses curiosity into prurience, where the passage keeps them distinct. C is a near-miss about diligence; the passage's defining contrast is the relation to the object, not effort.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-119", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s23", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is tempting to mark off curiosity from prurience by their objects, as though there were wholesome things to want to know and unwholesome ones. But the same fact, a stranger's grief, a scandal, the inside of a marriage, can be the object of either, and the difference lies not in what is wanted but in how. Curiosity wants to understand, and understanding submits itself to its object, takes the trouble to get the thing right, and is checked by the reality of the person it concerns. Prurience wants the frisson, and the object is for it merely the occasion of a sensation; it does not care to understand and would be disappointed by an explanation that dispelled the thrill. The two can fix on the identical fact and remain opposite, the one an act of respect for a reality, the other a use of it.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The insistence that 'the same fact... can be the object of either' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["suggest that some facts about people are simply not fit to be known by anyone at all", "show that the prurient and the curious are, as a rule, interested in quite different things", "rule out the object as the mark of the difference, forcing the distinction onto the knower's relation to what is known", "prove that there is in the end no real difference between curiosity and prurience at all, since the two may fix on exactly the same fact and so must come to one and the same thing"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: if 'the same fact... can be the object of either', the object cannot be what tells them apart, so 'the difference lies not in what is wanted but in how'. D is the trap, taking the shared object to collapse the distinction, the very inference the passage blocks. A reads it as a point about forbidden knowledge; B denies the shared object the passage insists on.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-120", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s23", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is tempting to mark off curiosity from prurience by their objects, as though there were wholesome things to want to know and unwholesome ones. But the same fact, a stranger's grief, a scandal, the inside of a marriage, can be the object of either, and the difference lies not in what is wanted but in how. Curiosity wants to understand, and understanding submits itself to its object, takes the trouble to get the thing right, and is checked by the reality of the person it concerns. Prurience wants the frisson, and the object is for it merely the occasion of a sensation; it does not care to understand and would be disappointed by an explanation that dispelled the thrill. The two can fix on the identical fact and remain opposite, the one an act of respect for a reality, the other a use of it.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's distinction?", format: "single_best", options: ["people often deceive themselves about which of the two motives is really moving them", "some facts can be wanted only for the frisson, so the difference does lie in the object after all", "curiosity and prurience are often mixed together in the very same person", "prurient interest is, as a matter of fact, a good deal commoner than the curious kind"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the passage stakes everything on object and motive coming apart, the same fact open to either relation; if some facts admit only the prurient relation, then the object does after all mark the difference, against the thesis. A is about self-deception; C grants that the two can mix without denying the distinction; D is about relative frequency.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-121", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s23", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is tempting to mark off curiosity from prurience by their objects, as though there were wholesome things to want to know and unwholesome ones. But the same fact, a stranger's grief, a scandal, the inside of a marriage, can be the object of either, and the difference lies not in what is wanted but in how. Curiosity wants to understand, and understanding submits itself to its object, takes the trouble to get the thing right, and is checked by the reality of the person it concerns. Prurience wants the frisson, and the object is for it merely the occasion of a sensation; it does not care to understand and would be disappointed by an explanation that dispelled the thrill. The two can fix on the identical fact and remain opposite, the one an act of respect for a reality, the other a use of it.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'Prurience wants the frisson', 'frisson' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["a thrill or shiver of excitement", "a flash of sudden understanding", "a feeling of vague unease", "a wave of moral disgust"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the frisson is the pleasurable shiver the prurient seeks, 'the object... merely the occasion of a sensation'. B is the trap, an insight, which belongs to curiosity's wish to understand, not prurience's; C and D substitute unease and disgust for the thrill the word names.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-122", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s23", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is tempting to mark off curiosity from prurience by their objects, as though there were wholesome things to want to know and unwholesome ones. But the same fact, a stranger's grief, a scandal, the inside of a marriage, can be the object of either, and the difference lies not in what is wanted but in how. Curiosity wants to understand, and understanding submits itself to its object, takes the trouble to get the thing right, and is checked by the reality of the person it concerns. Prurience wants the frisson, and the object is for it merely the occasion of a sensation; it does not care to understand and would be disappointed by an explanation that dispelled the thrill. The two can fix on the identical fact and remain opposite, the one an act of respect for a reality, the other a use of it.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best fits the passage's account of curiosity, as against prurience?", format: "single_best", options: ["a biographer who studies a dead poet's love letters to understand the work, and drops a salacious rumour the moment it proves false", "a man who reads gossip purely for the thrill of it and loses all interest the moment it is explained", "a reader who devours every published detail of a celebrity's collapsing marriage, telling himself all the while that he follows the story only out of a sympathetic wish to understand what so public an ordeal must feel like from the inside", "a man who refuses, on principle, to learn anything private about anyone at all"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the biographer 'submits to its object, takes the trouble to get the thing right, and is checked by the reality', and drops what proves false, the curious relation. C is the trap, prurience dressed in the language of understanding but really after the frisson, as the relish of every detail betrays. B is avowed prurience; D is the refusal of knowledge altogether, neither relation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-024", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s24", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Complaints about inequality are often dismissed as envy dressed up as principle: the poor man, it is said, does not really want the rich man's goods shared out, he merely cannot bear that the rich man has them. There is a test that sorts the two. Envy is satisfied by levelling down: it would pull the fortunate man's advantage away even into the sea, gaining nothing for anyone, so long as the gap is closed. The egalitarian properly so called is not; he objects to the gap because of what it does to the worse off, and a levelling that helped no one would leave his complaint untouched, even affronted. So the charge of envy, though it catches some, cannot be the whole story, for it cannot explain why the genuine egalitarian refuses the very remedy that would slake an envious man.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central argument is that the charge that egalitarianism is mere envy", format: "single_best", options: ["cannot be the whole account, since envy is satisfied by levelling down for itself while the egalitarian, caring for the worse off, is not", "is correct, since the demand for equality springs from an inability to tolerate that others should possess more than oneself", "is entirely baseless, since no one who calls for greater equality is ever in fact moved by envy", "confuses two separate complaints, one about the gap between rich and poor and one about the absolute condition of the poor"], answer: 0, explanation: "A rests on the levelling-down test: it 'cannot explain why the genuine egalitarian refuses the very remedy that would slake an envious man'. B is the dismissal the passage rebuts. C over-reaches; the passage concedes the charge 'catches some', so 'entirely baseless' overshoots. D is a real-sounding relative-versus-absolute distinction, but not the passage's argument, which turns on the test, not on disentangling two complaints.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-123", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s24", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Complaints about inequality are often dismissed as envy dressed up as principle: the poor man, it is said, does not really want the rich man's goods shared out, he merely cannot bear that the rich man has them. There is a test that sorts the two. Envy is satisfied by levelling down: it would pull the fortunate man's advantage away even into the sea, gaining nothing for anyone, so long as the gap is closed. The egalitarian properly so called is not; he objects to the gap because of what it does to the worse off, and a levelling that helped no one would leave his complaint untouched, even affronted. So the charge of envy, though it catches some, cannot be the whole story, for it cannot explain why the genuine egalitarian refuses the very remedy that would slake an envious man.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The 'test that sorts the two', whether one would accept a levelling that helps no one, serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["show that envy is, in the end, a far commoner motive than genuine principle", "argue that levelling down is always a pointless exercise that helps nobody", "distinguish envy from egalitarian principle by what each would accept, since only envy is satisfied by closing the gap for its own sake", "prove that those who complain of inequality are never moved by envy in the slightest, their concern being always and exclusively for the actual condition of the worse off and never for the gap as such"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: envy 'is satisfied by levelling down' while the egalitarian is not, so willingness to accept a no-gain levelling sorts the two motives. D is the trap, overshooting into the claim that envy never moves such complaints, where the passage says only that envy 'cannot be the whole story', since it 'catches some'. A and B reduce the test to a point about frequency or the futility of levelling.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-124", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s24", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Complaints about inequality are often dismissed as envy dressed up as principle: the poor man, it is said, does not really want the rich man's goods shared out, he merely cannot bear that the rich man has them. There is a test that sorts the two. Envy is satisfied by levelling down: it would pull the fortunate man's advantage away even into the sea, gaining nothing for anyone, so long as the gap is closed. The egalitarian properly so called is not; he objects to the gap because of what it does to the worse off, and a levelling that helped no one would leave his complaint untouched, even affronted. So the charge of envy, though it catches some, cannot be the whole story, for it cannot explain why the genuine egalitarian refuses the very remedy that would slake an envious man.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's reply to the charge of envy?", format: "single_best", options: ["envy is, in practice, very hard to tell apart from honest indignation", "the rich commonly defend inequality out of plain self-interest", "there are justifications for equality other than concern for the worse off", "many egalitarians would accept a levelling that helps no one, so the test fails"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the argument rests on the egalitarian's refusing a levelling that 'helped no one'; if real egalitarians would commonly accept just such a levelling, the test no longer distinguishes them from the envious and the reply to the charge collapses. A notes a practical difficulty without denying the test's logic; B is about the rich; C adds other grounds for equality, leaving the test intact.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-125", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s24", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Complaints about inequality are often dismissed as envy dressed up as principle: the poor man, it is said, does not really want the rich man's goods shared out, he merely cannot bear that the rich man has them. There is a test that sorts the two. Envy is satisfied by levelling down: it would pull the fortunate man's advantage away even into the sea, gaining nothing for anyone, so long as the gap is closed. The egalitarian properly so called is not; he objects to the gap because of what it does to the worse off, and a levelling that helped no one would leave his complaint untouched, even affronted. So the charge of envy, though it catches some, cannot be the whole story, for it cannot explain why the genuine egalitarian refuses the very remedy that would slake an envious man.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'the very remedy that would slake an envious man', 'slake' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["to provoke or inflame", "to satisfy or quench", "to weaken by diluting", "to conceal or cover over"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: to slake the envious man is to satisfy his desire, as levelling down quenches envy by closing the gap. A is its near-opposite, to inflame; C draws on the technical sense of slaking lime by dilution; D substitutes concealment for satisfaction, neither of which is the quenching the passage means.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-126", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s24", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Complaints about inequality are often dismissed as envy dressed up as principle: the poor man, it is said, does not really want the rich man's goods shared out, he merely cannot bear that the rich man has them. There is a test that sorts the two. Envy is satisfied by levelling down: it would pull the fortunate man's advantage away even into the sea, gaining nothing for anyone, so long as the gap is closed. The egalitarian properly so called is not; he objects to the gap because of what it does to the worse off, and a levelling that helped no one would leave his complaint untouched, even affronted. So the charge of envy, though it catches some, cannot be the whole story, for it cannot explain why the genuine egalitarian refuses the very remedy that would slake an envious man.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Whose complaint about inequality does the passage's test mark as genuinely egalitarian rather than envious?", format: "single_best", options: ["a woman who would refuse to confiscate a rich man's fortune if doing so helped no one, but presses hard for measures that actually raise the poor", "a man who is indifferent to inequality so long as he himself is comfortable enough", "a man who would gladly see a rich neighbour's vineyard burned to the ground even if the ash enriched no one and fed nobody, simply so that the two of them should at last be made to stand upon the same level", "a man who admires the rich and hopes one day to become one of them himself"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: refusing a levelling that 'helped no one' while pressing to raise the worse off is exactly the egalitarian concerned for 'what the gap does to the worse off', passing the test. C is the trap, the envy 'satisfied by levelling down' for its own sake, gaining nothing for anyone. B is indifference; D is admiration of wealth, neither the egalitarian complaint at issue.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-025", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s25", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is an old complaint that good advice is wasted, that people consult the wise and then do the opposite. The fault is usually laid on the advised, their weakness or their vanity. But the difficulty is built into advice itself. What lets the counsellor see clearly is his distance from the trouble: not being in love, he can see that the affair is folly; not being afraid, he can see that the risk is small. But this very distance is what the sufferer lacks and cannot borrow. Advice hands over a conclusion while withholding the only thing that could make it convincing, namely the standpoint from which it is obvious. The advised is asked to act on a clarity he does not possess, and his failure to do so is not weakness but the predictable result of being given the answer without the position from which it is an answer.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim is that good advice is so often disregarded because", format: "single_best", options: ["those who receive it are too weak or too vain to act against their own settled inclinations", "the detachment that gives the counsellor clarity is just what the sufferer lacks, so advice arrives as a conclusion stripped of its standpoint", "no one can really learn anything from another's counsel, since wisdom can only be won through one's own experience", "the counsellor, being outside the situation, cannot grasp its particulars well enough to give advice that truly fits the case"], answer: 1, explanation: "B rests on 'this very distance is what the sufferer lacks and cannot borrow'. A is the usual explanation the passage displaces. C over-reaches into total futility, where the passage diagnoses a specific structural difficulty. D reverses the passage, which says distance lets the counsellor see clearly, not that it leaves him ignorant of the particulars.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-127", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s25", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is an old complaint that good advice is wasted, that people consult the wise and then do the opposite. The fault is usually laid on the advised, their weakness or their vanity. But the difficulty is built into advice itself. What lets the counsellor see clearly is his distance from the trouble: not being in love, he can see that the affair is folly; not being afraid, he can see that the risk is small. But this very distance is what the sufferer lacks and cannot borrow. Advice hands over a conclusion while withholding the only thing that could make it convincing, namely the standpoint from which it is obvious. The advised is asked to act on a clarity he does not possess, and his failure to do so is not weakness but the predictable result of being given the answer without the position from which it is an answer.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The contrast 'not being in love, he can see that the affair is folly; not being afraid, he can see that the risk is small' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["prove that those who hand out advice are, as a class, emotionally cold people, incapable of the passions that move ordinary men and women and therefore very poorly placed to pass judgement on them", "show that advice, being clear-sighted, is usually right and so ought to be followed", "warn that the counsellor underestimates how strong the sufferer's feelings really are", "locate the counsellor's clarity in his very distance from the trouble, the thing the sufferer in the grip of it cannot share"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: 'what lets the counsellor see clearly is his distance from the trouble', the standpoint the sufferer 'lacks and cannot borrow', the contrast's point. A is the trap, turning the counsellor's distance into a coldness of temperament, where the passage makes it a matter of position, not character. B reads it as endorsing advice; C as a charge that the counsellor misjudges the feelings.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-128", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s25", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is an old complaint that good advice is wasted, that people consult the wise and then do the opposite. The fault is usually laid on the advised, their weakness or their vanity. But the difficulty is built into advice itself. What lets the counsellor see clearly is his distance from the trouble: not being in love, he can see that the affair is folly; not being afraid, he can see that the risk is small. But this very distance is what the sufferer lacks and cannot borrow. Advice hands over a conclusion while withholding the only thing that could make it convincing, namely the standpoint from which it is obvious. The advised is asked to act on a clarity he does not possess, and his failure to do so is not weakness but the predictable result of being given the answer without the position from which it is an answer.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's explanation?", format: "single_best", options: ["advice is, more often than not, clumsily and tactlessly given", "people tend to resent being given advice they did not ask for", "the sufferer can reach the detached view by his own effort after all", "counsellors are themselves sometimes mistaken in the advice they give"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the argument depends on the standpoint being one the sufferer 'cannot borrow'; if he can reach the detached view by his own effort, then the failure to act on advice is not the inevitable thing the passage makes it. A and B are about how advice is given and received; D notes that advice can be wrong, a different matter from why sound advice is ignored.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-129", genre: "dialectic", skill: "tone", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s25", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is an old complaint that good advice is wasted, that people consult the wise and then do the opposite. The fault is usually laid on the advised, their weakness or their vanity. But the difficulty is built into advice itself. What lets the counsellor see clearly is his distance from the trouble: not being in love, he can see that the affair is folly; not being afraid, he can see that the risk is small. But this very distance is what the sufferer lacks and cannot borrow. Advice hands over a conclusion while withholding the only thing that could make it convincing, namely the standpoint from which it is obvious. The advised is asked to act on a clarity he does not possess, and his failure to do so is not weakness but the predictable result of being given the answer without the position from which it is an answer.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's attitude toward the person who ignores good advice is best described as", format: "single_best", options: ["understanding, treating the failure to act as predictable rather than as a moral weakness", "indifferent, regarding the whole question as of no real importance", "admiring, praising the advised person for trusting his own judgement over another's", "sharply censorious, holding the advised person culpably weak for failing to act on a clarity that was, after all, offered to him in good faith and entirely free of charge"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the passage says his failure 'is not weakness but the predictable result' of lacking the standpoint, a sympathetic, exculpating attitude. D is the trap, the blaming view the passage explicitly sets aside ('The fault is usually laid on the advised'). B mistakes the careful analysis for indifference; C reads approval into what is really an explanation.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-130", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s25", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "It is an old complaint that good advice is wasted, that people consult the wise and then do the opposite. The fault is usually laid on the advised, their weakness or their vanity. But the difficulty is built into advice itself. What lets the counsellor see clearly is his distance from the trouble: not being in love, he can see that the affair is folly; not being afraid, he can see that the risk is small. But this very distance is what the sufferer lacks and cannot borrow. Advice hands over a conclusion while withholding the only thing that could make it convincing, namely the standpoint from which it is obvious. The advised is asked to act on a clarity he does not possess, and his failure to do so is not weakness but the predictable result of being given the answer without the position from which it is an answer.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best illustrates why, on the passage's account, good advice so often fails?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man who rejects advice he knows perfectly well to be sound, purely out of stubborn pride", "a friend tells a man in love that his partner is plainly using him; the man follows the reasoning and yet cannot feel its force while the love still holds him", "a man receives shrewd financial advice from an expert, follows it to the letter without ever really grasping the reasoning behind it, and is duly rewarded when the investment turns out exactly as the expert had foretold it would", "a man is given confident advice by someone who has plainly not understood his situation at all"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the man 'is asked to act on a clarity he does not possess', seeing the conclusion but unable to feel it from inside the love, the failure the passage explains. C is the trap, a case where advice succeeds, and on a matter where the missing standpoint does not bite. A is wilful pride, the weakness the passage denies is the real cause; D is advice that fails because it is ill-fitted, not because the standpoint cannot be shared.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-026", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s26", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a feeling that an act done from mere habit cannot be virtuous, that virtue must cost something, must be wrung from a reluctant nature in the teeth of temptation. On this view the man who returns the lost wallet without a flicker of temptation to keep it is less admirable than the man who wrestles his greed and barely wins. But this inverts the truth. The struggle is the mark not of the virtuous man but of the man still becoming one; in him goodness is not yet at home, and must each time defeat a rival. The settled honesty that feels no pull toward the purse is not a lesser thing than the victory over greed but a further stage, where the rival has not been beaten but has ceased to appear. We praise the struggle because we can see it, and overlook the deeper virtue that has nothing left to fight.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "What the author finally maintains is that", format: "single_best", options: ["an act is virtuous only when it is chosen against a contrary temptation, since virtue won without struggle costs nothing and proves nothing", "temptation is no part of the moral life at all, and a person who still feels it has by that fact already failed", "the effortless act of a settled disposition marks a higher virtue than the hard-won victory over temptation, which belongs to one still becoming good", "virtue is best cultivated by repeatedly acting well until good conduct becomes second nature and the pull of temptation fades"], answer: 2, explanation: "C rests on 'a further stage, where the rival has not been beaten but has ceased to appear'. A is the view the passage inverts. B over-reaches: the passage treats the struggler as on the way to virtue, not as already failed. D is a developmental maxim about how to acquire virtue, where the passage's claim ranks the two states, not advises on cultivation.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-131", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s26", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a feeling that an act done from mere habit cannot be virtuous, that virtue must cost something, must be wrung from a reluctant nature in the teeth of temptation. On this view the man who returns the lost wallet without a flicker of temptation to keep it is less admirable than the man who wrestles his greed and barely wins. But this inverts the truth. The struggle is the mark not of the virtuous man but of the man still becoming one; in him goodness is not yet at home, and must each time defeat a rival. The settled honesty that feels no pull toward the purse is not a lesser thing than the victory over greed but a further stage, where the rival has not been beaten but has ceased to appear. We praise the struggle because we can see it, and overlook the deeper virtue that has nothing left to fight.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The example of 'the man who returns the lost wallet without a flicker of temptation to keep it' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["show that most people would, in fact, feel at least some temptation to keep the wallet", "illustrate that plain honesty is a good deal commoner than we tend to suppose", "concede that such a man, feeling no temptation whatsoever, can claim no credit at all for an honesty that costs him precisely nothing and demands nothing of him in the way of effort", "present, against the common view, the very case the passage means to rank highest, a virtue so settled that it feels no contrary pull"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the untempted returner is the 'settled honesty that feels no pull', which the passage calls 'a further stage' above the struggler, the case it means to elevate. C is the trap, the popular verdict the passage overturns ('this inverts the truth'). A and B reduce the example to a point about how tempted or how honest most people are.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-132", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s26", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a feeling that an act done from mere habit cannot be virtuous, that virtue must cost something, must be wrung from a reluctant nature in the teeth of temptation. On this view the man who returns the lost wallet without a flicker of temptation to keep it is less admirable than the man who wrestles his greed and barely wins. But this inverts the truth. The struggle is the mark not of the virtuous man but of the man still becoming one; in him goodness is not yet at home, and must each time defeat a rival. The settled honesty that feels no pull toward the purse is not a lesser thing than the victory over greed but a further stage, where the rival has not been beaten but has ceased to appear. We praise the struggle because we can see it, and overlook the deeper virtue that has nothing left to fight.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's ranking?", format: "single_best", options: ["what we admire in virtue is a victory won, so where no temptation is felt nothing is achieved", "people who feel no temptation at all to do wrong are extremely rare", "the man who struggles against temptation is easier for the rest of us to identify with", "a settled good habit can be lost as easily as it was gained"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the passage ranks effortless virtue above the hard-won kind; if what makes virtue admirable just is the winning of a real struggle, then the untempted man, having won nothing, is the lesser case, reversing the passage's order. B and C are about rarity and relatability; D is about whether habits last, not whether the effortless act is the higher virtue.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-133", genre: "dialectic", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s26", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a feeling that an act done from mere habit cannot be virtuous, that virtue must cost something, must be wrung from a reluctant nature in the teeth of temptation. On this view the man who returns the lost wallet without a flicker of temptation to keep it is less admirable than the man who wrestles his greed and barely wins. But this inverts the truth. The struggle is the mark not of the virtuous man but of the man still becoming one; in him goodness is not yet at home, and must each time defeat a rival. The settled honesty that feels no pull toward the purse is not a lesser thing than the victory over greed but a further stage, where the rival has not been beaten but has ceased to appear. We praise the struggle because we can see it, and overlook the deeper virtue that has nothing left to fight.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "That 'in him goodness is not yet at home' implies of the struggler that", format: "single_best", options: ["goodness is an utter stranger to him, a thing he merely pretends to from time to time for show, without any of it ever taking the least root in his actual character", "goodness has not yet become settled and natural in him, so that it must each time defeat a rival to act at all", "he has not yet learned what goodness actually requires of him in the first place", "he is good only on those occasions when he knows that others are watching him"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: 'not yet at home' means goodness has not yet settled into him, so 'it must each time defeat a rival', the struggler's condition. A is the trap, pushing not-yet-settled into wholly absent or feigned, where the passage grants he is genuinely 'becoming' good. C makes it ignorance; D makes it hypocrisy, neither the unsettledness meant.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-134", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s26", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "There is a feeling that an act done from mere habit cannot be virtuous, that virtue must cost something, must be wrung from a reluctant nature in the teeth of temptation. On this view the man who returns the lost wallet without a flicker of temptation to keep it is less admirable than the man who wrestles his greed and barely wins. But this inverts the truth. The struggle is the mark not of the virtuous man but of the man still becoming one; in him goodness is not yet at home, and must each time defeat a rival. The settled honesty that feels no pull toward the purse is not a lesser thing than the victory over greed but a further stage, where the rival has not been beaten but has ceased to appear. We praise the struggle because we can see it, and overlook the deeper virtue that has nothing left to fight.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Whom would the passage rank as showing the higher virtue?", format: "single_best", options: ["a woman who gives only when she is sure of being publicly thanked for it", "a woman who must each time fight down a strong impulse to keep her money, and only after a hard inward struggle, and not on every occasion, brings herself to give away even the smaller part of it", "a woman who gives generously and feels no inward tug of meanness, generosity having become second nature to her", "a woman who never gives anything at all and feels not the least wish to"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the 'settled' generosity that feels no contrary pull is the 'further stage, where the rival has not been beaten but has ceased to appear', the higher virtue. B is the trap, the hard-won struggle the passage ranks lower, as belonging to one 'still in the course of becoming'. A gives for praise; D has no virtue at all, feeling no pull because it never gives.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-027", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s27", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We treat boredom as a vacancy, a lack of things to engage us, and reach for the remedy of more: more novelty, more stimulation, a fresh screen when the last palls. But the bored man is rarely short of objects; he sits in a room full of things he might attend to, a book, a window, his own thoughts, and finds them all flat. His complaint is not that the world has offered him too little but that nothing it offers will do. Boredom is thus less an emptiness than a refusal, a withdrawal of interest that no quantity of new objects can satisfy, since it is not objects that are wanting. This is why the cure of more stimulation fails and feeds what it would cure: each fresh novelty, consumed and discarded, confirms the very stance, that nothing here is worth attending to, from which the boredom came.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage's central claim about boredom is that it", format: "single_best", options: ["arises from a lack of engaging things to do, and is relieved by introducing fresh sources of novelty and stimulation", "is wholly self-inflicted, so that anyone who is bored has only their own ingratitude to blame", "results from consuming too much novelty, which gradually dulls the capacity to take pleasure in ordinary things", "is not an absence of things to engage with but a withdrawal of interest from objects already there, so more cannot cure it"], answer: 3, explanation: "D rests on 'less an emptiness than a refusal' and 'it is not objects that are wanting'. A is the vacancy view the passage rejects. B is a moralising over-claim the passage does not make. C names over-stimulation as a feeder of the stance, but the passage defines boredom as a refusal prior to that cycle, not as its product.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-135", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s27", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We treat boredom as a vacancy, a lack of things to engage us, and reach for the remedy of more: more novelty, more stimulation, a fresh screen when the last palls. But the bored man is rarely short of objects; he sits in a room full of things he might attend to, a book, a window, his own thoughts, and finds them all flat. His complaint is not that the world has offered him too little but that nothing it offers will do. Boredom is thus less an emptiness than a refusal, a withdrawal of interest that no quantity of new objects can satisfy, since it is not objects that are wanting. This is why the cure of more stimulation fails and feeds what it would cure: each fresh novelty, consumed and discarded, confirms the very stance, that nothing here is worth attending to, from which the boredom came.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The observation that the bored man 'sits in a room full of things he might attend to... and finds them all flat' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["suggest that the bored person really needs more interesting surroundings than he has", "argue that boredom comes, after all, of simply having too little to do", "show that boredom is not a shortage of objects but a withdrawal of interest from objects that are already there to be attended to", "prove that the bored man is at bottom simply ungrateful, surrounded by good things which he is too idle or too thoroughly spoilt to trouble himself to make any use of"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: 'the bored man is rarely short of objects', yet finds them flat, so the lack is of interest, not of things, the passage's redefinition. D is the trap, moralising boredom into ingratitude, a verdict the passage does not pass. A and B keep the very shortage-of-objects view ('more', 'too little to do') the passage is rejecting.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-136", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s27", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We treat boredom as a vacancy, a lack of things to engage us, and reach for the remedy of more: more novelty, more stimulation, a fresh screen when the last palls. But the bored man is rarely short of objects; he sits in a room full of things he might attend to, a book, a window, his own thoughts, and finds them all flat. His complaint is not that the world has offered him too little but that nothing it offers will do. Boredom is thus less an emptiness than a refusal, a withdrawal of interest that no quantity of new objects can satisfy, since it is not objects that are wanting. This is why the cure of more stimulation fails and feeds what it would cure: each fresh novelty, consumed and discarded, confirms the very stance, that nothing here is worth attending to, from which the boredom came.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the passage's account of boredom?", format: "single_best", options: ["people stop being bored once engaging things appear, so objects were the lack", "those who complain most of boredom are often the most privileged", "the appetite for novelty is something almost everyone shares", "boredom is, for most people, a distinctly unpleasant state to be in"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the passage holds that 'no quantity of new objects can satisfy' because the lack is of interest, not things; if supplying engaging objects does reliably cure boredom, then it was a shortage of objects, against the thesis. B is about who is bored; C about the appetite for novelty; D about boredom's unpleasantness, none touching the core claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-137", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s27", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We treat boredom as a vacancy, a lack of things to engage us, and reach for the remedy of more: more novelty, more stimulation, a fresh screen when the last palls. But the bored man is rarely short of objects; he sits in a room full of things he might attend to, a book, a window, his own thoughts, and finds them all flat. His complaint is not that the world has offered him too little but that nothing it offers will do. Boredom is thus less an emptiness than a refusal, a withdrawal of interest that no quantity of new objects can satisfy, since it is not objects that are wanting. This is why the cure of more stimulation fails and feeds what it would cure: each fresh novelty, consumed and discarded, confirms the very stance, that nothing here is worth attending to, from which the boredom came.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'a fresh screen when the last palls', 'palls' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["grows suddenly alarming", "loses its savour and grows wearisome", "covers something over like a shroud", "fades gradually from the memory"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: when the last screen palls it ceases to please and begins to weary, which is why one reaches for a fresh one. C is the trap, the unrelated noun pall (a cloth over a coffin); A and D substitute alarm and forgetting for the staling of interest the verb names here.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-138", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s27", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "We treat boredom as a vacancy, a lack of things to engage us, and reach for the remedy of more: more novelty, more stimulation, a fresh screen when the last palls. But the bored man is rarely short of objects; he sits in a room full of things he might attend to, a book, a window, his own thoughts, and finds them all flat. His complaint is not that the world has offered him too little but that nothing it offers will do. Boredom is thus less an emptiness than a refusal, a withdrawal of interest that no quantity of new objects can satisfy, since it is not objects that are wanting. This is why the cure of more stimulation fails and feeds what it would cure: each fresh novelty, consumed and discarded, confirms the very stance, that nothing here is worth attending to, from which the boredom came.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best fits the passage's account of why more stimulation fails to cure boredom?", format: "single_best", options: ["a man who cures his boredom for good by taking up one demanding discipline and faithfully sticking to it", "a man who is far too busy with absorbing work to feel any boredom at all", "a man who is bored only because he has genuinely run clean out of anything to do, and who is at once and lastingly absorbed the very moment a friend turns up with a fascinating new project for the two of them to set to work on together", "a man who, bored, flicks through a hundred channels, each briefly diverting and then flat, confirming with every one that nothing here is worth his attention"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: each new novelty, 'consumed and discarded, confirms the very stance... that nothing here is worth attending to', so the cure feeds the disease, exactly the passage's mechanism. C is the trap, boredom as a real lack of objects that fresh objects cure, the view the passage denies. B is never bored; A escapes boredom by renewed attention, not by more novelty.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-028", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s28", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The cultivation of taste is presented as pure gain: the trained palate finds in a thing distinctions the novice misses, and so, it is assumed, enjoys it more. Often it does. But discrimination has a cost the story leaves out. To learn the faults of a thing is to become unable not to see them, and the connoisseur who can no longer hear a familiar symphony without registering the orchestra's small failures has bought his fine perception at the price of the absorbed delight the amateur still has. The enthusiast's pleasure is whole because it is undivided by judgement; the expert's is keener in its parts but can no longer be whole. Refinement, then, is not simply more of the same pleasure but a different and partly poorer relation to its object, and whether the trade is worth it is not the settled question the praise of good taste assumes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim is that refined taste", format: "single_best", options: ["is not simply a greater capacity for enjoyment but a trade, buying fine discrimination at the cost of the amateur's whole absorption", "enhances enjoyment, since the trained perceiver finds in a work pleasures that the untrained novice cannot reach at all", "spoils enjoyment altogether, so that the expert in the end takes less pleasure in art than the amateur does", "ought to be cultivated only so far, lest the pursuit of discrimination cost one the capacity for simple enjoyment"], answer: 0, explanation: "A rests on 'a different and partly poorer relation to its object' and 'bought his fine perception at the price of the absorbed delight'. B is the pure-gain view the passage complicates. C over-reaches: the passage says the expert's pleasure is 'keener in its parts', a trade, not an outright loss. D turns the analysis into counsel of moderation, where the passage diagnoses a trade-off and leaves 'whether the trade is worth it' open.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-139", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s28", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The cultivation of taste is presented as pure gain: the trained palate finds in a thing distinctions the novice misses, and so, it is assumed, enjoys it more. Often it does. But discrimination has a cost the story leaves out. To learn the faults of a thing is to become unable not to see them, and the connoisseur who can no longer hear a familiar symphony without registering the orchestra's small failures has bought his fine perception at the price of the absorbed delight the amateur still has. The enthusiast's pleasure is whole because it is undivided by judgement; the expert's is keener in its parts but can no longer be whole. Refinement, then, is not simply more of the same pleasure but a different and partly poorer relation to its object, and whether the trade is worth it is not the settled question the praise of good taste assumes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The example of the connoisseur who 'can no longer hear a familiar symphony without registering the orchestra's small failures' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["argue that orchestras in fact play a good deal less well than they used to", "suggest that the expert simply hears more in the music than the amateur and so enjoys all of it more", "show the cost of fine discrimination, that it makes one unable not to see faults, and so divides the once-whole pleasure", "prove that the trained listener takes no pleasure in music whatever any longer, every performance being for him merely a dry catalogue of the small errors that he cannot any longer help noticing all through it"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the connoisseur 'can no longer hear... without registering the orchestra's small failures', the price of discrimination that breaks up the amateur's whole delight. D is the trap, hardening a divided pleasure into no pleasure at all, where the passage says the expert's is 'keener in its parts'. A blames the orchestras; B is the pure-gain view the passage is complicating.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-140", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s28", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The cultivation of taste is presented as pure gain: the trained palate finds in a thing distinctions the novice misses, and so, it is assumed, enjoys it more. Often it does. But discrimination has a cost the story leaves out. To learn the faults of a thing is to become unable not to see them, and the connoisseur who can no longer hear a familiar symphony without registering the orchestra's small failures has bought his fine perception at the price of the absorbed delight the amateur still has. The enthusiast's pleasure is whole because it is undivided by judgement; the expert's is keener in its parts but can no longer be whole. Refinement, then, is not simply more of the same pleasure but a different and partly poorer relation to its object, and whether the trade is worth it is not the settled question the praise of good taste assumes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's claim about refined taste?", format: "single_best", options: ["people differ as to what they will count as a fault in a performance", "some connoisseurs are insufferably pompous about their own refinement", "novices frequently take great pleasure in work that is, by any standard, bad", "trained perceivers say finer discrimination deepens rather than divides absorption"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the case is that the expert's pleasure 'can no longer be whole'; if fine discrimination in fact deepens absorption rather than breaking it up, the alleged trade does not occur and refinement is the pure gain the passage denies. A is about what counts as a fault; B about experts' manners; C about novices enjoying bad work, none touching the trade-off claim.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-141", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s28", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The cultivation of taste is presented as pure gain: the trained palate finds in a thing distinctions the novice misses, and so, it is assumed, enjoys it more. Often it does. But discrimination has a cost the story leaves out. To learn the faults of a thing is to become unable not to see them, and the connoisseur who can no longer hear a familiar symphony without registering the orchestra's small failures has bought his fine perception at the price of the absorbed delight the amateur still has. The enthusiast's pleasure is whole because it is undivided by judgement; the expert's is keener in its parts but can no longer be whole. Refinement, then, is not simply more of the same pleasure but a different and partly poorer relation to its object, and whether the trade is worth it is not the settled question the praise of good taste assumes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'discrimination has a cost the story leaves out', 'discrimination' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["the unjust treatment of a particular group", "the drawing of fine distinctions", "good taste in dress and manners", "a wary mistrust of other people"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: discrimination here is the trained perceiver's power to draw fine distinctions, 'distinctions the novice misses'. A is the trap, the social-prejudice sense of discrimination; C narrows it to sartorial taste; D takes the sense of suspicion, neither of which fits the fineness of perception meant.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-142", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s28", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "The cultivation of taste is presented as pure gain: the trained palate finds in a thing distinctions the novice misses, and so, it is assumed, enjoys it more. Often it does. But discrimination has a cost the story leaves out. To learn the faults of a thing is to become unable not to see them, and the connoisseur who can no longer hear a familiar symphony without registering the orchestra's small failures has bought his fine perception at the price of the absorbed delight the amateur still has. The enthusiast's pleasure is whole because it is undivided by judgement; the expert's is keener in its parts but can no longer be whole. Refinement, then, is not simply more of the same pleasure but a different and partly poorer relation to its object, and whether the trade is worth it is not the settled question the praise of good taste assumes.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best illustrates the trade the passage describes?", format: "single_best", options: ["a wine-lover who, having trained his palate, now notices a flaw in almost every glass and can no longer simply enjoy a drink as he once did", "a man who knows nothing of wine and happily enjoys whatever he is poured", "a wine-lover who finds, the more he learns, that he enjoys every glass more completely than before, each new distinction he is able to draw adding one further layer to a pleasure that loses nothing whatever of its old wholeness", "a man who pretends to a connoisseurship of wine that he does not actually possess"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: training has bought him fine discrimination 'at the price of the absorbed delight the amateur still has', exactly the trade. C is the trap, refinement as pure gain with no loss of wholeness, the comfortable story the passage sets out to complicate. B is the untrained whole pleasure, not the trade; D is mere pretence, no discrimination at all.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-029", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s29", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "What is the use of bearing witness to a suffering one cannot relieve? The watcher does not feed the starving or stop the blow; he only looks, and to look, the objection runs, is either useless or a kind of theft, a consumption of another's pain. Yet there is a wrong that witness, and only witness, prevents. Suffering that passes entirely unseen is destroyed twice: once in the body, and once in the record, sinking without trace as though it had not been, its victims subtracted even from the count of the wronged. To witness is to refuse that second erasure, to insist that this happened and was suffered by someone, whatever follows. The value of the act lies not in any relief it brings, for it brings none, but in the acknowledgement itself, which is owed to the sufferer even when nothing else can be given.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The author's central claim is that bearing witness to a suffering one cannot relieve", format: "single_best", options: ["is useless, or even a kind of voyeurism, since merely looking at a pain one cannot ease does the sufferer no good at all", "has its value not in any relief but in the acknowledgement it gives, which keeps the suffering from being erased a second time", "is more important than the relief of suffering, since the record of a wrong outlasts any aid that might be given to its victims", "serves the living, by preserving a record that may move later generations to act so as to prevent such suffering in future"], answer: 1, explanation: "B rests on 'the acknowledgement itself, which is owed to the sufferer even when nothing else can be given'. A is the objection the passage answers. C ranks witness above relief, which the passage does not; it values witness where relief is impossible. D is the instrumental near-twin, grounding witness in future usefulness, where the passage locates its value in acknowledgement owed to this sufferer now, 'whatever follows'.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-143", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s29", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "What is the use of bearing witness to a suffering one cannot relieve? The watcher does not feed the starving or stop the blow; he only looks, and to look, the objection runs, is either useless or a kind of theft, a consumption of another's pain. Yet there is a wrong that witness, and only witness, prevents. Suffering that passes entirely unseen is destroyed twice: once in the body, and once in the record, sinking without trace as though it had not been, its victims subtracted even from the count of the wronged. To witness is to refuse that second erasure, to insist that this happened and was suffered by someone, whatever follows. The value of the act lies not in any relief it brings, for it brings none, but in the acknowledgement itself, which is owed to the sufferer even when nothing else can be given.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The claim that unseen suffering 'is destroyed twice: once in the body, and once in the record' serves to", format: "single_best", options: ["prove that keeping an accurate historical record of past suffering matters a great deal more than doing anything at all to relieve the suffering of those who are still living and might yet be helped", "suggest that suffering is somehow made worse by being observed than it would have been unseen", "argue that anyone who witnesses suffering ought always to try to relieve it as well", "identify a second harm, erasure from the record, that witness alone can prevent, so grounding its value apart from any relief"], answer: 3, explanation: "D: the 'second' destruction, sinking 'without trace as though it had not been', is the erasure witness refuses, which is why its value lies in acknowledgement, not relief. A is the trap, ranking record above relief, where the passage values witness only where relief is impossible ('it brings none'). B reads it as observation worsening suffering; C imports a duty to help the passage is setting aside.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-144", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s29", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "What is the use of bearing witness to a suffering one cannot relieve? The watcher does not feed the starving or stop the blow; he only looks, and to look, the objection runs, is either useless or a kind of theft, a consumption of another's pain. Yet there is a wrong that witness, and only witness, prevents. Suffering that passes entirely unseen is destroyed twice: once in the body, and once in the record, sinking without trace as though it had not been, its victims subtracted even from the count of the wronged. To witness is to refuse that second erasure, to insist that this happened and was suffered by someone, whatever follows. The value of the act lies not in any relief it brings, for it brings none, but in the acknowledgement itself, which is owed to the sufferer even when nothing else can be given.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the author's argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["many records of past suffering turn out, on inspection, to be inaccurate", "those who watch suffering are sometimes little better than voyeurs", "suffering loses nothing by going unrecorded, since only what is felt matters", "some suffering is so terrible that to witness it at all is almost unbearable"], answer: 2, explanation: "C: the passage rests on a real 'second erasure', a wrong done by suffering's passing unseen; if going unrecorded costs the sufferer nothing, there is no second harm for witness to prevent and its whole value collapses. A is about records' accuracy; B revives the voyeurism objection the passage answers; D is about the cost of witnessing, not its value.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-145", genre: "dialectic", skill: "figurative_language", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s29", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "What is the use of bearing witness to a suffering one cannot relieve? The watcher does not feed the starving or stop the blow; he only looks, and to look, the objection runs, is either useless or a kind of theft, a consumption of another's pain. Yet there is a wrong that witness, and only witness, prevents. Suffering that passes entirely unseen is destroyed twice: once in the body, and once in the record, sinking without trace as though it had not been, its victims subtracted even from the count of the wronged. To witness is to refuse that second erasure, to insist that this happened and was suffered by someone, whatever follows. The value of the act lies not in any relief it brings, for it brings none, but in the acknowledgement itself, which is owed to the sufferer even when nothing else can be given.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'its victims subtracted even from the count of the wronged' implies that unseen suffering", format: "single_best", options: ["is not merely unrelieved but unacknowledged, its victims dropped from the very reckoning of those to whom a wrong was done", "is felt less keenly by victims who know that no one at all is watching them", "is, as a simple matter of arithmetic, undercounted, so that the official figures for the victims of any disaster will always fall a little short of the true number of those who actually suffered in it", "is soon forgotten by everyone except the victims who lived through it themselves"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: to be 'subtracted from the count of the wronged' is to be left out of the very acknowledgement that a wrong was suffered, the second erasure witness resists. C is the trap, literalising the 'count' into a statistical undercount, a point about figures rather than acknowledgement. B makes it a matter of feeling; D a matter of being forgotten over time.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-146", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s29", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "What is the use of bearing witness to a suffering one cannot relieve? The watcher does not feed the starving or stop the blow; he only looks, and to look, the objection runs, is either useless or a kind of theft, a consumption of another's pain. Yet there is a wrong that witness, and only witness, prevents. Suffering that passes entirely unseen is destroyed twice: once in the body, and once in the record, sinking without trace as though it had not been, its victims subtracted even from the count of the wronged. To witness is to refuse that second erasure, to insist that this happened and was suffered by someone, whatever follows. The value of the act lies not in any relief it brings, for it brings none, but in the acknowledgement itself, which is owed to the sufferer even when nothing else can be given.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which case best fits the value the passage assigns to bearing witness?", format: "single_best", options: ["a passer-by who films a beating on his phone purely for the shock and thrill of it", "a nurse who can do nothing to save a dying stranger but stays with him, learns his name, and records that he lived and suffered", "a campaigner who photographs a famine in great detail and circulates the images as widely as he can, in the settled expectation that the publicity will shame distant governments into sending the aid that alone can bring the famine to an end", "a doctor who saves a patient's life and then thinks no more about the matter at all"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: unable to relieve, the nurse gives 'the acknowledgement itself, which is owed to the sufferer even when nothing else can be given', refusing the second erasure. C is the trap, witness valued instrumentally for the relief it may bring, where the passage locates its worth precisely apart from relief ('it brings none'). A is the voyeurism the passage rejects; D relieves suffering but bears no witness.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-030", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s30", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity sounds like the least radical of ideals: not that all should end equal, only that all should start fair, the race open to talent regardless of birth. But the ideal, taken to its root, turns out to ask for more than we will give. The chief source of unequal starts is not the law, which can be changed, but the family, which we will not abolish: loving parents read to their children, pass on their advantages, their confidence, their connections, and in doing so make the starting line uneven before any race begins. To equalise opportunity completely, one would have to neutralise the family's effects, and that we are not prepared to do; we want both the fair start and the freedom of parents to favour their own. The modest ideal, pursued in earnest, collides with an attachment we will not give up, and we generally resolve the collision by not pursuing it in earnest.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The passage is chiefly concerned to show that the ideal of equality of opportunity", format: "single_best", options: ["is a modest and achievable ideal, requiring only that careers be open to talent regardless of the circumstances of a person's birth", "is incoherent, and ought to be abandoned in favour of the more honest ideal of equality of outcome", "collides, taken in earnest, with a freedom to favour one's own children that we will not give up, so the ideal survives only by not being pursued", "is undermined in practice by the persistence of inherited wealth, which gives the children of the rich advantages that the law cannot easily reach"], answer: 2, explanation: "C rests on 'collides with an attachment we will not give up' and 'the family, which we will not abolish'. A is the opening characterisation the passage overturns. B recommends abandoning the ideal for equality of outcome, which the passage does not; it exposes a tension we manage by half-measures. D relocates the obstacle to inherited wealth and the law, where the passage insists the chief source is the family's nurture, which we will not touch.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-147", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s30", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity sounds like the least radical of ideals: not that all should end equal, only that all should start fair, the race open to talent regardless of birth. But the ideal, taken to its root, turns out to ask for more than we will give. The chief source of unequal starts is not the law, which can be changed, but the family, which we will not abolish: loving parents read to their children, pass on their advantages, their confidence, their connections, and in doing so make the starting line uneven before any race begins. To equalise opportunity completely, one would have to neutralise the family's effects, and that we are not prepared to do; we want both the fair start and the freedom of parents to favour their own. The modest ideal, pursued in earnest, collides with an attachment we will not give up, and we generally resolve the collision by not pursuing it in earnest.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The phrase 'the family, which we will not abolish' does which of the following in the argument?", format: "single_best", options: ["it sites the decisive obstacle in an institution we refuse to disturb, not in a law we could amend", "it implies that abolishing the family would in fact be the rational course, were we only honest and resolute enough to carry the ideal through to its logical end", "it identifies the family as the sole cause of every inequality between one person's starting point and another's", "it concedes that the law, unlike the family, has already done all it can to equalise opportunity"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: the passage contrasts 'the law, which can be changed' with 'the family, which we will not abolish', placing the real obstacle in what we decline to touch. B is the trap, reading the passage as quietly recommending abolition, where it treats the family as a value we rightly keep. C overstates 'chief source' into sole cause; D misreads the law-family contrast as a verdict that the law has exhausted its remedies.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-148", genre: "dialectic", skill: "argument", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s30", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity sounds like the least radical of ideals: not that all should end equal, only that all should start fair, the race open to talent regardless of birth. But the ideal, taken to its root, turns out to ask for more than we will give. The chief source of unequal starts is not the law, which can be changed, but the family, which we will not abolish: loving parents read to their children, pass on their advantages, their confidence, their connections, and in doing so make the starting line uneven before any race begins. To equalise opportunity completely, one would have to neutralise the family's effects, and that we are not prepared to do; we want both the fair start and the freedom of parents to favour their own. The modest ideal, pursued in earnest, collides with an attachment we will not give up, and we generally resolve the collision by not pursuing it in earnest.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "Which one, if true, would most weaken the dilemma the passage presses?", format: "single_best", options: ["in practice many parents do rather little to pass on advantages, so the family's effect on the starting line is small", "the head start families give could be matched by public provision for other children, so the fair start need not require touching the family at all", "some of what parents pass on, such as steady character, is advantage no one would wish to equalise away", "equality of outcome is every bit as unreachable as equality of opportunity, so the passage has merely shown that no egalitarian ideal whatever can survive contact with the world as it actually is"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: the dilemma is that fairness seems to require neutralising the family's effects, which we will not do; if those effects can instead be offset by lifting others up, the fair start no longer demands abolishing the family and the collision dissolves. A only shrinks the effect without denying the structure. C in fact reinforces the passage's tension; D is a sweeping change of subject to equality of outcome.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-149", genre: "dialectic", skill: "vocab_in_context", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s30", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity sounds like the least radical of ideals: not that all should end equal, only that all should start fair, the race open to talent regardless of birth. But the ideal, taken to its root, turns out to ask for more than we will give. The chief source of unequal starts is not the law, which can be changed, but the family, which we will not abolish: loving parents read to their children, pass on their advantages, their confidence, their connections, and in doing so make the starting line uneven before any race begins. To equalise opportunity completely, one would have to neutralise the family's effects, and that we are not prepared to do; we want both the fair start and the freedom of parents to favour their own. The modest ideal, pursued in earnest, collides with an attachment we will not give up, and we generally resolve the collision by not pursuing it in earnest.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "In 'neutralise the family's effects', 'neutralise' is closest in meaning to", format: "single_best", options: ["cancel out", "render harmless", "stay impartial toward", "openly denounce"], answer: 0, explanation: "A: to neutralise the family's effects is to cancel them out, offsetting them to zero so they no longer tilt the starting line. B is the trap, the threat-defusing sense of neutralise, but the effects here are advantages to be equalised, not dangers to be defused. C leans on 'neutral' as impartial; D imports a condemnation the word does not carry.", difficulty: "hard", source: "original" },
  { id: "gs1-dialectic-150", genre: "dialectic", skill: "inference", stimulusId: "gs1-dialectic-s30", stimulus: { kind: "text", content: "Equality of opportunity sounds like the least radical of ideals: not that all should end equal, only that all should start fair, the race open to talent regardless of birth. But the ideal, taken to its root, turns out to ask for more than we will give. The chief source of unequal starts is not the law, which can be changed, but the family, which we will not abolish: loving parents read to their children, pass on their advantages, their confidence, their connections, and in doing so make the starting line uneven before any race begins. To equalise opportunity completely, one would have to neutralise the family's effects, and that we are not prepared to do; we want both the fair start and the freedom of parents to favour their own. The modest ideal, pursued in earnest, collides with an attachment we will not give up, and we generally resolve the collision by not pursuing it in earnest.", attribution: "Original passage" }, stem: "The closing sentence, that 'we generally resolve the collision by not pursuing it in earnest', implies that our commitment to equality of opportunity is", format: "single_best", options: ["a settled fiction we have privately abandoned while continuing to praise it in public", "real but unserious, professed sincerely yet held only on terms that stop short of what it would actually demand", "secure, since we have found a workable balance between the fair start and the freedom of families", "steadily eroding, as each generation's inherited advantages compound and push the ideal further out of any practical reach than the one before it"], answer: 1, explanation: "B: we neither drop the ideal nor pursue it to its demanding end; we hold it 'only by not pursuing it in earnest', a sincere but unserious commitment. A overshoots into cynical pretence, an ideal secretly abandoned, which the 'modest ideal' language resists. C reads the half-measure as a solved balance; D rewrites the point as a gradual empirical erosion through compounding wealth, the obstacle the passage explicitly relocates away from.", difficulty: "very_hard", source: "original" },
];

